{"title_page": "Milton Bradley (baseball)", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{other uses|Milton Bradley (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name          = Milton Bradley\n| image         = Milton Bradley, 2008 All-Star.jpg\n| caption       = Bradley at the 2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game\n| position      = [[Outfielder]]\n| bats          = Switch\n| throws        = Right\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1978|4|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Harbor City, California]]\n| debutleague   = MLB\n| debutdate     = July 19\n| debutyear     = 2000\n| debutteam     = Montreal Expos\n| finalleague   = MLB\n| finaldate     = May 8\n| finalyear     = 2011\n| finalteam     = Seattle Mariners\n| statleague    = MLB\n| stat1label    = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value    = .271\n| stat2label    = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value    = 125\n| stat3label    = [[Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value    = 481\n| teams         = \n* [[Montreal Expos]] ({{mlby|2000}}\u2013{{mlby|2001}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|2001}}\u2013{{mlby|2003}})\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2004}}\u2013{{mlby|2005}})\n* [[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|2006}}\u2013{{mlby|2007}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2007}})\n* [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2009}})\n* [[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2011}})\n| awards        = \n* [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2008]])\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{flagu|United States}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan American Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1999 Pan American Games|1999 Winnipeg]] | [[Baseball at the 1999 Pan American Games|Team]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Milton Obelle Bradley, Jr.''' (born April 15, 1978) is an American retired professional [[baseball]] [[outfielder]]. Standing {{convert|6|ft|m}} and weighing {{convert|215|lb|kg}}, Bradley was a [[switch hitter]] who threw right-handed. During an 11-year career in [[Major League Baseball]], Bradley played with the [[Montreal Expos]] (2000\u201301), [[Cleveland Indians]] (2001\u201303), [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] (2004\u201305), [[Oakland Athletics]] (2006\u201307), [[San Diego Padres]] (2007), [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] (2008), [[Chicago Cubs]] (2009), and [[Seattle Mariners]] (2010\u201311). His career was also marred by legal troubles and several notable on-field incidents.\n\nBorn in [[Harbor City, California]], Bradley attended [[Long Beach Polytechnic High School]] before he was drafted by the Expos in the [[1996 Major League Baseball draft]]. After playing four seasons of [[minor league baseball]] for the organization, he made his major league debut on July 19, 2000. In 2001, Bradley was traded to the Cleveland Indians in exchange for pitching [[prospect (sports)|prospect]] [[Zach Day]]; he was again traded in 2004 to the Los Angeles Dodgers. After playing in 216 games for the Dodgers, the most among all teams he has played for, Bradley was traded to the Oakland Athletics for [[Andre Ethier]]. Bradley was traded to the Padres in 2007, was granted [[free agent|free agency]] after one season with the team, and signed with the Texas Rangers in 2007. He was voted to the 2008 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game]] with the Rangers, and led the American League with a .436 [[on-base percentage]] and a .999 [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage. For the year, Bradley finished 17th in American League [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] voting.\n\nAfter becoming a free agent, Bradley signed with the Chicago Cubs in January 2009, who traded him in December of that year to the Seattle Mariners. In Seattle, Bradley batted .205 in 2010 and .218 in 2011 before he was released by the club. He has a career [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] of .271 with 135 [[home run]]s and 481 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) in 1,042 games played, and was described as having \"power, speed, a strong arm and star qualities\", although \"his temper \u2026 has never allowed him to fulfill his immense potential.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley All Smiles While Playing Cleveland |agency=[[Associated Press]] |last=Withers |first=Tom |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106731484.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224235446/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106731484.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2016 |date=March 25, 2005|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bradley was convicted by a jury of nine counts of physically attacking and threatening his wife including four counts of spousal battery, two counts of criminal threats, one count of assault with a deadly weapon, one count of vandalism and one count of brandishing a deadly weapon, and was sentenced to 32 months in prison.\n\n==Early life==\nBradley was born on April 15, 1978, in Harbor City, California. His mother, Charlena Rector, worked as a clerk at a local [[Safeway Inc.|Safeway]] supermarket,<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1574709&type=story |last=Schwarz |first=Alan |title=Bradley knows only one way \u2014 the hard way |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011 |date=July 9, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"Ealy_Life_2\">{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espnmag/story?id=3747583 |title=Milton Bradley knows you think he'll explode. He's out to prove you wrong |newspaper=[[ESPN The Magazine]] |last=Keown |first=Tim |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> while his father, Milton Bradley Sr., was a veteran of the [[Vietnam War]], and was awarded a [[Purple Heart]] for his service.<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\" /> Bradley was named Milton Bradley Jr. when Milton Bradley Sr. filled out his son's birth certificate without Rector's permission.<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\" /> According to Bradley Jr.'s mother, Bradley Sr. was addicted to [[cocaine]], physically abused her, and was homeless for several years.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> Growing up, Bradley had four half-siblings from Rector's previous marriage.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |title=Two Texas All-Stars Check Their Extra Baggage |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/13/sports/baseball/13spotlight.html?pagewanted=all |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |last=Schwarz |first=Alan |date=July 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBradley played baseball at Long Beach Polytechnic High School, and was a teammate of [[Chase Utley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=In Chase Utley's case, a star was formed |date=October 31, 2009 |last1=Baxter |first1=Kevin |last2=Bolch |first2=Ben |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/31/sports/sp-world-series31 |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> After graduating high school with a 3.7 [[Grade point average#United States|grade point average]],<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_2\" /> he committed to [[California State University, Long Beach]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Baseball in Long Beach |last=Meigs |first=Tom |page=97 |year=2008 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |isbn=978-0-7385-5823-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=404elIgZwbAC}}</ref> but instead signed with the Expos on July 1, 1996 after being drafted by the team in the second round of the 1996 Major League Baseball draft.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Major League Baseball career==\n\n===Montreal Expos (1996\u20132001)===\nBradley began his professional baseball career with the [[GCL Expos]] of the [[Gulf Coast League]] in 1996; in 32 games, he batted .241 with 27 [[hit (baseball)|hits]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=1e899210 |title=1996 GCL Expos |work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> The following season, he played nine games for the GCL Expos and 50 for the [[Vermont Expos]], a [[short season]] affiliate of the Montreal Expos. For the Expos, he was named to the postseason [[New York\u2013Penn League]] All-Star team.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\">{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley |work=MLB.com |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=150396#gameType=%27R%27&sectionType=career&statType=1&season=2012&level=%27ALL%27 |accessdate=May 5, 2012}} Note: Click \"Bio\" for more information</ref> In 1998, he played for the [[Cape Fear Crocs]] and the [[Jupiter Hammerheads]], tying for the Croc team lead in [[double (baseball)|doubles]] with 21 while hitting .302 for the Crocs and .287 for the Hammerheads.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=ebc8a460 |title=1998 Cape Fear Crocs |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=7e1e3456 |title=1998 Jupiter Hammerheads |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> While playing for the [[Harrisburg Senators]] the next season, he was suspended seven games for starting a fight after he had been hit by a pitch.<ref>{{cite web |title=Expos unload Bradley, Urbina |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2001/07/31/expos010731.html |date=August 1, 2001 |work=[[CBC.ca]] |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> He also played for the silver-medal-winning United States in the [[1999 Pan American Games]].<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\n\nFinishing 76\u201366, the Senators played the [[Norwich Navigators]] for the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] championship. The series was tied two games to two in a best-of-five series. In the final game, Bradley hit a [[Walk-off home run|walk-off]] [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] with two outs and a [[full count]], in the bottom of the ninth inning, to give the Senators a 12\u201311 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Harrisburg, Tribe's Bradley was once a Hero, Outfielder's Dramatic Grand Slam Brought Senators their 4th Consecutive Eastern League Championship |newspaper=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |page=D4 |date=May 26, 2002 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AK&s_site=ohio&p_multi=AK&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F3D7FE9A1378663&p_field_direct-0=document_id |accessdate=January 29, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During the next season, after playing in 88 games for the [[Ottawa Lynx]], he was promoted to the major league club and made his MLB debut on July 19, 2000. In his debut, he hit three straight [[single (baseball)|singles]] against the [[New York Mets]];<ref>{{cite news |title=Mets rally past Expos |newspaper=[[Record-Journal]] |publisher=The White Family |page=12 |date=July 20, 2000 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4f1IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ugINAAAAIBAJ&pg=2568,2880117 |accessdate=January 30, 2012}}</ref> and for the season, he batted .221 with 15 RBI over 42 games played.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nFor the 2001 Expos, Bradley played 67 games, including one on April 26 in which he [[base on balls|walked]] to give the Expos the [[Glossary of baseball (G)#go-ahead run|go-ahead run]] against [[Rick Ankiel]] of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] in the top of the 15th inning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2001/B04260SLN2001.htm |title=Montreal Expos 4, St. Louis Cardinals 3 |publisher=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=February 2, 2012}}</ref> On July 31 of that year, he was traded to the Cleveland Indians to serve as a possible replacement for [[Kenny Lofton]]; in exchange, the Expos received right-handed pitcher Zach Day.<ref name=\"Quote_Trade\" /> Speaking to the [[Associated Press]] about the trade, Indians [[General Manager]] [[John Hart (baseball)|John Hart]] stated:\n\n{{quote|In Milton Bradley we are getting a top-of-the-order, middle-of-the-diamond player we feel will have a major impact at the major-league level in the near future.<ref name=\"Quote_Trade\">{{cite news |title=Indians get center fielder |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |date=August 1, 2001 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SYkNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fHADAAAAIBAJ&pg=5714,143990 |accessdate=February 3, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n===Cleveland Indians (2001\u20132003)===\n[[File:M.bradley2003.jpg|thumb|right|Bradley as a Cleveland Indian]]\nAfter the deal, Bradley was assigned to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Buffalo Bisons]] and reported to the team on August 2.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley Impresses Tribe Exec |newspaper=[[The Buffalo News]] |date=August 5, 2001 |last=Harrington |first=Mike |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EDBF384B4C3451B&p_field_direct-0=document_id|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In addition to the 30 games he played for the Bisons, he also played 10 games for the major league Indians.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn April 15, 2002, he was placed on the [[disabled list]] (DL) following an [[appendectomy]] a day earlier at [[St. Anthony's Hospital (St. Petersburg, Florida)|St. Anthony's Hospital]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley has appendectomy |date=April 15, 2002 |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-08-15/sports/0208150246_1_appendectomy-babe-ruth-world-series-hyde-park |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> He went on the disabled list again on May 2 with a broken [[orbit (anatomy)|orbital bone]]<ref name=\"Eye\">{{cite news |title=American League notes |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=May 29, 2002 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/121890946.html?dids=121890946:121890946&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |page=C4 |accessdate=February 4, 2012 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> and a scratched [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]]<ref name=\"AP\" /> after a batted ball had bounced off the outfield wall and hit him below his left eye while he was trying to make a catch; up to that point, he was hitting .266 in 23 games.<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite web |title=Indians' Bradley out indefinitely with fracture near left eye |date=May 2, 2002 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |publisher=[[CNN]] |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/news/2002/05/02/indians_bradley_ap/ |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> After a rehabilitation stint of six games with the Bisons, he was reactivated by the Indians on June 4<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news |title=Indians activate Bradley from DL |date=June 5, 2002 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and finished the season with a .249 batting average, 38 RBIs and nine home runs.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nBradley spent the 2003 campaign with the Indians. Despite being placed on the 15-day DL with a strained right hamstring and missing the final six weeks of the season with a lower back injury, he led the team in [[stolen base]]s, with 17.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20030426&content_id=291178&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=null |title=Tribe notes: Bradley goes on DL Jody Gerut makes Major League Debut |last=Esper |first=Damin |work=[[MLB.com]] |publisher=[[Major League Baseball Advanced Media]] |date=April 26, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sign_\" /> On August 30, while on the DL with a back injury, he was ticketed for speeding in [[Cuyahoga Falls, Ohio]]. After being stopped, he refused the ticket and sped away.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1614567 |title=Outfielder charged with fleeing after pullover |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=September 12, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> He pleaded not guilty to speeding and fleeing charges on September 12, but was sentenced to a three-day jail term. The ruling was upheld by the [[Supreme Court of Ohio]] in December 2004.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=USA Today |title=Bradley begins serving three-day jail sentence |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/2004-12-15-legal-roundup_x.htm |date=December 15, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2003 he signed a one-year, $1.73 million contract with the Indians in order for the Indians to avoid [[salary arbitration]] with him.<ref name=\"Sign_\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1665715 |title=Bradley agrees to one-year deal |date=November 19, 2003 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> During [[spring training]], he was banned from the Indians' training camp after not running out a [[batted ball|popup]] a game earlier.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cleveland tires of Milton Bradley's games, plans trade |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=b30xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s6IFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6324,892959 |newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]] |date=April 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> On April 3, 2004, he was traded to the Dodgers for [[Franklin Guti\u00e9rrez]] and a player to be named later ([[Andrew Brown (pitcher)|Andrew Brown]]); the ''[[Akron Beacon Journal]]'' later reported that manager [[Eric Wedge]] had insisted that Bradley be traded.<ref>{{cite news |title=Talkin' Tribe |page=C4 |newspaper=Akron Beacon Journal |date=April 4, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Dodgers (2004\u20132005)===\n{{Quote box\n |quote=When we traded for Milton, I think we knew everything that came along with it. We knew the past, we don't necessarily think that everything's going to be completely different because he came to a different place. That's fine. I would take nine Milton Bradleys if I could get them.\n |source = \u2014 Dodgers [[general manager]] [[Paul DePodesta]]<ref name=\"Quote\" />\n |width  = 30em\n |align  = right\n |style=clear:none;max-width:50%\n}}\n\nIn his first game with the Dodgers, playing [[Center fielder|center field]], Bradley went 2-for-3, with two singles and two walks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=240405119 |title=Lawrence stingy, Nevin grand for San Diego |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=April 5, 2004 |accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref> On June 1, he was ejected from a game by home plate umpire [[Terry Craft]] for arguing over [[Strike zone|balls and strikes]]. After being restrained by manager [[Jim Tracy (baseball)|Jim Tracy]], he returned to the dugout and threw a ball bag onto the field.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley really, really upset |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/dodgers/2004-06-02-bradley-ejection-tantrum_x.htm |newspaper=USA Today |date=June 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> Bradley was suspended for four games and Tracy for one game.<ref name=\"Quote\">{{cite web |title=Outfielder also fined; Tracy suspended 1 game |date=June 4, 2004 |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1815331 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> On September 19, he hit a 479-foot home run against the [[Colorado Rockies]] in [[Coors Field]].<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" /> On September 28, during a home game against the Rockies, Bradley mishandled a [[line drive]] and was charged with an [[error (baseball)|error]]. A fan threw a bottle at Bradley, who left his position in right field, picked up the bottle and threw it into the stands, yelling at the fan. Bradley was immediately ejected from the game. The next day, MLB suspended him for the remainder of the season and fined him an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bradley also fined for tossing the bottle into stands |date=September 30, 2004 |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1891679 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> In postseason play, he hit .273 with a home run while the Dodgers lost the [[National League Division Series]] to the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] three games to one.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2004_NLDS1.shtml |title=2004 League Division Series |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> He finished the 2004 season batting .267 with 19 home runs and 67 RBIs, but was [[caught stealing]] 11 times, tying for eighth most in MLB.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2004-batting-leaders.shtml |title=2004 Major League Baseball Batting Leaders |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the offseason, Bradley went through [[anger management]] counseling.<ref>{{cite news |title=Milton Bradley Looks to Be a Role Model |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106202774.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172237/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106202774.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |agency=Associated Press |date=March 9, 2005 |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In a game against the [[San Francisco Giants]] on April 12, 2005, he drove in two runs with a single to tie the game in the bottom of the ninth inning with two outs, the winning run then scoring on [[Jason Ellison]]'s error in the same play.<ref>{{cite news |title=This is Just the Start |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131473440.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924125825/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131473440.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |date=April 13, 2005 |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Los Angeles Dodgers 9, San Francisco Giants 8 |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2005/B04120LAN2005.htm |publisher=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=June 17, 2012}}</ref> On August 25, 2005, after hitting .290 with 38 RBIs in 75 games, he was put on the 15-day DL with a torn [[patellar tendon]] and [[anterior cruciate ligament]] which rendered him inactive for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dodgers place Milton Bradley on disabled list |date=August 25, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=2143154 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> On December 13, 2005, the Dodgers traded him to the Oakland Athletics along with [[infielder]] [[Antonio P\u00e9rez (baseball)|Antonio P\u00e9rez]] for outfielder prospect [[Andre Ethier]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20051213&content_id=1281508&vkey=hotstove2005&fext=.jsp&affiliateId=CommentWidget |title=A's get Bradley, Perez in deal with LA |last=Urban |first=Mychael |work=MLB.com |date=December 23, 2005 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Oakland Athletics (2006\u20132007)===\nIn his first season with the Oakland Athletics, Bradley posted a .276 batting average with 14 home runs and 52 [[runs batted in]], in a part-time role. He went on the 15-day DL on May 11, 2006 for a strained oblique muscle and a sprained right knee.<ref>{{cite news |title=AL Notes: Athletics activate Bradley, Witasick |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/default/article/AL-Notes-Athletics-activate-Bradley-Witasick-1205506.php |date=June 6, 2006 |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> On July 30, he hit a three-run walk-off home run to beat the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] with two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley calls the winning shot: The often maligned outfielder's ninth-inning blast bails out Street for the A's sixth walk-off win of the year |last=Roderick |first=Joe |newspaper=[[Contra Costa Times]] |publisher=[[MediaNews Group]] |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-148863240.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610220631/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-148863240.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 10, 2014 |date=July 31, 2006 |accessdate=May 3, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During game four of the [[2006 American League Championship Series]] versus the [[Detroit Tigers]], Bradley became the third player in MLB history to hit home runs from each side of the plate in a postseason game, joining [[Bernie Williams]] and [[Chipper Jones]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20061011&content_id=1708819&vkey=news_oak&fext=.jsp&c_id=oak |title=Bradley's historic game can't boost A's |work=MLB.com |date=October 12, 2006 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> For the series, he went nine-for-eighteen with two home runs and five RBIs.<ref name=\"Rangers\">{{cite web |title=Rangers finalize one-year contract with Bradley |url=http://texas.rangers.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20071213&content_id=2324580&vkey=pr_tex&fext=.jsp&c_id=tex |work=MLB.com |date=December 17, 2007 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2007, the Athletics [[designated for assignment|designated him for assignment]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Urban |first=Mychael |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070621&content_id=2040883&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=A's designate Bradley for assignment |work=MLB.com |date=June 21, 2007 |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> A trade completed the next day, which would have sent Bradley to the [[Kansas City Royals]] for [[Leo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], was voided by the Royals because he had sustained an oblique injury in his last game as an Athletic.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kaegel |first=Dick |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070622&content_id=2043699&vkey=news_oak&fext=.jsp&c_id=oak |title=Bradley-to-Royals deal voided |work=MLB.com |date=June 22, 2007 |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref> He was then traded to the San Diego Padres on June 29, with cash, in exchange for Andrew Brown; it was the second time those two players had been traded for each other.\n\n===San Diego Padres (2007)===\n{{multiple image\n| footer=Bradley with the Padres, broke his bat over his knee after striking out on August 28, 2007.\n| align=left\n| image1=Milton Bradley breaking the bat over his knee after striking out.jpg\n| alt1=Milton Bradley before\n| width1=144\n| image2=Milton Bradley broke the bat over his knee after striking out.jpg\n| alt2=Milton Bradley after\n| width2=150\n}}\nBradley started his tenure with the Padres on the 15-day DL, but came off it on July 7; in July, he batted .364 with four home runs and 12 RBI in 18 games.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\nOn September 23, 2007, however, he tore his right [[anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] while being restrained by Padres manager [[Bud Black]] during an altercation with [[first base]] [[Umpire (baseball)|umpire]] [[Mike Winters]].<ref name=\"Padres\">{{cite news |title=Padres' Bradley tears ACL in fracas\u2013 Injury ends his season; blowup starts in dispute over outfielder's ejection |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-21794923.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924190543/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-21794923.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Commercial Appeal]] |date=September 25, 2007 |last=Wilson |first=Bernie |accessdate=June 19, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Home plate]] umpire [[Brian Runge]] reportedly told Bradley that Winters said that he had tossed his bat in Runge's direction in a previous [[at-bat]].<ref name=\"Padres\" /> After Bradley reached first base, he questioned Winters about the alleged bat throwing and subsequent communication with Runge. According to Bradley and Padres first base coach [[Bobby Meacham]], Winters addressed Bradley with a barrage of profanity.<ref name=\"Padres\" /> Bradley then moved towards Winters. While restrained by Black, Bradley fell to the ground and injured himself. He missed the final week of the regular season in 2007, during which the Padres lost to the [[Colorado Rockies]] in a [[2007 National League Wild Card tie-breaker game|one game playoff]] for the [[Major League Baseball wild card|National League wild card]] on October 1.<ref>{{cite news |title=Going Low, Standing Tall; Rockies' 3-Run Rally in 13th Inning Stuns Padres, Secures NL Wild Card |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7637760.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924200233/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7637760.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=October 2, 2007 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Crandall |first=Kate |accessdate=June 19, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nWinters was suspended for the remainder of the season and also spent the postseason on the restricted list for the incident, after MLB determined that he had indeed directed obscene language toward Bradley. Bradley was not suspended, MLB finding no need for such discipline since he did not make physical contact with Winters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3050020 |title=Pads' Bradley fined, not suspended in blow-up with umpire |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=October 5, 2007 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Texas Rangers (2008)===\nAfter the 2007 season, Bradley agreed to a one-year contract with the Texas Rangers. He announced in early January 2008 that he expected to be healthy and ready to play in the season opener.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3160349 |title=Rehabbing torn ACL, Bradley plans to play in Rangers' opener |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=December 18, 2007 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs the Rangers [[designated hitter]], he led the AL in on-base plus slugging with a .999 mark. He was third in batting average (.321), and led the league in [[on-base percentage]] (.443). On making the All-Star game, he stated, \"If I somehow miraculously made it to the All-Star Game, I would be floored. I'd really be totally humbled by that. I'm just happy right now to play, to produce and to be with a good group of guys.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/stories/060608dnspocowlishaw.3022001.html?npc |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519222902/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/stories/060608dnspocowlishaw.3022001.html?npc |archivedate=May 19, 2009 |title=Star glows, ballots grow for Texas Rangers' Bradley |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |last=Cowlishaw |first=Tim |date=June 6, 2008 |accessdate=January 4, 2009}}</ref> He was selected to play in his first All-Star Game in 2008 as a designated hitter (DH) after being officially selected as a DH reserve, but due to an injury to [[David Ortiz]] he became the starting DH in the [[2008 MLB All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite news |title=All-Star Game starting lineups |date=July 15, 2008 |newspaper=The Buffalo News}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' Bradley attempted to confront [[Kansas City Royals]] television announcer [[Ryan Lefebvre]] in the [[press box]] following a June 2008 game for what he believed were unfair comments made on the air. As the Rangers' designated hitter, Bradley watched the broadcast when he was not batting and took offense to a comparison Lefebvre made between him and [[Josh Hamilton]].<ref name=\"BQuote\" /> Manager [[Ron Washington]] and [[general manager]] [[Jon Daniels]] chased after him and stopped him before he got to Lefebvre, at which point he returned to the clubhouse in tears and said:\n\n{{quote|All I want to do is play baseball and make a better life for my kid than I had, that's it. I love all you guys. \u2026 I'm strong, but I'm not that strong.<ref name=\"BQuote\" />}}\n\nHe was quoted by Rangers radio broadcasters as saying that he never intended to physically harm Lefebvre but did want to speak to him; Daniels said he was upset that someone he didn't know was judging him.<ref name=\"BQuote\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/baseball/rangers/stories/061208dnsporangersbradley.3c7e26f.html |title=Texas Rangers' Bradley gets emotional over TV comments |newspaper=The Dallas Morning News |last=Durrett |first=Richard |date=June 12, 2008 |accessdate=January 4, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614234953/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/baseball/rangers/stories/061208dnsporangersbradley.3c7e26f.html |archivedate=June 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Cubs (2009)===\nOn January 8, 2009, Bradley signed a three-year, $30 million deal with the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Carrie |last=Muskat |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090108&content_id=3736641&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc |title='Blessed' Bradley signs with Cubs |work=MLB.com |date=January 8, 2009 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref> He was issued a two-game suspension for supposedly making contact with umpire [[Larry Vanover]] while arguing a strike call on April 16, which was reduced to one game on appeal.<ref>{{cite web |first=Carrie |last=Muskat |title=Bradley's suspension reduced |date=May 14, 2009 |work=MLB.com |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090514&content_id=4730876&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> During an interleague game against the [[Minnesota Twins]] on June 12, he caught a routine fly in right field and threw it into the stands, believing it was the third out of the inning when there were only two outs.<ref name='bradley-twins' /> The umpire allowed each of the Twins' baserunners to advance two bases as a result.<ref name='bradley-twins'>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/chi-13-cubs-twins-chicago-jun13,0,3738172.story |last=van Dyck |first=Dave |title=Chicago Cubs fall 7\u20134 to Minnesota Twins |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=June 13, 2009 |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nLater that month, Cub manager [[Lou Piniella]] told Bradley to leave the dugout and go home after he \"went after\" a [[Gatorade]] cooler in frustration after flying out in another interleague game, against the [[Chicago White Sox]]. Piniella and Bradley later confronted each other in the locker room and exchanged words.<ref name='bradley-lou'>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Seligman |title=Soto homer lifts Cubs over White Sox |date=June 27, 2009 |agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-D992M73G0.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924041611/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-D992M73G0.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |accessdate=June 27, 2009|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Piniella later apologized to Bradley, and reinserted him back into the line-up during the team's next start.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bradley: 'I don't have problem with Lou' |date=June 28, 2009 |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/news/story?id=4291786 |work=ESPN |accessdate=July 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 2009, the Cubs announced that Bradley would be suspended for the remainder of the season after an interview in which Bradley talked about \"negativity\" on the part of the Cub organization and declared, \"You understand why they [the Cubs] haven't won in 100 years here.\" He also said he was uncomfortable just being on the Cubs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/mlb/news/story?id=4490125 |title=Chicago Cubs suspend Milton Bradley for the rest of the season |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=September 27, 2009}}</ref> General Manager [[Jim Hendry]] felt the comments were disrespectful.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Paul |title=Bradley suspended for rest of season |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=September 20, 2009 |url=http://blogs.chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports_hardball/2009/09/bradley-not-with-cubs-hendry-will-address-team.html |accessdate=September 20, 2009}}</ref> Bradley later apologized to the Cubs organization for his remarks.<ref name=\"Bradley_apologize\">{{cite news |first=Rick |last=Morrissey |title=Here's a 'real' apology from Milton Bradley |date=September 25, 2009 |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-09-25/sports/0909250004_1_apology-milton-bradley-alfonso-soriano |accessdate=September 25, 2009}}</ref> For the Cubs, Bradley hit .257 with 12 home runs and 40 RBIs<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" /> before being traded to the Seattle Mariners for [[Carlos Silva]] and cash on December 18, 2009.<ref name='bradley-trade1'>{{cite news |first=Larry |last=Stone |title=Shocker: Mariners trade Carlos Silva for Milton Bradley |date=December 18, 2009 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/thehotstoneleague/2010540975_shocker_mariners_trading_carlo.html |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=May 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Seattle Mariners (2010\u20132011)===\n[[File:Milton Bradley speaks to the ump.jpg|thumb|right|Bradley speaking to umpire [[Joe West (umpire)|Joe West]]]]\nBradley was part of a flurry of offseason moves by the Mariners in hopes of returning to the playoffs, having not reached the postseason since 2001.<ref name=\"Cubs trade Bradley\">{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091218&content_id=7828862&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc&partnerId=rss_chc |title=Cubs trade Bradley for Silva, cash |last=Muskat |first=Carrie |work=MLB.com |accessdate=18 December 2009}}</ref> On May 4, 2010, he removed himself from a game and left the stadium. He asked the Mariners for help with a personal problem, and the organization responded. He was placed on the restricted list, and returned to the team on May 18 after undergoing treatment of an undisclosed nature.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2010/05/troubled-milton-bradley-placed-on-mariners-restricted-list/1 |title=Troubled Milton Bradley placed on Mariners' restricted list |newspaper=USA Today |last=Nightengale |first=Bob |date=May 6, 2010 |accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> He ended the season on the DL after having been placed on it on July 31 prior to right knee [[arthroscopic]] surgery on August 17. He finished the 2010 season batting .205, with eight home runs and 29 RBIs over 73 games played.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\n\nOn May 9, 2011, the Mariners designated Bradley for assignment after starting the 2011 season hitting .218 with two home runs and 13 RBI in 28 games. Reportedly, the Mariners lost patience with Bradley due to his performance in a series against the White Sox. In the first game, he was ejected for arguing balls and strikes in the eighth inning, preventing the Mariners from putting in a pinch-runner due to not having enough available players. In the second game, he was booed for not hustling after several balls hit his way. In the final game, he made a poor throw that led to two White Sox runs.<ref name=\"nwsource1\">{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2015005893_mari10.html |title=Mariners cut ties with Milton Bradley |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=May 9, 2011 |accessdate=May 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514005616/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2015005893_mari10.html |archivedate=May 14, 2011}}</ref> Unable to trade Bradley, the Mariners released him on May 16.<ref name=\"nwsource1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2005, Bradley was the Dodgers' nominee for the [[Roberto Clemente Award]] for working with the Dodgers Dream Foundation, [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]], and the Long Beach [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Clubs]], among other charities. Bradley has also opened two baseball academies, one in Long Beach and another in [[Baldwin Hills, Los Angeles|Baldwin Hills]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Milton Bradley |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308082647/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/components/official_info/community/clemente_2005/bios/bradley_milton.jsp |archivedate=March 8, 2009 |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/components/official_info/community/clemente_2005/bios/bradley_milton.jsp |work=MLB.com |accessdate=May 6, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2005, [[Redondo Beach, California|Redondo Beach]] police received three domestic-violence-related calls from Bradley's house. No charges were filed.<ref>{{cite news |title=3 Domestic Calls to Bradley's Home |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-112655375.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172455/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-112655375.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=August 31, 2005 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 2006, Bradley filed for divorce but the petition was never finalized.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley, wife will meet for hearing; Mariners; Bradley, wife to meet in L.A. to determine if felony case proceeds |date=February 10, 2011 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-248777587.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152832/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-248777587.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |accessdate=June 18, 2012 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, Bradley was arrested at his home in [[Encino, California]] and charged with making criminal threats to his wife, Monique. When he agreed to participate in an out-of-court hearing process, no charges were filed against him. However, his wife subsequently filed for divorce.<ref name=\"nwsource1\" /><ref>Bradley was arrested in August 2011 for allegedly attacking Monique with a bat, and in March 2012 he allegedly threatened her with a knife and while yelling profanities. Monique filed a domestic violence report with the LAPD in November 2012 claiming Bradley tried to choke her, with two hands, when she asked him to stop smoking marijuana in front of their sons.\nOn January 10, 2013, Bradley was formerly charged by LAPD with 13 misdemeanor counts of assault with a deadly weapon, vandalism and dissuading a witness from making a report. {{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/milton-bradley-charged-la-domestic-193023686--mlb.html1 |title=Milton Bradley charged in LA with domestic abuse |agency=Associated Press |date=January 11, 2013 |accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Bradley was charged with several crimes stemming from five different domestic incidents which occurred in 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former MLB outfielder Milton Bradley charged with domestic abuse |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2013/01/11/milton-bradley-charged-in-la-with-domestic-abuse/1827619/ |accessdate=4 June 2017 |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 11, 2013 |language=en}}</ref> On June 3, 2013, Bradley was convicted by a jury of nine counts of physically attacking and threatening his wife including four counts of spousal battery, two counts of criminal threats, one count of assault with a deadly weapon, one count of vandalism and one count of brandishing a deadly weapon. On July 2, 2013, he was sentenced to 32 months in prison and 52 weeks of domestic violence and anger-management classes, and was released on $250,000 bail.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/04/08/milton-bradley-domestic-abuse-mlb-monique-bradley |title=The tragic extent of Monique and Milton Bradley's violent relationship |last=McKnight |first=Michael |date=13 April 2015 |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=15 April 2015}}</ref> Despite his convictions and sentence, Bradley maintained [[sole custody]] of his and Monique's two sons.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=A's Bradley Files for Divorce |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117252832.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172638/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117252832.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=January 12, 2006 |accessdate=June 18, 2012 |agency=Associated Press|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"AP_2013\">{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley charged in LA with domestic abuse |agency=Associated Press |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/milton-bradley-charged-la-domestic-abuse}}</ref>\n\nOn September 14, 2013, at the age of 33, Monique Bradley died<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ohio/obituary.aspx?pid=167158640#fbLoggedOut Monique Bradley Obituary - Akron, OH | Akron Beacon Journal<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> at [[Encino Hospital Medical Center]].<ref name=\":0\" /> A [[death certificate]] dated October 10 lists the causes as [[Cryptogenic disease|cryptogenic]] [[cirrhosis]] of the [[liver]], [[Shock (circulatory)|hemorrhagic shock]] and [[cardiac arrest]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn January 21, 2015, a Los Angeles [[appellate court]] rejected Bradley's appeal.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' reported in May 2015 that following another unsuccessful appeal, Bradley was ordered to begin serving the 32-month sentence for his 2013 convictions, with the hearing judge stating that Bradley's request for leniency was \"breathtaking, frankly, in how callous\" it was.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-MLB outfielder Milton Bradley to start serving 32-month jail sentence |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/05/15/milton-bradley-jail-domestic-abuse |work=Sports Illustrated |date=May 15, 2015 |accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref> In early 2016, Bradley's request to have his jail sentence reduced was denied by a Los Angeles Superior Court judge.<ref>{{cite web |title=Judge denies request by ex-MLB OF Milton Bradley for reduced jail time |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/01/07/milton-bradley-release-court-case |work=Sports Illustrated |date=January 7, 2016 |accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Bradley was charged with spousal battery and taken into custody on bail of $175,000 for allegedly assaulting his wife during a January 2018 incident, at which time Bradley was on probation for his earlier domestic violence conviction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-MLB outfielder Milton Bradley Charged With Spousal Battery |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2018/04/09/milton-bradley-domestic-violence-spousal-battery |work=Sports Illustrated |date=2018-04-09 |accessdate=2018-08-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley Handcuffed In Court at Domestic Violence Hearing |url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/04/10/milton-bradley-handcuffed-custody-battery-domestic-violence/ |work=TMZ |date=2018-04-10 |accessdate=2018-08-07}}</ref> In June 2018 Bradley pleaded no contest to domestic battery, was sentenced to 36 months of probation, and was required to complete 52 weeks of domestic violence counseling.<ref>{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley Convicted in Dom. Violence Case |url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/06/13/milton-bradley-domestic-violence-convicted/ |work=TMZ |date=2018-06-13 |accessdate=2018-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Milton Bradley}}\n{{commonscat|Milton Bradley (baseball)}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=150396 |espn=4245 |br=b/bradlmi01 |fangraphs=369 |brm=bradle001mil}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradley, Milton}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American baseball players]]\n[[Category:Akron Aeros players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1999 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Cape Fear Crocs players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Expos players]]\n[[Category:Harrisburg Senators players]]\n[[Category:Jupiter Hammerheads players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas 51s players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball outfielders]]\n[[Category:Montreal Expos players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Lynx players]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of battery]]\n[[Category:People from Harbor City, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sacramento River Cats players]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Stockton Ports players]]\n[[Category:Texas Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Vermont Expos players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{other uses|Milton Bradley (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name          = Milton Bradley\n| image         = Milton Bradley, 2008 All-Star.jpg\n| caption       = Bradley at the 2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game\n| position      = [[Outfielder]]\n| bats          = Switch\n| throws        = Right\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1978|4|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Harbor City, California]]\n| debutleague   = MLB\n| debutdate     = July 19\n| debutyear     = 2000\n| debutteam     = Montreal Expos\n| finalleague   = MLB\n| finaldate     = May 8\n| finalyear     = 2011\n| finalteam     = Seattle Mariners\n| statleague    = MLB\n| stat1label    = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value    = .271\n| stat2label    = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value    = 125\n| stat3label    = [[Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value    = 481\n| teams         = \n* [[Montreal Expos]] ({{mlby|2000}}\u2013{{mlby|2001}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|2001}}\u2013{{mlby|2003}})\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2004}}\u2013{{mlby|2005}})\n* [[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|2006}}\u2013{{mlby|2007}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2007}})\n* [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2009}})\n* [[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2011}})\n| awards        = \n* [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2008]])\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{flagu|United States}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan American Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1999 Pan American Games|1999 Winnipeg]] | [[Baseball at the 1999 Pan American Games|Team]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Milton Obelle Bradley, Jr.''' (born April 15, 1978) is an American retired professional [[baseball]] [[outfielder]]. Standing {{convert|6|ft|m}} and weighing {{convert|215|lb|kg}}, Bradley was a [[switch hitter]] who threw right-handed. During an 11-year career in [[Major League Baseball]], Bradley played with the [[Montreal Expos]] (2000\u201301), [[Cleveland Indians]] (2001\u201303), [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] (2004\u201305), [[Oakland Athletics]] (2006\u201307), [[San Diego Padres]] (2007), [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] (2008), [[Chicago Cubs]] (2009), and [[Seattle Mariners]] (2010\u201311). His career was also marred by legal troubles and several notable on-field incidents.\n\nBorn in [[Harbor City, California]], Bradley attended [[Long Beach Polytechnic High School]] before he was drafted by the Expos in the [[1996 Major League Baseball draft]]. After playing four seasons of [[minor league baseball]] for the organization, he made his major league debut on July 19, 2000. In 2001, Bradley was traded to the Cleveland Indians in exchange for pitching [[prospect (sports)|prospect]] [[Zach Day]]; he was again traded in 2004 to the Los Angeles Dodgers. After playing in 216 games for the Dodgers, the most among all teams he has played for, Bradley was traded to the Oakland Athletics for [[Andre Ethier]]. Bradley was traded to the Padres in 2007, was granted [[free agent|free agency]] after one season with the team, and signed with the Texas Rangers in 2007. He was voted to the 2008 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game]] with the Rangers, and led the American League with a .436 [[on-base percentage]] and a .999 [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage. For the year, Bradley finished 17th in American League [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] voting.\n\nAfter becoming a free agent, Bradley signed with the Chicago Cubs in January 2009, who traded him in December of that year to the Seattle Mariners. In Seattle, Bradley batted .205 in 2010 and .218 in 2011 before he was released by the club. He has a career [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] of .271 with 135 [[home run]]s and 481 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) in  1,042 games played, and was described as having \"power, speed, a strong arm and star qualities\", although \"his temper \u2026 has never allowed him to fulfill his immense potential.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley All Smiles While Playing Cleveland |agency=[[Associated Press]] |last=Withers |first=Tom |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106731484.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224235446/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106731484.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2016 |date=March 25, 2005|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bradley was convicted by a jury of nine counts of physically attacking and threatening his wife including four counts of spousal battery, two counts of criminal threats, one count of assault with a deadly weapon, one count of vandalism and one count of brandishing a deadly weapon, and was sentenced to 32 months in prison.\n\n==Early life==\nBradley was born on April 15, 1978, in Harbor City, California. His mother, Charlena Rector, worked as a clerk at a local [[Safeway Inc.|Safeway]] supermarket,<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1574709&type=story |last=Schwarz |first=Alan |title=Bradley knows only one way \u2014 the hard way |publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=January 28, 2011 |date=July 9, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"Ealy_Life_2\">{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espnmag/story?id=3747583 |title=Milton Bradley knows you think he'll explode. He's out to prove you wrong |newspaper=[[ESPN The Magazine]]|last=Keown |first=Tim |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> while his father, Milton Bradley Sr., was a veteran of the [[Vietnam War]], and was awarded a [[Purple Heart]] for his service.<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\" /> Bradley was named Milton Bradley Jr. when Milton Bradley Sr. filled out his son's birth certificate without Rector's permission.<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\" /> According to Bradley Jr.'s mother, Bradley Sr. was addicted to [[cocaine]], physically abused her, and was homeless for several years.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> Growing up, Bradley had four half-siblings from Rector's previous marriage.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |title=Two Texas All-Stars Check Their Extra Baggage |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/13/sports/baseball/13spotlight.html?pagewanted=all |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |last=Schwarz |first=Alan |date=July 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBradley played baseball at Long Beach Polytechnic High School, and was a teammate of [[Chase Utley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=In Chase Utley's case, a star was formed |date=October 31, 2009 |last1=Baxter |first1=Kevin |last2=Bolch |first2=Ben |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]  |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/31/sports/sp-world-series31 |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> After graduating high school with a 3.7 [[Grade point average#United States|grade point average]],<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_2\" /> he committed to [[California State University, Long Beach]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Baseball in Long Beach |last=Meigs |first=Tom |page=97 |year=2008 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |isbn=978-0-7385-5823-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=404elIgZwbAC}}</ref> but instead signed with the Expos on July 1, 1996 after being drafted by the team in the second round of the 1996 Major League Baseball draft.\n\n==Major League Baseball career==\n\n===Montreal Expos (1996\u20132001)===\nBradley began his professional baseball career with the [[GCL Expos]] of the [[Gulf Coast League]] in 1996; in 32 games, he batted .241 with 27 [[hit (baseball)|hits]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=1e899210 |title=1996 GCL Expos |work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> The following season, he played nine games for the GCL Expos and 50 for the [[Vermont Expos]], a [[short season]] affiliate of the Montreal Expos. For the Expos, he was named to the postseason [[New York\u2013Penn League]] All-Star team.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\">{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley |work=MLB.com |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=150396#gameType=%27R%27&sectionType=career&statType=1&season=2012&level=%27ALL%27 |accessdate=May 5, 2012}} Note: Click \"Bio\" for more information</ref> In 1998, he played for the [[Cape Fear Crocs]] and the [[Jupiter Hammerheads]], tying for the Croc team lead in [[double (baseball)|doubles]] with 21 while hitting .302 for the Crocs and .287 for the Hammerheads.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=ebc8a460 |title=1998 Cape Fear Crocs |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=7e1e3456 |title=1998 Jupiter Hammerheads |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> While playing for the [[Harrisburg Senators]] the next season, he was suspended seven games for starting a fight after he had been hit by a pitch.<ref>{{cite web |title=Expos unload Bradley, Urbina |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2001/07/31/expos010731.html |date=August 1, 2001 |work=[[CBC.ca]] |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> He also played for the silver-medal-winning United States in the [[1999 Pan American Games]].<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\n\nFinishing 76\u201366, the Senators played the [[Norwich Navigators]] for the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] championship. The series was tied two games to two in a best-of-five series. In the final game, Bradley hit a [[Walk-off home run|walk-off]] [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] with two outs and a [[full count]], in the bottom of the ninth inning, to give the Senators a 12\u201311 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Harrisburg, Tribe's Bradley was once a Hero, Outfielder's Dramatic Grand Slam Brought Senators their 4th Consecutive Eastern League Championship |newspaper=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |page=D4 |date=May 26, 2002 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AK&s_site=ohio&p_multi=AK&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F3D7FE9A1378663&p_field_direct-0=document_id |accessdate=January 29, 2012|url-access=subscription }}</ref> During the next season, after playing in 88 games for the [[Ottawa Lynx]], he was promoted to the major league club and made his MLB debut on July 19, 2000. In his debut, he hit three straight [[single (baseball)|singles]] against the [[New York Mets]];<ref>{{cite news |title=Mets rally past Expos |newspaper=[[Record-Journal]] |publisher=The White Family |page=12 |date=July 20, 2000 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4f1IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ugINAAAAIBAJ&pg=2568,2880117 |accessdate=January 30, 2012}}</ref> and for the season, he batted .221 with 15 RBI over 42 games played.\n\nFor the 2001 Expos, Bradley played 67 games, including one on April 26 in which he [[base on balls|walked]] to give the Expos the [[Glossary of baseball (G)#go-ahead run|go-ahead run]] against [[Rick Ankiel]] of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] in the top of the 15th inning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2001/B04260SLN2001.htm |title=Montreal Expos 4, St. Louis Cardinals 3 |publisher=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=February 2, 2012}}</ref> On July 31 of that year, he was traded to the Cleveland Indians to serve as a possible replacement for [[Kenny Lofton]]; in exchange, the Expos received right-handed pitcher Zach Day.<ref name=\"Quote_Trade\" /> Speaking to the [[Associated Press]] about the trade, Indians [[General Manager]] [[John Hart (baseball)|John Hart]] stated:\n\n{{quote|In Milton Bradley we are getting a top-of-the-order, middle-of-the-diamond player we feel will have a major impact at the major-league level in the near future.<ref name=\"Quote_Trade\">{{cite news |title=Indians get center fielder |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |date=August 1, 2001 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SYkNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fHADAAAAIBAJ&pg=5714,143990 |accessdate=February 3, 2012 }}</ref>}}\n\n===Cleveland Indians (2001\u20132003)===\n[[File:M.bradley2003.jpg|thumb|right|Bradley as a Cleveland Indian]]\nAfter the deal, Bradley was assigned to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Buffalo Bisons]] and reported to the team on August 2.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley Impresses Tribe Exec |newspaper=[[The Buffalo News]] |date=August 5, 2001 |last=Harrington |first=Mike |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EDBF384B4C3451B&p_field_direct-0=document_id|url-access=subscription }}</ref> In addition to the 30 games he played for the Bisons, he also played 10 games for the major league Indians.\n\nOn April 15, 2002, he was placed on the [[disabled list]] (DL) following an [[appendectomy]] a day earlier at [[St. Anthony's Hospital (St. Petersburg, Florida)|St. Anthony's Hospital]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley has appendectomy |date=April 15, 2002 |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-08-15/sports/0208150246_1_appendectomy-babe-ruth-world-series-hyde-park |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]  |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> He went on the disabled list again on May 2 with a broken [[orbit (anatomy)|orbital bone]]<ref name=\"Eye\">{{cite news |title=American League notes |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=May 29, 2002 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/121890946.html?dids=121890946:121890946&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |page=C4 |accessdate=February 4, 2012 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and a scratched [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]]<ref name=\"AP\" /> after a batted ball had bounced off the outfield wall and hit him below his left eye while he was trying to make a catch; up to that point, he was hitting .266 in 23 games.<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite web |title=Indians' Bradley out indefinitely with fracture near left eye |date=May 2, 2002 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |publisher=[[CNN]] |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/news/2002/05/02/indians_bradley_ap/ |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> After a rehabilitation stint of six games with the Bisons, he was reactivated by the Indians on June 4<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news |title=Indians activate Bradley from DL |date=June 5, 2002 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and finished the season with a .249 batting average, 38 RBIs and nine home runs.\n\nBradley spent the 2003 campaign with the Indians. Despite being placed on the 15-day DL with a strained right hamstring and missing the final six weeks of the season with a lower back injury, he led the team in [[stolen base]]s, with 17.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20030426&content_id=291178&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=null |title=Tribe notes: Bradley goes on DL Jody Gerut makes Major League Debut |last=Esper |first=Damin |work=[[MLB.com]] |publisher=[[Major League Baseball Advanced Media]] |date=April 26, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sign_\" /> On August 30, while on the DL with a back injury, he was ticketed for speeding in [[Cuyahoga Falls, Ohio]]. After being stopped, he refused the ticket and sped away.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1614567 |title=Outfielder charged with fleeing after pullover |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=September 12, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> He pleaded not guilty to speeding and fleeing charges on September 12, but was sentenced to a three-day jail term. The ruling was upheld by the [[Supreme Court of Ohio]] in December 2004.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=USA Today  |title=Bradley begins serving three-day jail sentence |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/2004-12-15-legal-roundup_x.htm |date=December 15, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2003 he signed a one-year, $1.73 million contract with the Indians in order for the Indians to avoid [[salary arbitration]] with him.<ref name=\"Sign_\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1665715 |title=Bradley agrees to one-year deal |date=November 19, 2003 |publisher=ESPN|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> During [[spring training]], he was banned from the Indians' training camp after not running out a [[batted ball|popup]] a game earlier.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cleveland tires of Milton Bradley's games, plans trade |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=b30xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s6IFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6324,892959 |newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]] |date=April 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> On April 3, 2004, he was traded to the Dodgers for [[Franklin Guti\u00e9rrez]] and a player to be named later ([[Andrew Brown (pitcher)|Andrew Brown]]); the ''[[Akron Beacon Journal]]'' later reported that manager [[Eric Wedge]] had insisted that Bradley be traded.<ref>{{cite news |title=Talkin' Tribe |page=C4 |newspaper=Akron Beacon Journal |date=April 4, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Dodgers (2004\u20132005)===\n{{Quote box\n |quote=When we traded for Milton, I think we knew everything that came along with it. We knew the past, we don't necessarily think that everything's going to be completely different because he came to a different place. That's fine. I would take nine Milton Bradleys if I could get them.\n |source = \u2014 Dodgers [[general manager]] [[Paul DePodesta]]<ref name=\"Quote\" />\n |width  = 30em\n |align  = right\n |style=clear:none;max-width:50%\n}}\n\nIn his first game with the Dodgers, playing [[Center fielder|center field]], Bradley went 2-for-3, with two singles and two walks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=240405119 |title=Lawrence stingy, Nevin grand for San Diego |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=April 5, 2004 |accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref> On June 1, he was ejected from a game by home plate umpire [[Terry Craft]] for arguing over [[Strike zone|balls and strikes]]. After being restrained by manager [[Jim Tracy (baseball)|Jim Tracy]], he returned to the dugout and threw a ball bag onto the field.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley really, really upset |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/dodgers/2004-06-02-bradley-ejection-tantrum_x.htm |newspaper=USA Today  |date=June 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> Bradley was suspended for four games and Tracy for one game.<ref name=\"Quote\">{{cite web |title=Outfielder also fined; Tracy suspended 1 game |date=June 4, 2004 |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1815331 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> On September 19, he hit a 479-foot home run against the [[Colorado Rockies]] in [[Coors Field]].<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" /> On September 28, during a home game against the Rockies, Bradley mishandled a [[line drive]] and was charged with an [[error (baseball)|error]].  A fan threw a bottle at Bradley, who left his position in right field, picked up the bottle and threw it into the stands, yelling at the fan.  Bradley was immediately ejected from the game.  The next day, MLB suspended him for the remainder of the season and fined him an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bradley also fined for tossing the bottle into stands |date=September 30, 2004 |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1891679 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> In postseason play, he hit .273 with a home run while the Dodgers lost the [[National League Division Series]] to the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] three games to one.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2004_NLDS1.shtml |title=2004 League Division Series |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> He finished the 2004 season batting .267 with 19 home runs and 67 RBIs, but was [[caught stealing]] 11 times, tying for eighth most in MLB.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2004-batting-leaders.shtml |title=2004 Major League Baseball Batting Leaders |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the offseason, Bradley went through [[anger management]] counseling.<ref>{{cite news |title=Milton Bradley Looks to Be a Role Model |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106202774.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172237/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106202774.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |agency=Associated Press |date=March 9, 2005 |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription }}</ref> In a game against the [[San Francisco Giants]] on April 12, 2005, he drove in two runs with a single to tie the game in the bottom of the ninth inning with two outs, the winning run then scoring on [[Jason Ellison]]'s error in the same play.<ref>{{cite news |title=This is Just the Start |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131473440.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924125825/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131473440.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |date=April 13, 2005 |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Los Angeles Dodgers 9, San Francisco Giants 8 |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2005/B04120LAN2005.htm |publisher=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=June 17, 2012}}</ref> On August 25, 2005, after hitting .290 with 38 RBIs in 75 games, he was put on the 15-day DL with a torn [[patellar tendon]] and [[anterior cruciate ligament]] which rendered him inactive for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dodgers place Milton Bradley on disabled list |date=August 25, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=2143154 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> On December 13, 2005, the Dodgers traded him to the Oakland Athletics along with [[infielder]] [[Antonio P\u00e9rez (baseball)|Antonio P\u00e9rez]] for outfielder prospect [[Andre Ethier]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20051213&content_id=1281508&vkey=hotstove2005&fext=.jsp&affiliateId=CommentWidget |title=A's get Bradley, Perez in deal with LA |last=Urban |first=Mychael |work=MLB.com |date=December 23, 2005 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Oakland Athletics (2006\u20132007)===\nIn his first season with the Oakland Athletics, Bradley posted a .276 batting average with 14 home runs and 52 [[runs batted in]], in a part-time role. He went on the 15-day DL on May 11, 2006 for a strained oblique muscle and a sprained right knee.<ref>{{cite news |title=AL Notes: Athletics activate Bradley, Witasick |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/default/article/AL-Notes-Athletics-activate-Bradley-Witasick-1205506.php |date=June 6, 2006 |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]  |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> On July 30, he hit a three-run walk-off home run to beat the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] with two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley calls the winning shot: The often maligned outfielder's ninth-inning blast bails out Street for the A's sixth walk-off win of the year |last=Roderick |first=Joe |newspaper=[[Contra Costa Times]] |publisher=[[MediaNews Group]] |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-148863240.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610220631/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-148863240.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 10, 2014 |date=July 31, 2006 |accessdate=May 3, 2012|url-access=subscription }}</ref> During game four of the [[2006 American League Championship Series]] versus the [[Detroit Tigers]], Bradley became the third player in MLB history to hit home runs from each side of the plate in a postseason game, joining [[Bernie Williams]] and [[Chipper Jones]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20061011&content_id=1708819&vkey=news_oak&fext=.jsp&c_id=oak |title=Bradley's historic game can't boost A's |work=MLB.com |date=October 12, 2006 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> For the series, he went nine-for-eighteen with two home runs and five RBIs.<ref name=\"Rangers\">{{cite web |title=Rangers finalize one-year contract with Bradley |url=http://texas.rangers.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20071213&content_id=2324580&vkey=pr_tex&fext=.jsp&c_id=tex |work=MLB.com |date=December 17, 2007 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2007, the Athletics [[designated for assignment|designated him for assignment]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Urban |first=Mychael |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070621&content_id=2040883&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=A's designate Bradley for assignment |work=MLB.com |date=June 21, 2007 |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> A trade completed the next day, which would have sent Bradley to the [[Kansas City Royals]] for [[Leo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], was voided by the Royals because he had sustained an oblique injury in his last game as an Athletic.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kaegel |first=Dick |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070622&content_id=2043699&vkey=news_oak&fext=.jsp&c_id=oak |title=Bradley-to-Royals deal voided |work=MLB.com |date=June 22, 2007 |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref> He was then traded to the San Diego Padres on June 29, with cash, in exchange for Andrew Brown; it was the second time those two players had been traded for each other.\n\n===San Diego Padres (2007)===\n{{multiple image\n| footer=Bradley with the Padres, broke his bat over his knee after striking out on August 28, 2007.\n| align=left\n| image1=Milton Bradley breaking the bat over his knee after striking out.jpg\n| alt1=Milton Bradley before\n| width1=144\n| image2=Milton Bradley broke the bat over his knee after striking out.jpg\n| alt2=Milton Bradley after\n| width2=150\n}}\nBradley started his tenure with the Padres on the 15-day DL, but came off it on July 7; in July, he batted .364 with four home runs and 12 RBI in 18 games.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\nOn September 23, 2007, however, he tore his right [[anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] while being restrained by Padres manager [[Bud Black]] during an altercation with [[first base]] [[Umpire (baseball)|umpire]] [[Mike Winters]].<ref name=\"Padres\">{{cite news |title=Padres' Bradley tears ACL in fracas\u2013 Injury ends his season; blowup starts in dispute over outfielder's ejection |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-21794923.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924190543/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-21794923.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Commercial Appeal]]  |date=September 25, 2007 |last=Wilson |first=Bernie |accessdate=June 19, 2012|url-access=subscription }}</ref> [[Home plate]] umpire [[Brian Runge]] reportedly told Bradley that Winters said that he had tossed his bat in Runge's direction in a previous [[at-bat]].<ref name=\"Padres\" /> After Bradley reached first base, he questioned Winters about the alleged bat throwing and subsequent communication with Runge. According to Bradley and Padres first base coach [[Bobby Meacham]], Winters addressed Bradley with a barrage of profanity.<ref name=\"Padres\" /> Bradley then moved towards Winters. While restrained by Black, Bradley fell to the ground and injured himself. He missed the final week of the regular season in 2007, during which the Padres lost to the [[Colorado Rockies]] in a [[2007 National League Wild Card tie-breaker game|one game playoff]] for the [[Major League Baseball wild card|National League wild card]] on October 1.<ref>{{cite news |title=Going Low, Standing Tall; Rockies' 3-Run Rally in 13th Inning Stuns Padres, Secures NL Wild Card |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7637760.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924200233/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7637760.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=October 2, 2007 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Crandall |first=Kate |accessdate=June 19, 2012|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nWinters was suspended for the remainder of the season and also spent the postseason on the restricted list for the incident, after MLB determined that he had indeed directed obscene language toward Bradley. Bradley was not suspended, MLB finding no need for such discipline since he did not make physical contact with Winters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3050020 |title=Pads' Bradley fined, not suspended in blow-up with umpire |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=October 5, 2007 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Texas Rangers (2008)===\nAfter the 2007 season, Bradley agreed to a one-year contract with the Texas Rangers. He announced in early January 2008 that he expected to be healthy and ready to play in the season opener.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3160349 |title=Rehabbing torn ACL, Bradley plans to play in Rangers' opener |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=December 18, 2007 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs the Rangers [[designated hitter]], he led the AL in on-base plus slugging with a .999 mark. He was third in batting average (.321), and led the league in [[on-base percentage]] (.443). On making the All-Star game, he stated, \"If I somehow miraculously made it to the All-Star Game, I would be floored. I'd really be totally humbled by that. I'm just happy right now to play, to produce and to be with a good group of guys.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/stories/060608dnspocowlishaw.3022001.html?npc |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519222902/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/stories/060608dnspocowlishaw.3022001.html?npc |archivedate=May 19, 2009 |title=Star glows, ballots grow for Texas Rangers' Bradley |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |last=Cowlishaw |first=Tim |date=June 6, 2008 |accessdate=January 4, 2009}}</ref> He was selected to play in his first All-Star Game in 2008 as a designated hitter (DH) after being officially selected as a DH reserve, but due to an injury to [[David Ortiz]] he became the starting DH in the [[2008 MLB All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite news |title=All-Star Game starting lineups |date=July 15, 2008 |newspaper=The Buffalo News}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' Bradley attempted to confront [[Kansas City Royals]] television announcer [[Ryan Lefebvre]] in the [[press box]] following a June 2008 game for what he believed were unfair comments made on the air. As the Rangers' designated hitter, Bradley watched the broadcast when he was not batting and took offense to a comparison Lefebvre made between him and [[Josh Hamilton]].<ref name=\"BQuote\" /> Manager [[Ron Washington]] and [[general manager]] [[Jon Daniels]] chased after him and stopped him before he got to Lefebvre, at which point he returned to the clubhouse in tears and said:\n\n{{quote|All I want to do is play baseball and make a better life for my kid than I had, that's it. I love all you guys. \u2026 I'm strong, but I'm not that strong.<ref name=\"BQuote\" />}}\n\nHe was quoted by Rangers radio broadcasters as saying that he never intended to physically harm Lefebvre but did want to speak to him; Daniels said he was upset that someone he didn't know was judging him.<ref name=\"BQuote\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/baseball/rangers/stories/061208dnsporangersbradley.3c7e26f.html |title=Texas Rangers' Bradley gets emotional over TV comments |newspaper=The Dallas Morning News |last=Durrett |first=Richard |date=June 12, 2008 |accessdate=January 4, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614234953/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/baseball/rangers/stories/061208dnsporangersbradley.3c7e26f.html |archivedate=June 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Cubs (2009)===\nOn January 8, 2009, Bradley signed a three-year, $30 million deal with the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Carrie |last=Muskat |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090108&content_id=3736641&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc |title='Blessed' Bradley signs with Cubs |work=MLB.com |date=January 8, 2009 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref> He was issued a two-game suspension for supposedly making contact with umpire [[Larry Vanover]] while arguing a strike call on April 16, which was reduced to one game on appeal.<ref>{{cite web |first=Carrie |last=Muskat |title=Bradley's suspension reduced |date=May 14, 2009 |work=MLB.com |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090514&content_id=4730876&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> During an interleague game against the [[Minnesota Twins]] on June 12, he caught a routine fly in right field and threw it into the stands, believing it was the third out of the inning when there were only two outs.<ref name='bradley-twins' /> The umpire allowed each of the Twins' baserunners to advance two bases as a result.<ref name='bradley-twins'>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/chi-13-cubs-twins-chicago-jun13,0,3738172.story |last=van Dyck |first=Dave |title=Chicago Cubs fall 7\u20134 to Minnesota Twins |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=June 13, 2009 |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nLater that month, Cub manager [[Lou Piniella]] told Bradley to leave the dugout and go home after he \"went after\" a [[Gatorade]] cooler in frustration after flying out in another interleague game, against the [[Chicago White Sox]]. Piniella and Bradley later confronted each other in the locker room and exchanged words.<ref name='bradley-lou'>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Seligman |title=Soto homer lifts Cubs over White Sox |date=June 27, 2009 |agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-D992M73G0.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924041611/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-D992M73G0.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |accessdate=June 27, 2009|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Piniella later apologized to Bradley, and reinserted him back into the line-up during the team's next start.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bradley: 'I don't have problem with Lou' |date=June 28, 2009 |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/news/story?id=4291786 |work=ESPN |accessdate=July 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 2009, the Cubs announced that Bradley would be suspended for the remainder of the season after an interview in which Bradley talked about \"negativity\" on the part of the Cub organization and declared, \"You understand why they [the Cubs] haven't won in 100 years here.\" He also said he was uncomfortable just being on the Cubs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/mlb/news/story?id=4490125 |title=Chicago Cubs suspend Milton Bradley for the rest of the season |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=September 27, 2009}}</ref> General Manager [[Jim Hendry]] felt the comments were disrespectful.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Paul |title=Bradley suspended for rest of season |newspaper=Chicago Tribune  |date=September 20, 2009 |url=http://blogs.chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports_hardball/2009/09/bradley-not-with-cubs-hendry-will-address-team.html |accessdate=September 20, 2009}}</ref> Bradley later apologized to the Cubs organization for his remarks.<ref name=\"Bradley_apologize\">{{cite news |first=Rick |last=Morrissey |title=Here's a 'real' apology from Milton Bradley |date=September 25, 2009 |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-09-25/sports/0909250004_1_apology-milton-bradley-alfonso-soriano |accessdate=September 25, 2009}}</ref> For the Cubs, Bradley hit .257 with 12 home runs and 40 RBIs<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" /> before being traded to the Seattle Mariners for [[Carlos Silva]] and cash on December 18, 2009.<ref name='bradley-trade1'>{{cite news |first=Larry |last=Stone |title=Shocker: Mariners trade Carlos Silva for Milton Bradley |date=December 18, 2009 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/thehotstoneleague/2010540975_shocker_mariners_trading_carlo.html |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=May 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Seattle Mariners (2010\u20132011)===\n[[File:Milton Bradley speaks to the ump.jpg|thumb|right|Bradley speaking to umpire [[Joe West (umpire)|Joe West]]]]\nBradley was part of a flurry of offseason moves by the Mariners in hopes of returning to the playoffs, having not reached the postseason since 2001.<ref name=\"Cubs trade Bradley\">{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091218&content_id=7828862&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc&partnerId=rss_chc |title=Cubs trade Bradley for Silva, cash |last=Muskat |first=Carrie |work=MLB.com |accessdate=18 December 2009}}</ref> On May 4, 2010, he removed himself from a game and left the stadium.  He asked the Mariners for help with a personal problem, and the organization responded. He was placed on the restricted list, and returned to the team on May 18 after undergoing treatment of an undisclosed nature.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2010/05/troubled-milton-bradley-placed-on-mariners-restricted-list/1 |title=Troubled Milton Bradley placed on Mariners' restricted list |newspaper=USA Today |last=Nightengale |first=Bob |date=May 6, 2010 |accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> He ended the season on the DL after having been placed on it on July 31 prior to right knee [[arthroscopic]] surgery on August 17. He finished the 2010 season batting .205, with eight home runs and 29 RBIs over 73 games played.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\n\nOn May 9, 2011, the Mariners designated Bradley for assignment after starting the 2011 season hitting .218 with two home runs and 13 RBI in 28 games. Reportedly, the Mariners lost patience with Bradley due to his performance in a series against the White Sox. In the first game, he was ejected for arguing balls and strikes in the eighth inning, preventing the Mariners from putting in a pinch-runner due to not having enough available players. In the second game, he was booed for not hustling after several balls hit his way. In the final game, he made a poor throw that led to two White Sox runs.<ref name=\"nwsource1\">{{cite news|last=Baker |first=Geoff |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2015005893_mari10.html |title=Mariners cut ties with Milton Bradley |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=May 9, 2011 |accessdate=May 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514005616/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2015005893_mari10.html |archivedate=May 14, 2011 }}</ref> Unable to trade Bradley, the Mariners released him on May 16.<ref name=\"nwsource1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2005, Bradley was the Dodgers' nominee for the [[Roberto Clemente Award]] for working with the Dodgers Dream Foundation, [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]], and the Long Beach [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Clubs]], among other charities. Bradley has also opened two baseball academies, one in Long Beach and another in [[Baldwin Hills, Los Angeles|Baldwin Hills]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Milton Bradley |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308082647/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/components/official_info/community/clemente_2005/bios/bradley_milton.jsp |archivedate=March 8, 2009 |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/components/official_info/community/clemente_2005/bios/bradley_milton.jsp |work=MLB.com |accessdate=May 6, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2005, [[Redondo Beach, California|Redondo Beach]] police received three domestic-violence-related calls from Bradley's house. No charges were filed.<ref>{{cite news |title=3 Domestic Calls to Bradley's Home |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-112655375.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172455/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-112655375.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=August 31, 2005 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 2006, Bradley filed for divorce but the petition was never finalized.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley, wife will meet for hearing; Mariners; Bradley, wife to meet in L.A. to determine if felony case proceeds |date=February 10, 2011 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-248777587.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152832/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-248777587.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |accessdate=June 18, 2012 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, Bradley was arrested at his home in [[Encino, California]] and charged with making criminal threats to his wife, Monique. When he agreed to participate in an out-of-court hearing process, no charges were filed against him. However, his wife subsequently filed for divorce.<ref name=\"nwsource1\" /><ref>Bradley was arrested in August 2011 for allegedly attacking Monique with a bat, and in March 2012 he allegedly threatened her with a knife and while yelling profanities. Monique filed a domestic violence report with the LAPD in November 2012 claiming Bradley tried to choke her, with two hands, when she asked him to stop smoking marijuana in front of their sons.\nOn January 10, 2013, Bradley was formerly charged by LAPD with 13 misdemeanor counts of assault with a deadly weapon, vandalism and dissuading a witness from making a report. {{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/milton-bradley-charged-la-domestic-193023686--mlb.html1 |title=Milton Bradley charged in LA with domestic abuse |agency=Associated Press|date=January 11, 2013 |accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Bradley was charged with several crimes stemming from five different domestic incidents which occurred in 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former MLB outfielder Milton Bradley charged with domestic abuse|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2013/01/11/milton-bradley-charged-in-la-with-domestic-abuse/1827619/|accessdate=4 June 2017|work=[[USA Today]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 11, 2013|language=en}}</ref> On June 3, 2013, Bradley was convicted by a jury of nine counts of physically attacking and threatening his wife including four counts of spousal battery, two counts of criminal threats, one count of assault with a deadly weapon, one count of vandalism and one count of brandishing a deadly weapon. On July 2, 2013, he was sentenced to 32 months in prison and 52 weeks of domestic violence and anger-management classes, and was released on $250,000 bail.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/04/08/milton-bradley-domestic-abuse-mlb-monique-bradley |title=The tragic extent of Monique and Milton Bradley's violent relationship |last=McKnight |first=Michael |date=13 April 2015 |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=15 April 2015}}</ref> Despite his convictions and sentence, Bradley maintained [[sole custody]] of his and Monique's two sons.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=A's Bradley Files for Divorce |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117252832.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172638/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117252832.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=January 12, 2006 |accessdate=June 18, 2012 |agency=Associated Press|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"AP_2013\">{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley charged in LA with domestic abuse |agency=Associated Press |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/milton-bradley-charged-la-domestic-abuse}}</ref>\n\nOn September 14, 2013, at the age of 33, Monique Bradley died<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ohio/obituary.aspx?pid=167158640#fbLoggedOut Monique Bradley Obituary - Akron, OH | Akron Beacon Journal<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> at [[Encino Hospital Medical Center]].<ref name=\":0\" /> A [[death certificate]] dated October 10 lists the causes as [[Cryptogenic disease|cryptogenic]] [[cirrhosis]] of the [[liver]], [[Shock (circulatory)|hemorrhagic shock]] and [[cardiac arrest]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn January 21, 2015, a Los Angeles [[appellate court]] rejected Bradley's appeal.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' reported in May 2015 that following another unsuccessful appeal, Bradley was ordered to begin serving the 32-month sentence for his 2013 convictions, with the hearing judge stating that Bradley's request for leniency was \"breathtaking, frankly, in how callous\" it was.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ex-MLB outfielder Milton Bradley to start serving 32-month jail sentence|url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/05/15/milton-bradley-jail-domestic-abuse|work=Sports Illustrated|date=May 15, 2015|accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref> In early 2016, Bradley's request to have his jail sentence reduced was denied by a Los Angeles Superior Court judge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Judge denies request by ex-MLB OF Milton Bradley for reduced jail time|url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/01/07/milton-bradley-release-court-case|work=Sports Illustrated|date=January 7, 2016|accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Bradley was charged with spousal battery and taken into custody on bail of $175,000 for allegedly assaulting his wife during a January 2018 incident, at which time Bradley was on probation for his earlier domestic violence conviction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ex-MLB outfielder Milton Bradley Charged With Spousal Battery|url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2018/04/09/milton-bradley-domestic-violence-spousal-battery|work=Sports Illustrated|date=2018-04-09|accessdate=2018-08-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Milton Bradley Handcuffed In Court at Domestic Violence Hearing|url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/04/10/milton-bradley-handcuffed-custody-battery-domestic-violence/|work=TMZ|date=2018-04-10|accessdate=2018-08-07}}</ref> In June 2018 Bradley pleaded no contest to domestic battery, was sentenced to 36 months of probation, and was required to complete 52 weeks of domestic violence counseling.<ref>{{cite web|title=Milton Bradley Convicted in Dom. Violence Case|url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/06/13/milton-bradley-domestic-violence-convicted/|work=TMZ|date=2018-06-13|accessdate=2018-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Milton Bradley}}\n{{commonscat|Milton Bradley (baseball)}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=150396 |espn=4245 |br=b/bradlmi01 |fangraphs=369 |brm=bradle001mil}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradley, Milton}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American baseball players]]\n[[Category:Akron Aeros players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1999 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Cape Fear Crocs players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Expos players]]\n[[Category:Harrisburg Senators players]]\n[[Category:Jupiter Hammerheads players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas 51s players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball outfielders]]\n[[Category:Montreal Expos players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Lynx players]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of battery]]\n[[Category:People from Harbor City, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sacramento River Cats players]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Stockton Ports players]]\n[[Category:Texas Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Vermont Expos players]]\n", "name_user": "Coffeeandcrumbs", "label": "safe", "comment": "tag citations need and harmonize whitespace in citation templates (usinga script)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milton_Bradley_(baseball)"}
{"title_page": "Proactiv", "text_new": "{{Infobox brand\n|name         = Proactiv\n| logo           = File:ProactivLogo.png\n| logo_upright   = upright\n| image          = File:Proactiv three-step kit, June 2013 (cropped).jpg\n| producttype    = Skincare\n| currentowner   = [[Guthy-Renker]]<br> [[Galderma]]<ref name=\"Nestl\u00e9\"/>\n| producedby     =\n| country        = United States\n| introduced     = {{start date and age|1995|10}}\n| markets        = Australasia, Europe, North America, Scandinavia\n| previousowners = [[Katie Rodan]]<br>Kathy Fields\n| ambassadors    = [[Justin Bieber]], [[Sean Combs]], [[Avril Lavigne]] and others\n| tagline        = \"Be Proactiv\"\n| website        = {{URL|proactiv.com}}\n}}\n'''Proactiv''', also known as '''Proactiv Solution''', is a brand of [[Skin care#Skin care products|skin-care products]] developed by two American [[Dermatology|dermatologists]], [[Katie Rodan]] and [[Kathy A. Fields]], and launched in 1995 by [[Guthy-Renker]], a California-based [[direct marketing]] company.<ref>Katie Rodan, Kathy Fields (2008). ''Unblemished'', Simon and Schuster, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=RXRfwjMnl38C&pg=PA4 4\u20138].</ref> The range includes moisturizers, body washes and hair products, but the brand is known for its three-step anti-[[Acne vulgaris|acne]] kit consisting of a cleanser, toner and lotion.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011>{{cite journal | author = Kraft John, Freiman Anatoli | year = 2011 | title = Management of acne | journal = Canadian Medical Journal | volume = 183 | issue = 7| pages = E430\u2013E435 | doi = 10.1503/cmaj.090374 | pmid = 21398228 | pmc = 3080563 }}</ref><ref name=NIH/> Proactiv+, a reformulation of the three-step kit, was introduced in 2013.<ref name=MychaskiwInStyle2013/>\n\nAs a result of its celebrity endorsements and [[infomercial]]s, Proactiv is one of the most popular skincare brands of all time, according to the ''Journal of Clinical and Aesthetic Dermatology''.<ref name=DeckerJCAD2012/> Sales amounted to $800 million a year as of 2010, with a media budget of nearly $200 million and $12\u201315 million for celebrity fees.<ref name=LaceyForbes2010/> The product is mostly sold online as part of a [[Continuity sales model|continuity program]]. A month after ordering, customers are sent a three-month supply, which continues until the subscription is cancelled.<ref name=RomeroABC72011>{{cite news|title=Which Acne Treatment Works Best, Costs Less?|url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/consumer&id=8422230|publisher=ABC7|author=Ric Romero|date=November 7, 2011}}</ref> Customers have complained that the subscriptions are hard to cancel.<ref name=truthinadvertising2013/>\n\nAccording to a 2011 [[Review article|review]], there have been few studies on the efficacy of Proactiv.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/> A 2011 ''[[Consumer Reports]]'' study compared Proactiv with two less expensive types of [[benzoyl peroxide]], AcneFree and OXY Maximum, and found all three to be equally effective.<ref name=consumerreports2011/> The US [[Food and Drug Administration]] warned in 2014 that over-the-counter acne treatments can cause severe irritation, as well as rare but life-threatening allergic reactions.<ref name=FDA2014/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Product development===\nProactiv was created in the late 1980s by [[Katie Rodan]] and [[Kathy A. Fields]], who met while at [[Stanford University School of Medicine]].<ref name=R&F2008pp4-7>Rodan and Fields 2008, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=RXRfwjMnl38C&pg=PA4 4\u20137].</ref><ref name=\"EspinozaPeople2002\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20137526,00.html|newspaper=People|title=Saving Face|author=Galina Espinoza|date=July 15, 2002}}</ref>\n\nProactiv was offered to [[Neutrogena]], which declined it, but its CEO, Allan Kurtzman, suggested selling it via infomercials.<ref name=\"EspinozaPeople2002\"/><ref name=R&F2008p8>Rodan and Fields 2008, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=RXRfwjMnl38C&pg=PA8 8].</ref> Guthy-Renker were already in the infomercial business and agreed to market and distribute it. The first infomercial appeared in October 1995, offering a money-back guarantee and fast delivery, and featuring [[Judith Light]], who suffered from acne problems herself.<ref name=R&F2008p8/><ref name=CasserlyForbes2010>{{cite news|author=Meghan Casserly|newspaper=Forbes|date=November 30, 2010|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/meghancasserly/2010/11/30/proactiv-celebrity-endorsement-katy-perry-lindsay-lohan-justin-bieber/|title=Proactiv's Active Ingredient: Celebrity}}</ref> Rodan and Fields later founded their own skincare brand, Rodan + Fields.<ref>Dana Mattioli, Gillian Tan (February 18, 2015). [https://www.wsj.com/articles/skin-care-company-rodan-fields-pursuing-a-sale-1424283321 \"Skin Care Company Rodan & Fields Pursuing a Sale\"], ''Wall Street Journal''.</ref>\n\n===Guthy-Renker===\n[[Guthy-Renker]] LLC is a [[direct-response marketing]] company registered in [[Palm Desert]], California. Founded in 1988 by Bill Guthy and [[Greg Renker]], the company is known as \"the Rolls Royce\" of the infomercial industry.<ref name=ArndorferAA2005/><ref>Bernice Kanner (October 21, 1991). [https://books.google.com/books?id=8ugCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA24 \"30 Minutes: Selling with Infomercials\"], ''New York Magazine.</ref> As of 2012 its portfolio of products was making $1.8 billion a year.<ref name=JohnsonSuccess2012/> The range includes [[Victoria Principal]]'s Principal Secret skincare (its earliest skincare brand), Wen Hair Care, [[Cindy Crawford]]'s Meaningful Beauty skincare, the Dean Martin Celebrity Roast DVDs, and the Malibu Pilates Chair.<ref>[http://www.responsemagazine.com/ims-top-drtv-national-cable-and-satelite-rankings-2 \"The Top DRTV National and Cable Satellite Rankings\"], ''Response Magazine''.</ref><ref name=LunauMacleans2011>Kate Lunau (January 8, 2011). [http://www.macleans.ca/economy/business/pretty-valuable-faces/ \"Pretty valuable faces\"], ''Macleans''.</ref><ref>Charles Wesley Orton (May 2001). [https://webms.guthy-renker.eu/WMS/Upload/WMS_BrandSites/Resources/Guthy-Renker_Europe/Response_Magazine.pdf \"Partners in Time: The Guthy-Renker story\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022235306/https://webms.guthy-renker.eu/WMS/Upload/WMS_BrandSites/Resources/Guthy-Renker_Europe/Response_Magazine.pdf |date=2013-10-22 }}, ''Response Magazine''.</ref>\n\n===Nestl\u00e9===\nIn March 2016, [[Nestl\u00e9]] joined Guthy-Renker as a majority owner of Proactiv. In October 2019, Nestle sold its shares to EQT.<ref name=\"Nestl\u00e9\">{{cite news|last1=Grettler|first1=Corinne|title=Nestle Forms Alliance With Bieber's Fave Acne Cure Proactiv|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-24/nestle-forms-acne-joint-venture-with-maker-of-proactiv-brand|accessdate=April 11, 2016|publisher=Bloomberg|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nProactiv is a registered trademark of Guthy-Renker. The brand's primary product is a three-step kit comprising a cleanser, toner and lotion, which sells for $20 a month in the United States if purchased as part of the continuity program.<ref>{{cite news|title=Acne Treatment Helps Some, Not All|date=January 30, 2003|newspaper=Newsday|author=Joanne Kabak|url=http://www.newsday.com/acne-treatment-helps-some-not-all-1.438693}}</ref>\n\nThe toner contains [[glycolic acid]], an [[Exfoliation (cosmetology)|exfoliant]], and [[witch hazel (astringent)|witch hazel]], an [[astringent]].<ref name=SingerNYT2007/><ref>{{cite news|title=The lucrative business of pimples; Proactiv ad campaign transforms way consumers think about acne|author=Natasha Singer|date=October 19, 2007|pp=D2|newspaper=LIFE}}</ref> The active ingredient in the cleanser and lotion, outside Europe, is a 2.5% concentration of [[benzoyl peroxide]], lower than in most prescription-strength [[Acne vulgaris#Management|acne treatments]].<ref name=\"FiremanDT2011\">{{cite journal | author = Fireman Sharon | year = 2011 | title = A look at emerging delivery systems for topical drug products | url = | journal = Dermatologic Therapy | volume = 24 | issue = 5| pages = 477\u2013488 | doi = 10.1111/j.1529-8019.2012.01464.x | pmid = 22353154 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|John Kraft, Anatoli Freiman (''Canadian Medical Association Journal'', 2011): \"[[Benzoyl peroxide]] is available in various topical preparations, ranging in strength from 2.5% to 10.0%. Any strength can be used initially, although it may be more prudent to start with a lower concentration; stronger preparations are more irritating and not necessarily more effective.\"<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/>}} Benzoyl peroxide has been used since 1934 to kill ''[[Cutibacterium acnes]]'', the bacterium that causes acne.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Fluhr J. W., Degitz K. | year = 2010 | title = Antibiotics, azelaic acid and benzoyl peroxide in topical acne therapy | journal = Journal der Deutschen Dermatologischen Gesellschaft | volume = 8 | issue = S1| pages = S24\u2013S30 | doi = 10.1111/j.1610-0387.2009.07169.x | pmid = 20482689 }}</ref> Several over-the-counter acne treatments contain it, including [[Clean & Clear]], [[Clearasil]], [[List of Procter & Gamble brands#Skin care|Doctor's Dermatologic Formula]], [[Neutrogena|Neutrogena Advanced Systems]], [[Stiefel Laboratories|PanOxyl]] and [[Stridex]].<ref name=ParikhSalon2011/><ref>Jessica Wu (2011). ''Feed Your Face'', Macmillan, p. 70.</ref>\n\nThere is also a three-step program in Extra Strength, with a 7% concentration of benzoyl peroxide,<ref name=\"FiremanDT2011\"/> and a Gentle Formula that instead contains a 2% concentration of [[salicylic acid]], an exfoliant.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/> The three-step kit in Europe is based on salicylic acid; in the UK it costs \u00a339.99 ($60) for a two-month supply.{{refn|group=n|As of 2015 [[Boots UK|Boots the Chemist]] in the UK charges \u00a339.99 ($60) for the Proactiv Solution cleanser (120 ml), toner (120 ml) and lotion (60 ml).<ref name=Boots2015>[http://www.boots.com/en/Proactiv-Solution-3-Step-System-To-Clearer-Healthier-Looking-Skin_1248826/ \"Proactiv Solution 3 Step System To Clearer Healthier Looking Skin\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121160709/http://www.boots.com/en/Proactiv-Solution-3-Step-System-To-Clearer-Healthier-Looking-Skin_1248826 |date=2015-11-21 }}, Boots.</ref>}}<ref>Tamara Hinson (February 16, 2012). [https://uk.lifestyle.yahoo.com/blogs/tamara-hinson/proactive-skincare-arrived-uk-worth-money-125054667.html \"Proactiv skincare has arrived in the UK \u2013 but is it worth your money?\"], ''The Beauty Files'', Yahoo.</ref> Other Proactiv products include an oil-free moisturizer that uses [[octinoxate]] (7.5%) and [[zinc oxide]] (3%), and an anti-dandruff shampoo with a 1% concentration of [[zinc pyrithione]].<ref name=NIH>{{cite web|title=List of Proactiv products and their ingredients|publisher=[[DailyMed]], [[National Institutes of Health]]|url=http://dailymed.nlm.nih.gov/dailymed/search.cfm?query=proactiv&searchdb=all&labeltype=all&sortby=rel&audience=professional&page=1&pagesize=200}}</ref>\n\nGuthy-Renker introduced Proactiv+ in 2013, charging $30 in the United States for a month's supply if the customer creates a subscription. It is a [[paraben]]-free three-step kit comprising a cleanser and toning gel, each with 2.5% benzoyl peroxide, and a moisturizer with salicylic acid. It is reportedly more hydrating than the original program.<ref name=MychaskiwInStyle2013>{{cite web|author=Marianne Mychaskiw|title=Proactiv Launches Proactiv+ Line, More Hydrating Formula|url=http://news.instyle.com/2013/01/29/proactiv-plus-line/|newspaper=InStyle|date=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Safety and efficacy==\n[[File:BenzoperoxideRx.JPG|thumb|A skin reaction from benzoyl peroxide]]\n\nProactiv is aimed at customers with mild to moderate acne.<ref name=SingerNYT2007>Natasha Singer (October 18, 2007). [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/18/fashion/18skin.html  \"Why Should Kids Have All the Acne?\"], ''The New York Times''.</ref> According to a 2011 review, there have been few studies examining its efficacy.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/> A 2007 study saw inflammatory lesions reduced by 39% in subjects using a combination of [[butenafine]] and benzoyl peroxide, compared with 34% in those using Proactiv containing only benzoyl peroxide.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/><ref name=\"BurkhartBurkhartIJD2007\">{{cite journal|author= Craig G. Burkhart; Craig N. Burkhart|title=Treatment of acne vulgaris without antibiotics: tertiary amine-benzoyl peroxide combination vs. benzoyl peroxide alone (Proactiv Solution?)|journal=International Journal of Dermatology|volume=46|issue=1|year=2007|pages=89\u201393|doi=10.1111/j.1365-4632.2007.03081.x|pmid=17214729}}</ref> A physician suggested in ''Salon'' that its three-step system might make it easier for teenagers to comply, but that the key to its success lay with its celebrity endorsements.<ref name=ParikhSalon2011>{{cite news|date=February 28, 2011|title=Proactiv's celebrity shell game|author=Rahul Parikh|url=http://www.salon.com/2011/02/28/proactiv_celebrity_sham/|newspaper=Salon}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[Consumer Reports]]'' compared Proactiv (2.5% benzoyl peroxide) with two less expensive products, AcneFree (2.5% benzoyl peroxide) and OXY Maximum (10% benzoyl peroxide).<ref name=consumerreports2011/> At the time a two-month supply of Proactiv cost around $40 in the US, AcneFree $20 and OXY Maximum $5.<ref name=RomeroABC72011/> Eighty-three subjects, aged 14 to 40, used one of the products twice a day for eight weeks. The magazine reported that, no matter which product was used, after two weeks around 75% of subjects saw a 35% reduction in blemishes on average. After eight weeks, around 50\u201366% saw a 40% reduction on average.<ref name=consumerreports2011>{{citation|publisher=[[Consumer Reports]]|date=November 2011|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/2011/11/review-of-acne-treatments/index.htm|title=Review of acne treatments}}</ref>\n\nBenzoyl peroxide can have a drying effect on the skin, can cause [[erythema]] (redness) and fine scaling, though these effects are usually mild, and can increase sensitivity to sunlight. One in 500 may experience [[allergic contact dermatitis]]. It is categorized as a [[Pregnancy category#United States|pregnancy category]] C agent, \"suggesting that its use in pregnancy may not be prudent,\" according to a literature review in the ''Journal of Clinical and Aesthetic Dermatology''.{{refn|group=n|Ashley Decker, Emmy M. Graber (''Journal of Clinical and Aesthetic Dermatology'', 2012): \"Since the 1930s, BP [benzoyl peroxide] has been a popular choice for the treatment of AV [acne vulgaris] due to its [[keratolytic]], moderate comedolytic, and [[Antibiotics|antibacterial]] properties, which include the reduction of ''[[Cutibacterium acnes]]'' and ''[[Staphylococcus aureus]]'' on skin. Cutaneous side effects of BP are most often irritant in nature, may be concentration and/or vehicle dependent, and are usually mild, including signs such as dryness, [[erythema]], and fine scaling. A minority of the population treated with BP for AV will experience true [[allergic contact dermatitis]] (1:500). Although available OTC, BP is a [[pregnancy category]] C agent, suggesting that its use in pregnancy may not be prudent.\"<ref name=DeckerJCAD2012>{{cite journal | author = Decker Ashley, Graber Emmy M | year = 2012 | title = Over-the-counter Acne Treatments | journal = Journal of Clinical and Aesthetic Dermatology | volume = 5 | issue = 5| pages = 32\u201340 | pmid = 22808307 | pmc=3366450}}</ref>}} If benzoyl peroxide comes into contact with clothing it is likely to bleach it.<ref>Robert M. Kliegman et al. (2015). ''Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics'', Elsevier Health Sciences, p&nbsp;[https://books.google.com/books?id=mseNCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA3402 3231].<!--Note: the page number in the link and on the page differ.--></ref>\n\nThe US [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) warned in 2014 that over-the-counter acne products containing benzoyl peroxide and/or salicylic acid, including Proactiv, can cause severe irritation, as well as rare but life-threatening allergic reactions. Consumers were advised to stop using the products if they experience hives or itching, and to seek emergency medical attention if they feel faint, or experience throat tightness, breathing problems, or swelling of the eyes, face, lips or tongue. The FDA noted that it remains unclear whether the reactions are caused by the active ingredients, inactive ingredients or a combination.<ref name=FDA2014>[https://www.fda.gov/Safety/MedWatch/SafetyInformation/SafetyAlertsforHumanMedicalProducts/ucm402722.htm \"Over-The-Counter Topical Acne Products: Drug Safety Communication - Rare But Serious Hypersensitivity Reactions\"], Food and Drug Administration, June 25, 2014.{{pb}}\n[https://www.fda.gov/downloads/ForConsumers/ConsumerUpdates/UCM402554.pdf \"Topical Acne Products Can Cause Dangerous Side Effects\"], Food and Drug Administration, June 2014.{{pb}}\n[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/26/business/fda-warns-of-allergy-to-some-anti-acne-products.html \"F.D.A. Warns of Allergy to Some Anti-Acne Products\"], Associated Press, June 25, 2014.{{pb}}\n[https://www.fda.gov/Drugs/GuidanceComplianceRegulatoryInformation/Surveillance/AdverseDrugEffects/ucm376571.htm \"Potential Signals of Serious Risks/New Safety Information Identified by the FDA Adverse Event Reporting System (FAERS) between July \u2013 September 2013\"], Food and Drug Administration, November 1, 2013, updated September 10, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Sales and marketing==\n\n===Sales===\n[[File:Proactiv vending machine, Indianapolis airport, February 2008.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|Proactiv vending machine, [[Indianapolis International Airport]], 2008]]\nProactiv is marketed and distributed by Guthy-Renker, and is responsible for about half the company's revenue.<ref name=ArndorferAA2005>J. B. Arndorfer (May 2, 2005). \"[http://adage.com/article/news/guthy-renker-infomercial-street-cred/103068/ Guthy-Renker gives the infomercial street cred],\" ''Advertising Age'', 76(18).</ref><ref name=JohnsonSuccess2012>{{cite news|author=Emma Johnson|newspaper=Success Magazine|title=As Seen on TV|url=http://www.success.com/articles/1949-------as-seen-on-tv|date=September 10, 2012}}</ref> Sales of Proactiv amounted to $800 million as of 2010.<ref name=LaceyForbes2010/> 70% of sales were in the United States as of 2007.<ref name=SingerNYT2007/>\n\nThe product is available in some stores, including [[Boots UK|Boots]] in the UK,<ref name=Boots2015/> and in kiosks and vending machines (known as [[Zoom Systems|ZoomShops]]) in malls and airports through a partnership between American Kiosk Management and Guthy-Renker .<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/26/business/26vending.html?pagewanted=all|title=The New Touch-Face of Vending Machines|author=Stephanie Rosenbloom|date=May 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=SteinbergWSJ2007>{{citation|title=Questions for ... Greg Renker & Ben Van De Bunt|author=Brian Steinberg|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=April 18, 2007|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB117684790782073165}}</ref> But the product is mostly sold online or through a toll-free number directly by Guthy-Renker; 60% of Proactiv orders were placed online as of 2010.<ref name=NetherbyBillboard20Aug2010/>\n\n===Continuity program===\nGuthy-Renker sells Proactiv as part of a [[Continuity sales model|continuity program]], also known as a [[Negative option billing|negative-option offer]], whereby customers are sent repeat orders until they cancel.<ref name=RomeroABC72011/><ref name=truthinadvertising2013>[https://www.truthinadvertising.org/five-common-complaints-about-guthy-renker/ \"Five Common Complaints about Guthy-Renker\"], [[Truth in Advertising (organization)|Truth in Advertising]], June 25, 2013.</ref> When purchasing directly from the company, customers automatically become members of a Proactiv club. A month after ordering, and every three months thereafter, they are sent a three-month supply costing $60 (in the US as of 2011), plus shipping and handling.<ref name=RomeroABC72011/> They are billed monthly until they cancel the subscription.<ref>Lynda Steele (November 9, 2011). [http://bc.ctvnews.ca/testing-star-endorsed-proactiv-1.722916 \"Testing star-endorsed Proactiv\"], CTV News.</ref> The approach is based on the [[customer lifetime value]] model.<ref>{{cite book|author=Josh Kaufman|title=The Personal MBA: Master the Art of Business|date=2010|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-101-44608-9|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=_DZ_AMDl5yUC&pg=PT196 196]}}</ref>\n\nCustomers have complained that they have created subscriptions inadvertently and found them difficult to cancel.<ref>[[Amanda Marcotte]] (January 14, 2013). [http://www.slate.com/blogs/xx_factor/2013/01/14/proactiv_acne_system_may_be_bad_for_consumers_nothing_special_for_your_skin.html \"Don't Bother With Proactiv\"], ''Slate''.{{pb}}\nJennifer Abel (September 13, 2013). [http://www.consumeraffairs.com/news/acnes-hard-to-get-rid-of-so-is-proactiv-091313.html \"Acne's hard to get rid of; so is Proactiv\"], ConsumerAffairs.{{pb}}\nKatie J. M. Baker (January 11, 2013). [http://jezebel.com/5975176/proactiv-horror-stories-tales-from-skincares-big-scam \"Proactiv Horror Stories: Tales From Skincare's Big Scam\"], ''Jezebel''.{{pb}}\nKatie J. M. Baker (January 4, 2013). [http://jezebel.com/5972898/why-is-it-so-hard-to-quit-proactiv \"Why Is It So Hard to Quit Proactiv?\"], ''Jezebel''.{{pb}}\nRob Walker (June 12, 2005). [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/12/magazine/12CONSUMED.html \"The Celebrity Solution\"], ''The New York Times''.</ref> The most common complaints about Guthy-Renker, according to [[Truth in Advertising (organization)|Truth in Advertising]], are unauthorized billing, difficulty cancelling orders, billing for products that never arrive, unhelpful customer service, and refusing refunds despite money-back guarantees.<ref name=truthinadvertising2013/>\n\n===Commercials===\nGuthy-Renker had a media budget of $200 million for Proactive as of 2010, much of it spent on air-time, and was spending another $12\u201315 million a year on celebrity endorsements.<ref name=LaceyForbes2010>{{cite news|newspaper=Forbes|date=November 3, 2010|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2010/1122/private-companies-10-guthy-renker-media-shill-shocked.html|title=Shill Shocked|author=Rose Lacey}}</ref> [[Justin Bieber]] for example, was paid $3 million over two years.<ref name=NetherbyBillboard20Aug2010>{{cite news|title=Justin Bieber Joins Proactiv's Zit-Geist |newspaper=Billboard|author=Jennifer Netherby |date=August 20, 2010|url=http://www.billboard.com/features/justin-bieber-joins-proactiv-s-zit-geist-1004110497.story#/features/justin-bieber-joins-proactiv-s-zit-geist-1004110497.story}}</ref> Its infomercials have featured celebrities who have themselves suffered from acne problems; the list includes [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[P. Diddy]], [[Avril Lavigne]], [[Lindsay Lohan]], [[Alyssa Milano]], [[Katy Perry]], [[Jessica Simpson]], [[Britney Spears]] and [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]].<ref name=CasserlyForbes2010/>\n\nAccording to the ''New York Times'', until 2010 Proactiv infomercials were \"fast-talking\" and \"hard-selling\"; an announcer repeatedly advised viewers to \"call now,\" and offered faster shipping if the order was placed within three minutes. As infomercials became less popular, Proactiv sales stalled.<ref name=ElliottNYT2010/> Since 2010 Guthy-Renker has tried to move the brand into the mainstream cosmetics market, focusing on quality rather than price.<ref name=LaceyForbes2010/> It began advertising on network television during shows like [[American Idol]], and in ''Elle'', ''InStyle'' and ''People'' magazines.<ref name=ElliottNYT2010>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/04/business/media/04adco.html|title=Trying to Move Up From a Fast-Talking, Buy-Now Approach|author=Stuart Elliott|date=May 4, 2010|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] (ASA) in the UK banned some of Proactiv's advertising as misleading. A viewer complained that the celebrities were likely to have used the US version of Proactiv, which differs from the UK version. According to the ASA, the celebrities had signed statements saying they had used the UK version for a few weeks one to three years earlier, but the advertisements gave the appearance that they had continued to benefit from it, so the viewer's complaint was upheld.<ref>[https://www.asa.org.uk/Rulings/Adjudications/2012/7/Guthy_Renker-UK-Ltd/SHP_ADJ_168048.aspx \"ASA Ruling on Guthy-Renker UK Ltd\"], Advertising Standards Authority, July 18, 2012.{{pb}}\n{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/18/katy-perry-justin-bieber|title=Katy Perry and Justin Bieber zit ad campaign banned |author=Mark Sweney |newspaper=The Guardian|date=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{good article}}\n{{portal|Companies}}\n\n[[Category:Acne treatments]]\n[[Category:Direct marketing]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1995]]\n[[Category:Skin care]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox brand\n|name         = Proactiv\n| logo           = File:ProactivLogo.png\n| logo_upright   = upright\n| image          = File:Proactiv three-step kit, June 2013 (cropped).jpg\n| producttype    = Skincare\n| currentowner   = [[Guthy-Renker]]<br> [[Galderma]]<ref name=\"Nestl\u00e9\"/>\n| producedby     =\n| country        = United States\n| introduced     = {{start date and age|1995|10}}\n| markets        = Australasia, Europe, North America, Scandinavia\n| previousowners = [[Katie Rodan]]<br>Kathy Fields\n| ambassadors    = [[Justin Bieber]], [[Sean Combs]], [[Avril Lavigne]] and others\n| tagline        = \"Be Proactiv\"\n| website        = {{URL|proactiv.com}}\n}}\n'''Proactiv''', also known as '''Proactiv Solution''', is a brand of [[Skin care#Skin care products|skin-care products]] developed by two American [[Dermatology|dermatologists]], [[Katie Rodan]] and [[Kathy A. Fields]], and launched in 1995 by [[Guthy-Renker]], a California-based [[direct marketing]] company.<ref>Katie Rodan, Kathy Fields (2008). ''Unblemished'', Simon and Schuster, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=RXRfwjMnl38C&pg=PA4 4\u20138].</ref> The range includes moisturizers, body washes and hair products, but the brand is known for its three-step anti-[[Acne vulgaris|acne]] kit consisting of a cleanser, toner and lotion.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011>John Kraft, Anatoli Freiman (April 19, 2011). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3080563/ \"Management of acne\"], ''Canadian Medical Journal'', 183(7), pp.&nbsp;E430\u2013E435. {{doi|10.1503/cmaj.090374}} {{PMID|21398228}}</ref><ref name=NIH/> Proactiv+, a reformulation of the three-step kit, was introduced in 2013.<ref name=MychaskiwInStyle2013/>\n\nAs a result of its celebrity endorsements and [[infomercial]]s, Proactiv is one of the most popular skincare brands of all time, according to the ''Journal of Clinical and Aesthetic Dermatology''.<ref name=DeckerJCAD2012/> Sales amounted to $800 million a year as of 2010, with a media budget of nearly $200 million and $12\u201315 million for celebrity fees.<ref name=LaceyForbes2010/> The product is mostly sold online as part of a [[Continuity sales model|continuity program]]. A month after ordering, customers are sent a three-month supply, which continues until the subscription is cancelled.<ref name=RomeroABC72011>{{cite news|title=Which Acne Treatment Works Best, Costs Less?|url=http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/consumer&id=8422230|publisher=ABC7|author=Ric Romero|date=November 7, 2011}}</ref> Customers have complained that the subscriptions are hard to cancel.<ref name=truthinadvertising2013/>\n\nAccording to a 2011 [[Review article|review]], there have been few studies on the efficacy of Proactiv.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/> A 2011 ''[[Consumer Reports]]'' study compared Proactiv with two less expensive types of [[benzoyl peroxide]], AcneFree and OXY Maximum, and found all three to be equally effective.<ref name=consumerreports2011/> The US [[Food and Drug Administration]] warned in 2014 that over-the-counter acne treatments can cause severe irritation, as well as rare but life-threatening allergic reactions.<ref name=FDA2014/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Product development===\nProactiv was created in the late 1980s by [[Katie Rodan]] and [[Kathy A. Fields]], who met while at [[Stanford University School of Medicine]].<ref name=R&F2008pp4-7>Rodan and Fields 2008, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=RXRfwjMnl38C&pg=PA4 4\u20137].</ref><ref name=\"EspinozaPeople2002\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20137526,00.html|newspaper=People|title=Saving Face|author=Galina Espinoza|date=July 15, 2002}}</ref>\n\nProactiv was offered to [[Neutrogena]], which declined it, but its CEO, Allan Kurtzman, suggested selling it via infomercials.<ref name=\"EspinozaPeople2002\"/><ref name=R&F2008p8>Rodan and Fields 2008, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=RXRfwjMnl38C&pg=PA8 8].</ref> Guthy-Renker were already in the infomercial business and agreed to market and distribute it. The first infomercial appeared in October 1995, offering a money-back guarantee and fast delivery, and featuring [[Judith Light]], who suffered from acne problems herself.<ref name=R&F2008p8/><ref name=CasserlyForbes2010>{{cite news|author=Meghan Casserly|newspaper=Forbes|date=November 30, 2010|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/meghancasserly/2010/11/30/proactiv-celebrity-endorsement-katy-perry-lindsay-lohan-justin-bieber/|title=Proactiv's Active Ingredient: Celebrity}}</ref> Rodan and Fields later founded their own skincare brand, Rodan + Fields.<ref>Dana Mattioli, Gillian Tan (February 18, 2015). [https://www.wsj.com/articles/skin-care-company-rodan-fields-pursuing-a-sale-1424283321 \"Skin Care Company Rodan & Fields Pursuing a Sale\"], ''Wall Street Journal''.</ref>\n\n===Guthy-Renker===\n[[Guthy-Renker]] LLC is a [[direct-response marketing]] company registered in [[Palm Desert]], California. Founded in 1988 by Bill Guthy and [[Greg Renker]], the company is known as \"the Rolls Royce\" of the infomercial industry.<ref name=ArndorferAA2005/><ref>Bernice Kanner (October 21, 1991). [https://books.google.com/books?id=8ugCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA24 \"30 Minutes: Selling with Infomercials\"], ''New York Magazine.</ref> As of 2012 its portfolio of products was making $1.8 billion a year.<ref name=JohnsonSuccess2012/> The range includes [[Victoria Principal]]'s Principal Secret skincare (its earliest skincare brand), Wen Hair Care, [[Cindy Crawford]]'s Meaningful Beauty skincare, the Dean Martin Celebrity Roast DVDs, and the Malibu Pilates Chair.<ref>[http://www.responsemagazine.com/ims-top-drtv-national-cable-and-satelite-rankings-2 \"The Top DRTV National and Cable Satellite Rankings\"], ''Response Magazine''.</ref><ref name=LunauMacleans2011>Kate Lunau (January 8, 2011). [http://www.macleans.ca/economy/business/pretty-valuable-faces/ \"Pretty valuable faces\"], ''Macleans''.</ref><ref>Charles Wesley Orton (May 2001). [https://webms.guthy-renker.eu/WMS/Upload/WMS_BrandSites/Resources/Guthy-Renker_Europe/Response_Magazine.pdf \"Partners in Time: The Guthy-Renker story\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022235306/https://webms.guthy-renker.eu/WMS/Upload/WMS_BrandSites/Resources/Guthy-Renker_Europe/Response_Magazine.pdf |date=2013-10-22 }}, ''Response Magazine''.</ref>\n\n===Nestl\u00e9===\nIn March 2016, [[Nestl\u00e9]] joined Guthy-Renker as a majority owner of Proactiv. In October 2019, Nestle sold its shares to EQT. <ref name=\"Nestl\u00e9\">{{cite news|last1=Grettler|first1=Corinne|title=Nestle Forms Alliance With Bieber's Fave Acne Cure Proactiv|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-24/nestle-forms-acne-joint-venture-with-maker-of-proactiv-brand|accessdate=April 11, 2016|publisher=Bloomberg|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nProactiv is a registered trademark of Guthy-Renker. The brand's primary product is a three-step kit comprising a cleanser, toner and lotion, which sells for $20 a month in the United States if purchased as part of the continuity program.<ref>{{cite news|title=Acne Treatment Helps Some, Not All|date=January 30, 2003|newspaper=Newsday|author=Joanne Kabak|url=http://www.newsday.com/acne-treatment-helps-some-not-all-1.438693}}</ref>\n\nThe toner contains [[glycolic acid]], an [[Exfoliation (cosmetology)|exfoliant]], and [[witch hazel (astringent)|witch hazel]], an [[astringent]].<ref name=SingerNYT2007/><ref>{{cite news|title=The lucrative business of pimples; Proactiv ad campaign transforms way consumers think about acne|author=Natasha Singer|date=October 19, 2007|pp=D2|newspaper=LIFE}}</ref> The active ingredient in the cleanser and lotion, outside Europe, is a 2.5% concentration of [[benzoyl peroxide]], lower than in most prescription-strength [[Acne vulgaris#Management|acne treatments]].<ref name=\"FiremanDT2011\">{{cite journal | author = Fireman Sharon | year = 2011 | title = A look at emerging delivery systems for topical drug products | url = | journal = Dermatologic Therapy | volume = 24 | issue = 5| pages = 477\u2013488 | doi = 10.1111/j.1529-8019.2012.01464.x | pmid = 22353154 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|John Kraft, Anatoli Freiman (''Canadian Medical Association Journal'', 2011): \"[[Benzoyl peroxide]] is available in various topical preparations, ranging in strength from 2.5% to 10.0%. Any strength can be used initially, although it may be more prudent to start with a lower concentration; stronger preparations are more irritating and not necessarily more effective.\"<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/>}} Benzoyl peroxide has been used since 1934 to kill ''[[Cutibacterium acnes]]'', the bacterium that causes acne.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Fluhr J. W., Degitz K. | year = 2010 | title = Antibiotics, azelaic acid and benzoyl peroxide in topical acne therapy | journal = Journal der Deutschen Dermatologischen Gesellschaft | volume = 8 | issue = S1| pages = S24\u2013S30 | doi = 10.1111/j.1610-0387.2009.07169.x | pmid = 20482689 }}</ref> Several over-the-counter acne treatments contain it, including [[Clean & Clear]], [[Clearasil]], [[List of Procter & Gamble brands#Skin care|Doctor's Dermatologic Formula]], [[Neutrogena|Neutrogena Advanced Systems]], [[Stiefel Laboratories|PanOxyl]] and [[Stridex]].<ref name=ParikhSalon2011/><ref>Jessica Wu (2011). ''Feed Your Face'', Macmillan, p. 70.</ref>\n\nThere is also a three-step program in Extra Strength, with a 7% concentration of benzoyl peroxide,<ref name=\"FiremanDT2011\"/> and a Gentle Formula that instead contains a 2% concentration of [[salicylic acid]], an exfoliant.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/> The three-step kit in Europe is based on salicylic acid; in the UK it costs \u00a339.99 ($60) for a two-month supply.{{refn|group=n|As of 2015 [[Boots UK|Boots the Chemist]] in the UK charges \u00a339.99 ($60) for the Proactiv Solution cleanser (120 ml), toner (120 ml) and lotion (60 ml).<ref name=Boots2015>[http://www.boots.com/en/Proactiv-Solution-3-Step-System-To-Clearer-Healthier-Looking-Skin_1248826/ \"Proactiv Solution 3 Step System To Clearer Healthier Looking Skin\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121160709/http://www.boots.com/en/Proactiv-Solution-3-Step-System-To-Clearer-Healthier-Looking-Skin_1248826 |date=2015-11-21 }}, Boots.</ref>}}<ref>Tamara Hinson (February 16, 2012). [https://uk.lifestyle.yahoo.com/blogs/tamara-hinson/proactive-skincare-arrived-uk-worth-money-125054667.html \"Proactiv skincare has arrived in the UK \u2013 but is it worth your money?\"], ''The Beauty Files'', Yahoo.</ref> Other Proactiv products include an oil-free moisturizer that uses [[octinoxate]] (7.5%) and [[zinc oxide]] (3%), and an anti-dandruff shampoo with a 1% concentration of [[zinc pyrithione]].<ref name=NIH>{{cite web|title=List of Proactiv products and their ingredients|publisher=[[DailyMed]], [[National Institutes of Health]]|url=http://dailymed.nlm.nih.gov/dailymed/search.cfm?query=proactiv&searchdb=all&labeltype=all&sortby=rel&audience=professional&page=1&pagesize=200}}</ref>\n\nGuthy-Renker introduced Proactiv+ in 2013, charging $30 in the United States for a month's supply if the customer creates a subscription. It is a [[paraben]]-free three-step kit comprising a cleanser and toning gel, each with 2.5% benzoyl peroxide, and a moisturizer with salicylic acid. It is reportedly more hydrating than the original program.<ref name=MychaskiwInStyle2013>{{cite web|author=Marianne Mychaskiw|title=Proactiv Launches Proactiv+ Line, More Hydrating Formula|url=http://news.instyle.com/2013/01/29/proactiv-plus-line/|newspaper=InStyle|date=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Safety and efficacy==\n[[File:BenzoperoxideRx.JPG|thumb|A skin reaction from benzoyl peroxide]]\n\nProactiv is aimed at customers with mild to moderate acne.<ref name=SingerNYT2007>Natasha Singer (October 18, 2007). [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/18/fashion/18skin.html  \"Why Should Kids Have All the Acne?\"], ''The New York Times''.</ref> According to a 2011 review, there have been few studies examining its efficacy.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/> A 2007 study saw inflammatory lesions reduced by 39% in subjects using a combination of [[butenafine]] and benzoyl peroxide, compared with 34% in those using Proactiv containing only benzoyl peroxide.<ref name=KraftCMJ2011/><ref name=\"BurkhartBurkhartIJD2007\">{{cite journal|author= Craig G. Burkhart; Craig N. Burkhart|title=Treatment of acne vulgaris without antibiotics: tertiary amine-benzoyl peroxide combination vs. benzoyl peroxide alone (Proactiv Solution?)|journal=International Journal of Dermatology|volume=46|issue=1|year=2007|pages=89\u201393|doi=10.1111/j.1365-4632.2007.03081.x|pmid=17214729}}</ref> A physician suggested in ''Salon'' that its three-step system might make it easier for teenagers to comply, but that the key to its success lay with its celebrity endorsements.<ref name=ParikhSalon2011>{{cite news|date=February 28, 2011|title=Proactiv's celebrity shell game|author=Rahul Parikh|url=http://www.salon.com/2011/02/28/proactiv_celebrity_sham/|newspaper=Salon}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[Consumer Reports]]'' compared Proactiv (2.5% benzoyl peroxide) with two less expensive products, AcneFree (2.5% benzoyl peroxide) and OXY Maximum (10% benzoyl peroxide).<ref name=consumerreports2011/> At the time a two-month supply of Proactiv cost around $40 in the US, AcneFree $20 and OXY Maximum $5.<ref name=RomeroABC72011/> Eighty-three subjects, aged 14 to 40, used one of the products twice a day for eight weeks. The magazine reported that, no matter which product was used, after two weeks around 75% of subjects saw a 35% reduction in blemishes on average. After eight weeks, around 50\u201366% saw a 40% reduction on average.<ref name=consumerreports2011>{{citation|publisher=[[Consumer Reports]]|date=November 2011|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/2011/11/review-of-acne-treatments/index.htm|title=Review of acne treatments}}</ref>\n\nBenzoyl peroxide can have a drying effect on the skin, can cause [[erythema]] (redness) and fine scaling, though these effects are usually mild, and can increase sensitivity to sunlight. One in 500 may experience [[allergic contact dermatitis]]. It is categorized as a [[Pregnancy category#United States|pregnancy category]] C agent, \"suggesting that its use in pregnancy may not be prudent,\" according to a literature review in the ''Journal of Clinical and Aesthetic Dermatology''.{{refn|group=n|Ashley Decker, Emmy M. Graber (''Journal of Clinical and Aesthetic Dermatology'', 2012): \"Since the 1930s, BP [benzoyl peroxide] has been a popular choice for the treatment of AV [acne vulgaris] due to its [[keratolytic]], moderate comedolytic, and [[Antibiotics|antibacterial]] properties, which include the reduction of ''[[Cutibacterium acnes]]'' and ''[[Staphylococcus aureus]]'' on skin. Cutaneous side effects of BP are most often irritant in nature, may be concentration and/or vehicle dependent, and are usually mild, including signs such as dryness, [[erythema]], and fine scaling. A minority of the population treated with BP for AV will experience true [[allergic contact dermatitis]] (1:500). Although available OTC, BP is a [[pregnancy category]] C agent, suggesting that its use in pregnancy may not be prudent.\"<ref name=DeckerJCAD2012>{{cite journal | author = Decker Ashley, Graber Emmy M | year = 2012 | title = Over-the-counter Acne Treatments | journal = Journal of Clinical and Aesthetic Dermatology | volume = 5 | issue = 5| pages = 32\u201340 | pmid = 22808307 | pmc=3366450}}</ref>}} If benzoyl peroxide comes into contact with clothing it is likely to bleach it.<ref>Robert M. Kliegman et al. (2015). ''Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics'', Elsevier Health Sciences, p&nbsp;[https://books.google.com/books?id=mseNCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA3402 3231].<!--Note: the page number in the link and on the page differ.--></ref>\n\nThe US [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) warned in 2014 that over-the-counter acne products containing benzoyl peroxide and/or salicylic acid, including Proactiv, can cause severe irritation, as well as rare but life-threatening allergic reactions. Consumers were advised to stop using the products if they experience hives or itching, and to seek emergency medical attention if they feel faint, or experience throat tightness, breathing problems, or swelling of the eyes, face, lips or tongue. The FDA noted that it remains unclear whether the reactions are caused by the active ingredients, inactive ingredients or a combination.<ref name=FDA2014>[https://www.fda.gov/Safety/MedWatch/SafetyInformation/SafetyAlertsforHumanMedicalProducts/ucm402722.htm \"Over-The-Counter Topical Acne Products: Drug Safety Communication - Rare But Serious Hypersensitivity Reactions\"], Food and Drug Administration, June 25, 2014.{{pb}}\n[https://www.fda.gov/downloads/ForConsumers/ConsumerUpdates/UCM402554.pdf \"Topical Acne Products Can Cause Dangerous Side Effects\"], Food and Drug Administration, June 2014.{{pb}}\n[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/26/business/fda-warns-of-allergy-to-some-anti-acne-products.html \"F.D.A. Warns of Allergy to Some Anti-Acne Products\"], Associated Press, June 25, 2014.{{pb}}\n[https://www.fda.gov/Drugs/GuidanceComplianceRegulatoryInformation/Surveillance/AdverseDrugEffects/ucm376571.htm \"Potential Signals of Serious Risks/New Safety Information Identified by the FDA Adverse Event Reporting System (FAERS) between July \u2013 September 2013\"], Food and Drug Administration, November 1, 2013, updated September 10, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Sales and marketing==\n\n===Sales===\n[[File:Proactiv vending machine, Indianapolis airport, February 2008.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|Proactiv vending machine, [[Indianapolis International Airport]], 2008]]\nProactiv is marketed and distributed by Guthy-Renker, and is responsible for about half the company's revenue.<ref name=ArndorferAA2005>J. B. Arndorfer (May 2, 2005). \"[http://adage.com/article/news/guthy-renker-infomercial-street-cred/103068/ Guthy-Renker gives the infomercial street cred],\" ''Advertising Age'', 76(18).</ref><ref name=JohnsonSuccess2012>{{cite news|author=Emma Johnson|newspaper=Success Magazine|title=As Seen on TV|url=http://www.success.com/articles/1949-------as-seen-on-tv|date=September 10, 2012}}</ref> Sales of Proactiv amounted to $800 million as of 2010.<ref name=LaceyForbes2010/> 70% of sales were in the United States as of 2007.<ref name=SingerNYT2007/>\n\nThe product is available in some stores, including [[Boots UK|Boots]] in the UK,<ref name=Boots2015/> and in kiosks and vending machines (known as [[Zoom Systems|ZoomShops]]) in malls and airports through a partnership between American Kiosk Management and Guthy-Renker .<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/26/business/26vending.html?pagewanted=all|title=The New Touch-Face of Vending Machines|author=Stephanie Rosenbloom|date=May 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=SteinbergWSJ2007>{{citation|title=Questions for ... Greg Renker & Ben Van De Bunt|author=Brian Steinberg|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=April 18, 2007|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB117684790782073165}}</ref> But the product is mostly sold online or through a toll-free number directly by Guthy-Renker; 60% of Proactiv orders were placed online as of 2010.<ref name=NetherbyBillboard20Aug2010/>\n\n===Continuity program===\nGuthy-Renker sells Proactiv as part of a [[Continuity sales model|continuity program]], also known as a [[Negative option billing|negative-option offer]], whereby customers are sent repeat orders until they cancel.<ref name=RomeroABC72011/><ref name=truthinadvertising2013>[https://www.truthinadvertising.org/five-common-complaints-about-guthy-renker/ \"Five Common Complaints about Guthy-Renker\"], [[Truth in Advertising (organization)|Truth in Advertising]], June 25, 2013.</ref> When purchasing directly from the company, customers automatically become members of a Proactiv club. A month after ordering, and every three months thereafter, they are sent a three-month supply costing $60 (in the US as of 2011), plus shipping and handling.<ref name=RomeroABC72011/> They are billed monthly until they cancel the subscription.<ref>Lynda Steele (November 9, 2011). [http://bc.ctvnews.ca/testing-star-endorsed-proactiv-1.722916 \"Testing star-endorsed Proactiv\"], CTV News.</ref> The approach is based on the [[customer lifetime value]] model.<ref>{{cite book|author=Josh Kaufman|title=The Personal MBA: Master the Art of Business|date=2010|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-101-44608-9|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=_DZ_AMDl5yUC&pg=PT196 196]}}</ref>\n\nCustomers have complained that they have created subscriptions inadvertently and found them difficult to cancel.<ref>[[Amanda Marcotte]] (January 14, 2013). [http://www.slate.com/blogs/xx_factor/2013/01/14/proactiv_acne_system_may_be_bad_for_consumers_nothing_special_for_your_skin.html \"Don't Bother With Proactiv\"], ''Slate''.{{pb}}\nJennifer Abel (September 13, 2013). [http://www.consumeraffairs.com/news/acnes-hard-to-get-rid-of-so-is-proactiv-091313.html \"Acne's hard to get rid of; so is Proactiv\"], ConsumerAffairs.{{pb}}\nKatie J. M. Baker (January 11, 2013). [http://jezebel.com/5975176/proactiv-horror-stories-tales-from-skincares-big-scam \"Proactiv Horror Stories: Tales From Skincare's Big Scam\"], ''Jezebel''.{{pb}}\nKatie J. M. Baker (January 4, 2013). [http://jezebel.com/5972898/why-is-it-so-hard-to-quit-proactiv \"Why Is It So Hard to Quit Proactiv?\"], ''Jezebel''.{{pb}}\nRob Walker (June 12, 2005). [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/12/magazine/12CONSUMED.html \"The Celebrity Solution\"], ''The New York Times''.</ref> The most common complaints about Guthy-Renker, according to [[Truth in Advertising (organization)|Truth in Advertising]], are unauthorized billing, difficulty cancelling orders, billing for products that never arrive, unhelpful customer service, and refusing refunds despite money-back guarantees.<ref name=truthinadvertising2013/>\n\n===Commercials===\nGuthy-Renker had a media budget of $200 million for Proactive as of 2010, much of it spent on air-time, and was spending another $12\u201315 million a year on celebrity endorsements.<ref name=LaceyForbes2010>{{cite news|newspaper=Forbes|date=November 3, 2010|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2010/1122/private-companies-10-guthy-renker-media-shill-shocked.html|title=Shill Shocked|author=Rose Lacey}}</ref> [[Justin Bieber]] for example, was paid $3 million over two years.<ref name=NetherbyBillboard20Aug2010>{{cite news|title=Justin Bieber Joins Proactiv's Zit-Geist |newspaper=Billboard|author=Jennifer Netherby |date=August 20, 2010|url=http://www.billboard.com/features/justin-bieber-joins-proactiv-s-zit-geist-1004110497.story#/features/justin-bieber-joins-proactiv-s-zit-geist-1004110497.story}}</ref> Its infomercials have featured celebrities who have themselves suffered from acne problems; the list includes [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[P. Diddy]], [[Avril Lavigne]], [[Lindsay Lohan]], [[Alyssa Milano]], [[Katy Perry]], [[Jessica Simpson]], [[Britney Spears]] and [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]].<ref name=CasserlyForbes2010/>\n\nAccording to the ''New York Times'', until 2010 Proactiv infomercials were \"fast-talking\" and \"hard-selling\"; an announcer repeatedly advised viewers to \"call now,\" and offered faster shipping if the order was placed within three minutes. As infomercials became less popular, Proactiv sales stalled.<ref name=ElliottNYT2010/> Since 2010 Guthy-Renker has tried to move the brand into the mainstream cosmetics market, focusing on quality rather than price.<ref name=LaceyForbes2010/> It began advertising on network television during shows like [[American Idol]], and in ''Elle'', ''InStyle'' and ''People'' magazines.<ref name=ElliottNYT2010>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/04/business/media/04adco.html|title=Trying to Move Up From a Fast-Talking, Buy-Now Approach|author=Stuart Elliott|date=May 4, 2010|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] (ASA) in the UK banned some of Proactiv's advertising as misleading. A viewer complained that the celebrities were likely to have used the US version of Proactiv, which differs from the UK version. According to the ASA, the celebrities had signed statements saying they had used the UK version for a few weeks one to three years earlier, but the advertisements gave the appearance that they had continued to benefit from it, so the viewer's complaint was upheld.<ref>[https://www.asa.org.uk/Rulings/Adjudications/2012/7/Guthy_Renker-UK-Ltd/SHP_ADJ_168048.aspx \"ASA Ruling on Guthy-Renker UK Ltd\"], Advertising Standards Authority, July 18, 2012.{{pb}}\n{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/18/katy-perry-justin-bieber|title=Katy Perry and Justin Bieber zit ad campaign banned |author=Mark Sweney |newspaper=The Guardian|date=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{good article}}\n{{portal|Companies}}\n\n[[Category:Acne treatments]]\n[[Category:Direct marketing]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1995]]\n[[Category:Skin care]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proactiv"}
{"title_page": "Matur Maker", "text_new": "{{About|the professional basketball player|his cousin|Makur Maker}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Matur Maker\n| image =\n| caption = \n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]] / [[Center (basketball)|Center]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 205\n| league =[[NBA G League]]\n| team = Rio Grande Valley Vipers\n| number = 8\n| nationality = Australian / South Sudanese\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1998|1|1}}\n| birth_place = [[Sudan]] <small>(now [[South Sudan]])</small>\n| high_school = \n*[[Carlisle School]]<br>([[Martinsville, Virginia]])\n*[[Orangeville District Secondary School|Orangeville Prep]]<br>([[Orangeville, Ontario]])\n*Prolific Prep North<br>([[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario]])\n*[[Mississauga Secondary School|Mississauga Prep]]<br>([[Mississauga|Mississauga, Ontario]])\n<!--Do not add the Athlete Institute in Mono, Ontario as well since students in Orangeville Prep also play in the Athlete Institute by extension.-->\n| draft_year = 2019\n| career_start = 2018\n| years1 = 2018\n| team1 = [[Union Neuch\u00e2tel Basket|Union Neuch\u00e2tel]]\n| years2 = 2018\u20132019\n| team2 = [[KK Zlatorog La\u0161ko|Zlatorog La\u0161ko]]\n| years3 = 2019\u2013present\n| team3 = [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]]\n| highlights =\n*[[BioSteel All-Canadian Game]] MVP (2017)\n}}\n'''Matur Maker''' (born 1 January 1998) is a South Sudanese-born Australian [[basketball]] player for the [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]] of the [[NBA G League]]. He moved to Australia in his childhood and played for various prep schools in Canada and the United States. Maker was ranked among the top [[power forward (basketball)|power forwards]] in his class but chose to skip college and play professionally. He is the younger cousin of [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) player [[Thon Maker]].\n\n== Early life ==\nMaker was born in what is now known as [[South Sudan]] on 1 January 1998, with his older brother [[Thon Maker]].<ref name=\"follow\">{{cite web|last1=Campbell|first1=Morgan|title=Matur Maker hopes to follow brother Thon straight to the NBA|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/basketball/2018/01/11/matur-maker-hopes-to-follow-brother-thon-straight-to-the-nba.html|website=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=11 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nbadraftnet\">{{cite web|title=Matur Maker|url=http://www.nbadraft.net/players/matur-maker|website=NBADraft.net|accessdate=18 February 2018}}</ref> In Matur's early childhood, his uncle, a local administrator, helped the family flee to [[Uganda]] amid a [[Second Sudanese Civil War|civil war]] in their home country.<ref name=\"impressed\">{{cite web|last1=Uluc|first1=Olgun|title=NBA scouts impressed by Matur Maker, the younger brother of Milwaukee Bucks big man Thon Maker|url=https://thewest.com.au/sport/basketball/nba-scouts-impressed-by-matur-maker-the-younger-brother-of-milwaukee-bucks-big-man-thon-maker-ng-b88561940z|website=[[The West Australian]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=8 August 2017}}</ref> They then settled in [[Perth|Perth, Western Australia]] as refugees but continued making occasional visits to South Sudan.<ref name=ahead/><ref name=\"smh\">{{cite web|last1=Sygall|first1=David|title=Refugees escaping war are aiming for the stars|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/basketball/refugees-escaping-war-are-aiming-for-the-stars-20130810-2rovx.html|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=11 August 2013}}</ref> Matur first started playing soccer at Grayhounds soccer club, a club where many south Sudanese kids played for and alongside his brother Thon. At age 13, Matur was discovered by basketball scout Edward Smith and began living with him in [[Sydney]], before moving to the United States.<ref name=\"thonschoolboy\">{{cite web|last1=Croy|first1=Liam|title=Mirrabooka schoolboy Thon Maker to play in the NBA|url=https://thewest.com.au/news/wa/mirrabooka-schoolboy-thon-maker-to-play-in-the-nba-ng-ya-110842|website=[[The West Australian]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=23 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ahead\">{{cite web|last1=Bozich|first1=Alex|title=\u201cBest basketball ahead\u201d for 2017\u2019s Matur Maker|url=http://www.insidethehall.com/2014/05/21/best-basketball-ahead-2017s-matur-maker/|website=InsideTheHall.com|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=21 May 2014}}</ref> After his parents were satisfied by the decision, Matur was allowed to join his brother in high school and Smith eventually became their [[legal guardian]].<ref name=ahead/>\n\n== High school career ==\nMaker began playing high school basketball as a freshman at [[Carlisle School]] in [[Martinsville, Virginia]], where he joined Thon, a sophomore, in the middle of the season.<ref name=\"jordan\">{{cite web|last1=Halley|first1=Jim|title=Jordan Classic: Matur Maker a big part of brother Thon's possible reclassifcation decision|url=http://usatodayhss.com/2015/younger-maker-a-big-part-of-his-brothers-possible-reclassifcation-decision|website=USATodayHSS.com|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=27 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bypass\">{{cite web|last1=Daniels|first1=Evan|title=Matur Maker, Thon's brother, will bypass college to go pro|url=https://247sports.com/Article/Matur-Maker-Thons-brother-will-bypass-college-to-go-pro-113259321|website=[[247Sports.com]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> His guardian Edward Smith, who the brothers lived with in a two-story house, was an assistant coach for the team at the time.<ref name=jordan/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Mannix|first1=Chris|title=Maker's Lark|url=https://www.si.com/vault/2014/04/14/106453260/makers-lark|website=[[Sports Illustrated]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=14 April 2014}}</ref> According to Smith, Matur's arrival at Carlisle helped Thon better acclimate to the United States.<ref name=jordan/> During his freshman season, Matur was considered one of the best high school players in the country at the [[small forward]] position.<ref name=\"nola\">{{cite web|last1=Gretschel|first1=Johanna|title=Former local player, top national prospect Thon Maker to transfer|url=http://highschoolsports.nola.com/news/article/3270439919825155606/former-local-player-top-national-prospect-thon-maker-to-transfer/|website=[[The Times-Picayune]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=3 September 2014}}</ref> He helped Carlisle win a state championship and played with Team Loaded VA of the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU).<ref name=\"enroll\">{{cite web|last1=Wolstat|first1=Ryan|title=World's top basketball prospect Canada-bound|url=http://torontosun.com/2014/09/04/worlds-top-basketball-prospect-canada-bound/wcm/ff1e1b14-42f4-4684-a75a-e75856c113c8|website=[[Toronto Sun]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor his sophomore year, Maker transferred from Carlisle, with [[Hopewell Academy]] in [[Cary, North Carolina]] and [[Orangeville District Secondary School|Orangeville Prep]] in [[Orangeville, Ontario]] as potential destinations.<ref name=nola/> In September 2014, Maker and his brother enrolled at Orangeville Prep, where they played under head coach Larry Blunt and with fellow top prospect [[Jamal Murray]].<ref name=enroll/> He was named Ontario Scholastic Basketball Association (OSBA) second-team all-star.<ref name=\"landscape\">{{cite web|last1=Ebner|first1=David|title=Choosing Canada: The rapidly changing landscape of elite teenage basketball|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/basketball/choosing-canada-the-rapidly-changing-landscape-of-elite-teenage-basketball/article31689155/|website=[[The Globe and Mail]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016\u201317, Maker moved to Prolific Prep North in [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario]], where he was coached by his guardian Edward Smith and became teammates with cousin Makur Makur.<ref name=\"makur\">{{cite web|title=Thon Maker's 6-11 cousin joins Prolific Prep North in Canada|url=http://usatodayhss.com/2016/thon-makers-6-11-cousin-joins-prolific-prep-north-in-canada|website=USATodayHSS.com|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=29 September 2016}}</ref> With the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] having selected Thon at the [[2016 NBA draft]], the transfer allowed Matur to live closer to his brother.<ref name=landscape/> In April 2017, Maker competed in the [[BioSteel All-Canadian Basketball Game]] in [[Toronto]], where he was named most valuable player.<ref name=\"biosteel\">{{cite web|last1=Kent|first1=Austin|title=2017 BioSteel All Canadian Basketball Game Top Performers|url=http://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/2017-biosteel-canadian-basketball-game-top-performers/|website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=11 April 2017}}</ref> In the game, he recorded 25 points and six rebounds, shooting 8-of-11 from the field, playing only 12 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matur Maker Game Logs|url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Matur-Maker/GameLogs/72278/Special/2017|website=[[RealGM]]|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref> At an [[adidas]] Nations event in August, he averaged 26 points and seven rebounds for the Asia Pacific team.<ref name=skipcollege/>\n\nMaker played a postgraduate season of basketball at [[Mississauga Secondary School|Mississauga Prep]] in [[Mississauga, Ontario]] for 2017\u201318.<ref name=skipcollege/> By 2018, he was averaging 25.5 points, 11.3 rebounds, 2.8 assists, 2.1 blocks and 1.7 steals.<ref name=\"zags\">{{cite web|last1=Zagoria|first1=Adam|title=Matur Maker hoping to follow older brother Thon Maker\u2019s prep-to-pros route to the NBA|url=http://www.zagsblog.com/2018/01/05/matur-maker-hoping-follow-older-brother-thon-makers-prep-pros-route-nba/|website=ZagsBlog.com|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> On 5 January 2018, Maker declared intentions to bypass college and enter the [[2018 NBA draft]], attempting to follow a similar path as his brother in 2016.<ref name=\"skipcollege\">{{cite web|last1=Borzello|first1=Jeff|title=Matur Maker to skip college, enter NBA draft|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/21972366/matur-maker-skip-college-enter-nba-draft|website=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=5 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Nathan|first1=Alec|title=Thon Maker's Brother Matur to Skip College, Apply for 2018 NBA Draft|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2752643-thon-makers-brother-matur-to-skip-college-apply-for-2018-nba-draft|website=[[Bleacher Report]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> He drew attention from scouts on 11 January, when he notched 45 points, 20 rebounds, two blocks, and three steals in a 95\u201385 defeat to GTA Prep.<ref name=zags/> However, due to a lack of attention on his name during the [[2018 NBA Draft]] process, he withdrew his name from the 2018 NBA draft on the 11 June international deadline.\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2018}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = Matur Maker\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|PF]]\n| hometown = [[Orangeville, Ontario|Orangeville]] (ON)\n| highschool = [[Mississauga Secondary School|Mississauga Prep]] (ON)\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 9.7\n| weight = 193.3\n| 40     =\n| commitdate = \u2014\n| rivals stars = 4\n| 247 stars = 3\n| espn stars = 4\n| espn grade = 80\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40               =\n| year             = 2017\n| rivals ref title = \n| scout ref title  = \n| espn ref title   =  \n| espn schoolid    = \n| 247 overall      = 155, 39 (PF)\n| rivals overall   = \n| accessdate       = 18 February 2018\n| bball            = yes\n}}\n\n== Professional career ==\n===Union Neuch\u00e2tel (2018)===\nOn 7 August 2018, Maker signed with [[Union Neuch\u00e2tel Basket|Union Neuch\u00e2tel]] of the [[Swiss Basketball League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Matur Maker signs with Union Neuchatel |url=https://sportando.basketball/en/europe/switzerland/284874/matur-maker-signs-with-union-neuchatel.html |publisher=Sportando |accessdate=7 August 2018 |date=7 August 2018}}</ref> Through 4 appearances, he averaged 5.8 points, 3.8 rebounds, and 0.8 assists in 13.9 minutes per game.<ref name=\"realgm\">{{cite web |title=Matur Maker Player Profile |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Matur-Maker/Summary/72278 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Zlatorog La\u0161ko (2018\u20132019)===\nOn 30 December 2018, Maker signed with [[KK Zlatorog La\u0161ko|Zlatorog La\u0161ko]] of the [[Premier A Slovenian Basketball League|Slovenian Basketball League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Matur Maker (ex Neuchatel) agreed terms with Zlatorog |url=https://www.eurobasket.com/Slovenia/news/561138/Matur-Maker-(ex-Neuchatel)-agreed-terms-with-Zlatorog |publisher=[[Eurobasket.com]] |accessdate=6 February 2019 |date=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Rio Grande Valley Vipers (2019\u2013present)===\nOn October 19, 2019, Maker signed with the [[Houston Rockets]] of the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]],<ref name=\"Matur-Maker\">{{cite web|title=Official Roster Updates:   The Rockets have waived guard Michael Frazier and forward Jaron Blossomgame.  The team has signed free agent forward Matur Maker.|url=https://twitter.com/HoustonRockets/status/1185190969655910400|website=Houston Rockets on Twitter|accessdate=October 21, 2019|date=October 18, 2019}}</ref> but was waived the next day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rockets Waive Ray Spalding, Two Others|url=https://www.hoopsrumors.com/2019/10/rockets-waive-ray-spalding-two-others.html|website=Hoops Rumors|accessdate=October 21, 2019|date=October 19, 2019}}</ref> Following this, Maker was added to the roster of the Rockets' [[NBA G League]] affiliate, the [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Vipers Finaliz Training Camp Roster |url= https://riograndevalley.gleague.nba.com/news/vipers-finalize-training-camp-roster/ |accessdate=November 2, 2019 |work=[[NBA.com]] |date=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://basketball.usbasket.com/player/Matur-Maker/Canada/Prolific-Prep-North/332913 Matur Maker] at [[Eurobasket.com]]\n*[https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Matur-Maker/Summary/72278 Matur Maker] at [[RealGM]]\n\n{{Rio Grande Valley Vipers current roster}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maker, Matur}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate basketball people in Canada]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Australian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Australian people of South Sudanese descent]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Dinka people]]\n[[Category:Expatriate basketball people in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate basketball people in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:KK Zlatorog La\u0161ko players]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Rio Grande Valley Vipers players]]\n[[Category:South Sudanese expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:South Sudanese expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:South Sudanese men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Union Neuch\u00e2tel Basket players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{About|the professional basketball player|his cousin|Makur Maker}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Matur Maker\n| image =\n| caption = \n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]] / [[Center (basketball)|Center]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 205\n| league =[[NBA G League]]\n| team = Rio Grande Valley Vipers\n| number = 8\n| nationality = Australian / South Sudanese\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1998|1|1}}\n| birth_place = [[Sudan]] <small>(now [[South Sudan]])</small>\n| high_school = \n*[[Carlisle School]]<br>([[Martinsville, Virginia]])\n*[[Orangeville District Secondary School|Orangeville Prep]]<br>([[Orangeville, Ontario]])\n*Prolific Prep North<br>([[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario]])\n*[[Mississauga Secondary School|Mississauga Prep]]<br>([[Mississauga|Mississauga, Ontario]])\n<!--Do not add the Athlete Institute in Mono, Ontario as well since students in Orangeville Prep also play in the Athlete Institute by extension.-->\n| draft_year = 2019\n| career_start = 2018\n| years1 = 2018\n| team1 = [[Union Neuch\u00e2tel Basket|Union Neuch\u00e2tel]]\n| years2 = 2018\u20132019\n| team2 = [[KK Zlatorog La\u0161ko|Zlatorog La\u0161ko]]\n| years3 = 2019\u2013present\n| team3 = [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]]\n| highlights =\n*[[BioSteel All-Canadian Game]] MVP (2017)\n}}\n'''Matur Maker''' (born 1 January 1998) is a South Sudanese-born Australian [[basketball]] player for the [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]] of the [[NBA G League]]. He moved to Australia in his childhood and played for various prep schools in Canada and the United States. Maker was ranked among the top [[power forward (basketball)|power forwards]] in his class but chose to skip college and play professionally. He is the younger cousin of [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) player [[Thon Maker]].\n\n== Early life ==\nMaker was born in what is now known as [[South Sudan]] on 1 January 1998, with his older brother [[Thon Maker]].<ref name=\"follow\">{{cite web|last1=Campbell|first1=Morgan|title=Matur Maker hopes to follow brother Thon straight to the NBA|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/basketball/2018/01/11/matur-maker-hopes-to-follow-brother-thon-straight-to-the-nba.html|website=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=11 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nbadraftnet\">{{cite web|title=Matur Maker|url=http://www.nbadraft.net/players/matur-maker|website=NBADraft.net|accessdate=18 February 2018}}</ref> In Matur's early childhood, his uncle, a local administrator, helped the family flee to [[Uganda]] amid a [[Second Sudanese Civil War|civil war]] in their home country.<ref name=\"impressed\">{{cite web|last1=Uluc|first1=Olgun|title=NBA scouts impressed by Matur Maker, the younger brother of Milwaukee Bucks big man Thon Maker|url=https://thewest.com.au/sport/basketball/nba-scouts-impressed-by-matur-maker-the-younger-brother-of-milwaukee-bucks-big-man-thon-maker-ng-b88561940z|website=[[The West Australian]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=8 August 2017}}</ref> They then settled in [[Perth|Perth, Western Australia]] as refugees but continued making occasional visits to South Sudan.<ref name=ahead/><ref name=\"smh\">{{cite web|last1=Sygall|first1=David|title=Refugees escaping war are aiming for the stars|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/basketball/refugees-escaping-war-are-aiming-for-the-stars-20130810-2rovx.html|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=11 August 2013}}</ref> Matur first started playing soccer at Grayhounds soccer club, a club where many south Sudanese kids played for and along side his brother Thon. At age 13, Matur was discovered by basketball scout Edward Smith and began living with him in [[Sydney]], before moving to the United States.<ref name=\"thonschoolboy\">{{cite web|last1=Croy|first1=Liam|title=Mirrabooka schoolboy Thon Maker to play in the NBA|url=https://thewest.com.au/news/wa/mirrabooka-schoolboy-thon-maker-to-play-in-the-nba-ng-ya-110842|website=[[The West Australian]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=23 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ahead\">{{cite web|last1=Bozich|first1=Alex|title=\u201cBest basketball ahead\u201d for 2017\u2019s Matur Maker|url=http://www.insidethehall.com/2014/05/21/best-basketball-ahead-2017s-matur-maker/|website=InsideTheHall.com|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=21 May 2014}}</ref> After his parents were satisfied by the decision, Matur was allowed to join his brother in high school and Smith eventually became their [[legal guardian]].<ref name=ahead/>\n\n== High school career ==\nMaker began playing high school basketball as a freshman at [[Carlisle School]] in [[Martinsville, Virginia]], where he joined Thon, a sophomore, in the middle of the season.<ref name=\"jordan\">{{cite web|last1=Halley|first1=Jim|title=Jordan Classic: Matur Maker a big part of brother Thon's possible reclassifcation decision|url=http://usatodayhss.com/2015/younger-maker-a-big-part-of-his-brothers-possible-reclassifcation-decision|website=USATodayHSS.com|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=27 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bypass\">{{cite web|last1=Daniels|first1=Evan|title=Matur Maker, Thon's brother, will bypass college to go pro|url=https://247sports.com/Article/Matur-Maker-Thons-brother-will-bypass-college-to-go-pro-113259321|website=[[247Sports.com]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> His guardian Edward Smith, who the brothers lived with in a two-story house, was an assistant coach for the team at the time.<ref name=jordan/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Mannix|first1=Chris|title=Maker's Lark|url=https://www.si.com/vault/2014/04/14/106453260/makers-lark|website=[[Sports Illustrated]]|accessdate=18 February 2018|date=14 April 2014}}</ref> According to Smith, Matur's arrival at Carlisle helped Thon better acclimate to the United States.<ref name=jordan/> During his freshman season, Matur was considered one of the best high school players in the country at the [[small forward]] position.<ref name=\"nola\">{{cite web|last1=Gretschel|first1=Johanna|title=Former local player, top national prospect Thon Maker to transfer|url=http://highschoolsports.nola.com/news/article/3270439919825155606/former-local-player-top-national-prospect-thon-maker-to-transfer/|website=[[The Times-Picayune]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=3 September 2014}}</ref> He helped Carlisle win a state championship and played with Team Loaded VA of the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU).<ref name=\"enroll\">{{cite web|last1=Wolstat|first1=Ryan|title=World's top basketball prospect Canada-bound|url=http://torontosun.com/2014/09/04/worlds-top-basketball-prospect-canada-bound/wcm/ff1e1b14-42f4-4684-a75a-e75856c113c8|website=[[Toronto Sun]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor his sophomore year, Maker transfered from Carlisle, with [[Hopewell Academy]] in [[Cary, North Carolina]] and [[Orangeville District Secondary School|Orangeville Prep]] in [[Orangeville, Ontario]] as potential destinations.<ref name=nola/> In September 2014, Maker and his brother enrolled at Orangeville Prep, where they played under head coach Larry Blunt and with fellow top prospect [[Jamal Murray]].<ref name=enroll/> He was named Ontario Scholastic Basketball Association (OSBA) second-team all-star.<ref name=\"landscape\">{{cite web|last1=Ebner|first1=David|title=Choosing Canada: The rapidly changing landscape of elite teenage basketball|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/basketball/choosing-canada-the-rapidly-changing-landscape-of-elite-teenage-basketball/article31689155/|website=[[The Globe and Mail]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016\u201317, Maker moved to Prolific Prep North in [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario]], where he was coached by his guardian Edward Smith and became teammates with cousin Makur Makur.<ref name=\"makur\">{{cite web|title=Thon Maker's 6-11 cousin joins Prolific Prep North in Canada|url=http://usatodayhss.com/2016/thon-makers-6-11-cousin-joins-prolific-prep-north-in-canada|website=USATodayHSS.com|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=29 September 2016}}</ref> With the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] having selected Thon at the [[2016 NBA draft]], the transfer allowed Matur to live closer to his brother.<ref name=landscape/> In April 2017, Maker competed in the [[BioSteel All-Canadian Basketball Game]] in [[Toronto]], where he was named most valuable player.<ref name=\"biosteel\">{{cite web|last1=Kent|first1=Austin|title=2017 BioSteel All Canadian Basketball Game Top Performers|url=http://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/high-school/2017-biosteel-canadian-basketball-game-top-performers/|website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=11 April 2017}}</ref> In the game, he recorded 25 points and six rebounds, shooting 8-of-11 from the field, playing only 12 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matur Maker Game Logs|url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Matur-Maker/GameLogs/72278/Special/2017|website=[[RealGM]]|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref> At an [[Adidas|adidas]] Nations event in August, he averaged 26 points and seven rebounds for the Asia Pacific team.<ref name=skipcollege/>\n\nMaker played a postgraduate season of basketball at [[Mississauga Secondary School|Mississauga Prep]] in [[Mississauga, Ontario]] for 2017\u201318.<ref name=skipcollege/> By 2018, he was averaging 25.5 points, 11.3 rebounds, 2.8 assists, 2.1 blocks and 1.7 steals.<ref name=\"zags\">{{cite web|last1=Zagoria|first1=Adam|title=Matur Maker hoping to follow older brother Thon Maker\u2019s prep-to-pros route to the NBA|url=http://www.zagsblog.com/2018/01/05/matur-maker-hoping-follow-older-brother-thon-makers-prep-pros-route-nba/|website=ZagsBlog.com|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> On 5 January 2018, Maker declared intentions to bypass college and enter the [[2018 NBA draft]], attempting to follow a similar path as his brother in 2016.<ref name=\"skipcollege\">{{cite web|last1=Borzello|first1=Jeff|title=Matur Maker to skip college, enter NBA draft|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/21972366/matur-maker-skip-college-enter-nba-draft|website=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=5 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Nathan|first1=Alec|title=Thon Maker's Brother Matur to Skip College, Apply for 2018 NBA Draft|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2752643-thon-makers-brother-matur-to-skip-college-apply-for-2018-nba-draft|website=[[Bleacher Report]]|accessdate=19 February 2018|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> He drew attention from scouts on 11 January, when he notched 45 points, 20 rebounds, two blocks, and three steals in a 95\u201385 defeat to GTA Prep.<ref name=zags/> However, due to a lack of attention on his name during the [[2018 NBA Draft]] process, he withdrew his name from the 2018 NBA draft on the 11 June international deadline.\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2018}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = Matur Maker\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|PF]]\n| hometown = [[Orangeville, Ontario|Orangeville]] (ON)\n| highschool = [[Mississauga Secondary School|Mississauga Prep]] (ON)\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 9.7\n| weight = 193.3\n| 40     =\n| commitdate = \u2014\n| rivals stars = 4\n| 247 stars = 3\n| espn stars = 4\n| espn grade = 80\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40               =\n| year             = 2017\n| rivals ref title = \n| scout ref title  = \n| espn ref title   =  \n| espn schoolid    = \n| 247 overall      = 155, 39 (PF)\n| rivals overall   = \n| accessdate       = 18 February 2018\n| bball            = yes\n}}\n\n== Professional career ==\n===Union Neuch\u00e2tel (2018)===\nOn 7 August 2018, Maker signed with [[Union Neuch\u00e2tel Basket|Union Neuch\u00e2tel]] of the [[Swiss Basketball League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Matur Maker signs with Union Neuchatel |url=https://sportando.basketball/en/europe/switzerland/284874/matur-maker-signs-with-union-neuchatel.html |publisher=Sportando |accessdate=7 August 2018 |date=7 August 2018}}</ref> Through 4 appearances, he averaged 5.8 points, 3.8 rebounds, and 0.8 assists in 13.9 minutes per game.<ref name=\"realgm\">{{cite web |title=Matur Maker Player Profile |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Matur-Maker/Summary/72278 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Zlatorog La\u0161ko (2018\u20132019)===\nOn 30 December 2018, Maker signed with [[KK Zlatorog La\u0161ko|Zlatorog La\u0161ko]] of the [[Premier A Slovenian Basketball League|Slovenian Basketball League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Matur Maker (ex Neuchatel) agreed terms with Zlatorog |url=https://www.eurobasket.com/Slovenia/news/561138/Matur-Maker-(ex-Neuchatel)-agreed-terms-with-Zlatorog |publisher=[[Eurobasket.com]] |accessdate=6 February 2019 |date=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Rio Grande Valley Vipers (2019\u2013present)===\nOn October 19, 2019, Maker signed with the [[Houston Rockets]] of the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]],<ref name=\"Matur-Maker\">{{cite web|title=Official Roster Updates:   The Rockets have waived guard Michael Frazier and forward Jaron Blossomgame.  The team has signed free agent forward Matur Maker.|url=https://twitter.com/HoustonRockets/status/1185190969655910400|website=Houston Rockets on Twitter|accessdate=October 21, 2019|date=October 18, 2019}}</ref> but was waived the next day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rockets Waive Ray Spalding, Two Others|url=https://www.hoopsrumors.com/2019/10/rockets-waive-ray-spalding-two-others.html|website=Hoops Rumors|accessdate=October 21, 2019|date=October 19, 2019}}</ref> Following this, Maker was added to the roster of the Rockets' [[NBA G League]] affiliate, the [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Vipers Finaliz Training Camp Roster |url= https://riograndevalley.gleague.nba.com/news/vipers-finalize-training-camp-roster/ |accessdate=November 2, 2019 |work=[[NBA.com]] |date=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://basketball.usbasket.com/player/Matur-Maker/Canada/Prolific-Prep-North/332913 Matur Maker] at [[Eurobasket.com]]\n*[https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Matur-Maker/Summary/72278 Matur Maker] at [[RealGM]]\n\n{{Rio Grande Valley Vipers current roster}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maker, Matur}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate basketball people in Canada]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian expatr