{"title_page": "Whiteboard", "text_new": "{{about|physical whiteboards|software-based wipeboards|Wipeboarding}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2007}}\n[[File:Blank whiteboard.JPG|thumb|A blank whiteboard]]\n[[File:NCTR Intern Claire Boyle (15558843862).jpg|thumb|Researcher writing on a whiteboard]]\n\nA '''whiteboard''' (also known by the terms '''marker board''', '''dry-erase board''', '''wipe board''', '''dry-wipe board''', and '''pen-board''') is a glossy, usually white surface for making nonpermanent markings (an evolved version of the blackboard). Whiteboards are analogous to [[blackboard]]s, but with a smoother surface allowing rapid marking and erasing of markings on their surface. The popularity of whiteboards increased rapidly in the mid-1990s and they have become a fixture in many offices, meeting rooms, school classrooms, and other work environments.\n\nThe term ''whiteboard'' is also used metaphorically to refer to features of computer software applications that simulate whiteboards. Such \"virtual tech whiteboards\" allow one or more people to write or draw images on a simulated canvas. This is a common feature of many virtual meeting, [[collaborative software|collaboration]], and [[instant messaging]] applications. The term ''whiteboard'' is also used to refer to [[interactive whiteboard]]s.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Combo whiteboard and bulletin board.JPG|thumb|A combination whiteboard and cork [[bulletin board]]]]\n[[File:Plasti-slate 001.jpg|thumb|Original early 1960s ad for \"Plasti-slate\", the first whiteboard/dry erase board invented by Martin Heit]]\n\nAlbert Stallion invented whiteboards while working at Alliance in the 1960s. Alliance (now known as [[PolyVision (company)|PolyVision]]) produced enameled steel for architectural cladding, but Stallion noted it could also potentially be used as a writing surface. Stallion later left Alliance to form his own whiteboard production company, MagiBoards.<ref name=\"Whiteboards History\">{{cite web |last=McClean |first=Garry |title=Whiteboards History |url=http://www.theworkplacedepot.co.uk/news/2014/08/20/whiteboards-history/ |work=The Workplace Depot |access-date=24 October 2016 |date=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Company Overview of Alliance International Group |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=24608 |work=[[Bloomberg.com]] |access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Magiboards 1966 Door Sign.JPG|thumb|Door sign to the offices of Magiboards at The Cut in Waterloo, London, in 1966. Made of enameled steel]]\n\nWhiteboards became commercially available in the early 1960s, but did not become widely used until 30 years later. Early whiteboards needed to be wiped with a damp cloth and markers had a tendency to leave marks behind, even after erasing the board.<ref name=\"Whiteboards History\"/><ref name=\"History of Whiteboard Learning\">{{cite web |title=The History of Whiteboard Learning |url=https://www.magnatag.com/blog/2014/12/17/the-history-of-whiteboard-learning/ |work=Magnatag Visible Systems |access-date=24 October 2016 |date=17 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111005636/https://www.magnatag.com/blog/2014/12/17/the-history-of-whiteboard-learning/ |archive-date=11 January 2017 |first=Tom |last=Shaw}}</ref> Dry-erase markers for whiteboards were invented in 1975.<ref name=\"Whiteboards History\"/>\n\nWhiteboards started becoming commonly used by businesses in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/11/12/google-releases-jamboard-a-high-tech-whiteboard-for-office-meetings.html |title=Google releases Jamboard, a high-tech whiteboard for office meetings |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |date=November 12, 2016 |page=B4 |first=Steven |last=Overly |access-date=9 March 2019 |publisher=[[Toronto Star Newspapers Ltd.]]}}</ref> They became more common in classrooms during the 1990s due to concerns over health problems in children with dust allergies and the potential for chalk dust to damage computers. By the late 1990s, about 21% of American classrooms had converted from [[Chalkboard|chalkboards]] to whiteboards.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wojenski |first=Jerry |title=Erasing the Past, Typing the Future: Timeline of the Chalkboard |url=http://people.ischool.illinois.edu/~chip/projects/timeline/1801wojenski.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025052101/http://people.ischool.illinois.edu/~chip/projects/timeline/1801wojenski.htm |archive-date=25 October 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== Types of whiteboards ==\n\nThe first whiteboards were very expensive and were made of an enameled steel. Cheaper versions were then produced, including laminated chipboard, high-pressure laminates and steel boards with a matte-finished or glossy white, usually polyester or acrylic, coating. Enameled whiteboards, also referred to as porcelain, and sometimes glass boards, have the advantage that markings can be erased completely; other materials tend to become stained over time. Enameled boards are more expensive and less used in commercial environments, but in more demanding environments with heavier use, such as educational establishments, porcelain boards are considered superior.\n\nOther types of dry marker boards are also available, such as high gloss vinyl and [[coated paper]], which can be rolled up, high-density two-part high gloss paints, glass and coated acrylics and polypropylene magic whiteboards which use static electricity to cling to walls, windows, and doors.\n\nClear marker surfaces, made of glass (matte or glossy) or specially coated acrylic, became available around the [[2000s (decade)|mid-2000s]]. They are generally manufactured from technical glass, e.g. for monitor screen filters, which is optically coated.\n\n=== Adhesive whiteboards ===\nWhiteboard material can be bought in rolls, sheets, and pre-formed boards. Adhesive whiteboards come in either a sheet or a roll and feature a stick back enabling the user to create a custom size board or project with the material. Although adhesive whiteboard material does not come in a thick, hard glass or painted steel plate, the melamine allows for a flexible material while preserving the high-quality whiteboard attributes of other surface materials.<ref name=\":0\" /> Adhesive whiteboards allow for custom projects such as dry erase wall calendars, whiteboard tables, cupboard grocery lists, indoor games for kids, and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.discountmagnet.com/informationcenter/resources/5-ways-to-use-whiteboards|title=5 Creative Ways to Use Dry Erase & Adhesive Whiteboards|website=www.discountmagnet.com|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Erasable marker ===\nThe whiteboard pen (also called a [[whiteboard marker]] or dry erasable marker) was invented by Jerry Woolf of Techform Laboratories and later patented by [[Pilot Pen]] in 1975. <ref>{{cite patent|title=Writing surface and ink composition for marking thereon|date=Feb 16, 1971|url=http://www.google.com/patents/US3563782|inventor-last=D|inventor2-last=U|inventor3-last=A|inventor-first=Atchley Raymond|inventor2-first=Liberman Isaiah|inventor3-first=Woolf Jerome|issue=US3563782 A|accessdate=2017-08-14}}</ref>It is a non-permanent marker and uses an erasable ink that adheres to the writing surface without binding to or being absorbed by it. Applications range from temporary writing with acetate sheets (for use with overhead projectors) to whiteboards and similar glossy surfaces. The erasable ink does not contain the toxic chemical compounds xylene and/or toluene, unlike permanent markers.\n\n== Surface materials ==\nThere are six types of materials commonly used for whiteboard surfaces:\n\n; [[Melamine resin|Melamine]]: A [[resin]]-infused paper which is typically used over a substrate that can range from particle board to MDF (medium density fiberboard).  Melamine boards range in quality primarily because of the amount of resin deposited on the base material.  Some melamine boards remain clean (no ghosting) for a long time, others less so.  Generally, this least expensive type of whiteboard is most commonly found in use in non-institutional applications.  They are available in any [[office supply]] stores. Performance varies widely. These boards are not suitable for heavy use, as in many educational cases, with time the paint erodes and the original surface reappears.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=How It works|url=https://www.remarkablecoating.com/how-it-works/|website=Remarkable Coating|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n;  [[steel]] or [[aluminum]]: Painted steel and aluminum dry erase also have a wide range of quality.  Painted surfaces tend to be smoother, which leads to better methods of erasing.  The painted surface is generally a multiple layer of coatings made up of a base coat in color (most commonly white) and a clear performance coating that is the dry erase component.  Paint varies from electron beam cured coatings to UV and other coating systems.  Good commercial grade painted steel or aluminum has excellent dry erase properties and many will be able to have permanent marker cleaned from the surface.  Any coated surface is susceptible to scratching.  Painted steel surfaces are magnetic and allow the use of magnets. Painted aluminum surfaces are rarely used as a base for whiteboards as they are not magnetic and are more expensive than steel.  Painted steel whiteboards are most commonly used for custom printed whiteboards.  These products are used as tracking boards, patient information boards and tournament and training boards.\n; Hardcoat laminate: Here again the performance varies over a wide range depending on the amount of resin used in the manufacturer.  Basically, this category primarily uses melamine as its dry erase performance coat and therefore falls into the melamine universe.  Depending on the manufacturer (and the price) these laminate often are less porous and highly resistant to staining. Less common than other whiteboard surfaces, because they usually are used in combination with something else (a cabinet, doors or table tops for example). (This statement applies to Porcelain steel which is the only lifetime warranty available on the market)\n; [[Porcelain]], [[Vitreous enamel|enamel]]-on-[[steel]]: [[Ceramic]] fired onto a steel surface in a kiln.  They are the most durable surfaces, and most carry a lifetime [[warranty]].  They are very common in heavy-use industrial settings. They are highly scratch-resistant, although materials harder than glass, such as [[diamond]], can scratch them. They do not absorb dry erase or permanent marker ink.  They allow the use of [[magnets]].  The surface can be cleaned with any non-abrasive cleaner suitable for porcelain, then rinsed off with water to prevent smearing.  Permanent marker can be removed using a polar solvent such as ethanol, isopropanol or acetone, or by writing over it with a dry-erase marker and erasing it.\n; Tempered glass:[[Tempered glass]] is easier to erase.  Most tempered glass white boards have no frame.\n; [[Polypropylene]] film: Polypropylene film is temporary and uses [[static electricity]] to cling to existing surfaces. It works with dry whiteboard markers and wipes. Whiteboards are reusable and materials are recyclable.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Grease pencil]]\n*[[Flip chart]]\n*[[Album (Ancient Rome)]], a board chalked or painted white, on which public notices were inscribed in black\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Whiteboards}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Office equipment]]\n[[Category:Writing media]]\n[[Category:Educational devices]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|physical whiteboards|software-based wipeboards|Wipeboarding}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2007}}\n[[File:Blank whiteboard.JPG|thumb|A blank whiteboard]]\n[[File:NCTR Intern Claire Boyle (15558843862).jpg|thumb|Researcher writing on a whiteboard]]\n\nA '''whiteboard''' (also known by the terms '''marker board''', '''dry-erase board''', '''wipe board''', '''dry-wipe board''', and '''pen-board''') is a glossy, usually white surface for making nonpermanent markings (an evolved version of the blackboard). Whiteboards are analogous to [[blackboard]]s, but with a smoother surface allowing rapid marking and erasing of markings on their surface. The popularity of whiteboards increased rapidly in the mid-1990s and they have become a fixture in many offices, meeting rooms, school classrooms, and other work environments.\n\nThe term ''whiteboard'' is also used metaphorically to refer to features of computer software applications that simulate whiteboards. Such \"virtual tech whiteboards\" allow one or more people to write or draw images on a simulated canvas. This is a common feature of many virtual meeting, [[collaborative software|collaboration]], and [[instant messaging]] applications. The term ''whiteboard'' is also used to refer to [[interactive whiteboard]]s.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Combo whiteboard and bulletin board.JPG|thumb|A combination whiteboard and cork [[bulletin board]]]]\n[[File:Plasti-slate 001.jpg|thumb|Original early 1960s ad for \"Plasti-slate\", the first whiteboard/dry erase board invented by Martin Heit]]\n\nAlbert Stallion invented whiteboards while working at Alliance in the 1960s. Alliance (now known as [[PolyVision (company)|PolyVision]]) produced enameled steel for architectural cladding, but Stallion noted it could also potentially be used as a writing surface. Stallion later left Alliance to form his own whiteboard production company, MagiBoards.<ref name=\"Whiteboards History\">{{cite web |last=McClean |first=Garry |title=Whiteboards History |url=http://www.theworkplacedepot.co.uk/news/2014/08/20/whiteboards-history/ |work=The Workplace Depot |access-date=24 October 2016 |date=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Company Overview of Alliance International Group |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=24608 |work=[[Bloomberg.com]] |access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Magiboards 1966 Door Sign.JPG|thumb|Door sign to the offices of Magiboards at The Cut in Waterloo, London, in 1966. Made of enameled steel]]\n\nWhiteboards became commercially available in the early 1960s, but did not become widely used until 30 years later. Early whiteboards needed to be wiped with a damp cloth and markers had a tendency to leave marks behind, even after erasing the board.<ref name=\"Whiteboards History\"/><ref name=\"History of Whiteboard Learning\">{{cite web |title=The History of Whiteboard Learning |url=https://www.magnatag.com/blog/2014/12/17/the-history-of-whiteboard-learning/ |work=Magnatag Visible Systems |access-date=24 October 2016 |date=17 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111005636/https://www.magnatag.com/blog/2014/12/17/the-history-of-whiteboard-learning/ |archive-date=11 January 2017 |first=Tom |last=Shaw}}</ref> Dry-erase markers for whiteboards were invented in 1975.<ref name=\"Whiteboards History\"/>\n\nWhiteboards started becoming commonly used by businesses in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/11/12/google-releases-jamboard-a-high-tech-whiteboard-for-office-meetings.html |title=Google releases Jamboard, a high-tech whiteboard for office meetings |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |date=November 12, 2016 |page=B4 |first=Steven |last=Overly |access-date=9 March 2019 |publisher=[[Toronto Star Newspapers Ltd.]]}}</ref> They became more common in classrooms during the 1990s due to concerns over health problems in children with dust allergies and the potential for chalk dust to damage computers. By the late 1990s, about 21% of American classrooms had converted from [[Chalkboard|chalkboards]] to whiteboards.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wojenski |first=Jerry |title=Erasing the Past, Typing the Future: Timeline of the Chalkboard |url=http://people.ischool.illinois.edu/~chip/projects/timeline/1801wojenski.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025052101/http://people.ischool.illinois.edu/~chip/projects/timeline/1801wojenski.htm |archive-date=25 October 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== Types of whiteboards ==\n\nThe first whiteboards were very expensive and were made of an enameled steel. Cheaper versions were then produced, including laminated chipboard, high-pressure laminates and steel boards with a matte-finished or glossy white, usually polyester or acrylic, coating. Enameled whiteboards, also referred to as porcelain, and sometimes glass boards, have the advantage that markings can be erased completely; other materials tend to become stained over time. Enameled boards are more expensive and less used in commercial environments, but in more demanding environments with heavier use, such as educational establishments, porcelain boards are considered superior.\n\nOther types of dry marker boards are also available, such as high gloss vinyl and [[coated paper]], which can be rolled up, high-density two-part high gloss paints, glass and coated acrylics and polypropylene magic whiteboards which use static electricity to cling to walls, windows, and doors.\n\nClear marker surfaces, made of glass (matte or gGlossy) or specially coated acrylic, became available around the [[2000s (decade)|mid-2000s]]. They are generally manufactured from technical glass, e.g. for monitor screen filters, which is optically coated.\n\n=== Adhesive whiteboards ===\nWhiteboard material can be bought in rolls, sheets, and pre-formed boards. Adhesive whiteboards come in either a sheet or a roll and feature a stick back enabling the user to create a custom size board or project with the material. Although adhesive whiteboard material does not come in a thick, hard glass or painted steel plate, the melamine allows for a flexible material while preserving the high-quality whiteboard attributes of other surface materials.<ref name=\":0\" /> Adhesive whiteboards allow for custom projects such as dry erase wall calendars, whiteboard tables, cupboard grocery lists, indoor games for kids, and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.discountmagnet.com/informationcenter/resources/5-ways-to-use-whiteboards|title=5 Creative Ways to Use Dry Erase & Adhesive Whiteboards|website=www.discountmagnet.com|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Erasable marker ===\nThe whiteboard pen (also called a [[whiteboard marker]] or dry erasable marker) was invented by Jerry Woolf of Techform Laboratories and later patented by [[Pilot Pen]] in 1975. <ref>{{cite patent|title=Writing surface and ink composition for marking thereon|date=Feb 16, 1971|url=http://www.google.com/patents/US3563782|inventor-last=D|inventor2-last=U|inventor3-last=A|inventor-first=Atchley Raymond|inventor2-first=Liberman Isaiah|inventor3-first=Woolf Jerome|issue=US3563782 A|accessdate=2017-08-14}}</ref>It is a non-permanent marker and uses an erasable ink that adheres to the writing surface without binding to or being absorbed by it. Applications range from temporary writing with acetate sheets (for use with overhead projectors) to whiteboards and similar glossy surfaces. The erasable ink does not contain the toxic chemical compounds xylene and/or toluene, unlike permanent markers.\n\n== Surface materials ==\nThere are six types of materials commonly used for whiteboard surfaces:\n\n; [[Melamine resin|Melamine]]: A [[resin]]-infused paper which is typically used over a substrate that can range from particle board to MDF (medium density fiberboard).  Melamine boards range in quality primarily because of the amount of resin deposited on the base material.  Some melamine boards remain clean (no ghosting) for a long time, others less so.  Generally, this least expensive type of whiteboard is most commonly found in use in non-institutional applications.  They are available in any [[office supply]] stores. Performance varies widely. These boards are not suitable for heavy use, as in many educational cases, with time the paint erodes and the original surface reappears.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=How It works|url=https://www.remarkablecoating.com/how-it-works/|website=Remarkable Coating|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n;  [[steel]] or [[aluminum]]: Painted steel and aluminum dry erase also have a wide range of quality.  Painted surfaces tend to be smoother, which leads to better methods of erasing.  The painted surface is generally a multiple layer of coatings made up of a base coat in color (most commonly white) and a clear performance coating that is the dry erase component.  Paint varies from electron beam cured coatings to UV and other coating systems.  Good commercial grade painted steel or aluminum has excellent dry erase properties and many will be able to have permanent marker cleaned from the surface.  Any coated surface is susceptible to scratching.  Painted steel surfaces are magnetic and allow the use of magnets. Painted aluminum surfaces are rarely used as a base for whiteboards as they are not magnetic and are more expensive than steel.  Painted steel whiteboards are most commonly used for custom printed whiteboards.  These products are used as tracking boards, patient information boards and tournament and training boards.\n; Hardcoat laminate: Here again the performance varies over a wide range depending on the amount of resin used in the manufacturer.  Basically, this category primarily uses melamine as its dry erase performance coat and therefore falls into the melamine universe.  Depending on the manufacturer (and the price) these laminate often are less porous and highly resistant to staining. Less common than other whiteboard surfaces, because they usually are used in combination with something else (a cabinet, doors or table tops for example). (This statement applies to Porcelain steel which is the only lifetime warranty available on the market)\n; [[Porcelain]], [[Vitreous enamel|enamel]]-on-[[steel]]: [[Ceramic]] fired onto a steel surface in a kiln.  They are the most durable surfaces, and most carry a lifetime [[warranty]].  They are very common in heavy-use industrial settings. They are highly scratch-resistant, although materials harder than glass, such as [[diamond]], can scratch them. They do not absorb dry erase or permanent marker ink.  They allow the use of [[magnets]].  The surface can be cleaned with any non-abrasive cleaner suitable for porcelain, then rinsed off with water to prevent smearing.  Permanent marker can be removed using a polar solvent such as ethanol, isopropanol or acetone, or by writing over it with a dry-erase marker and erasing it.\n; Tempered glass:[[Tempered glass]] is easier to erase.  Most tempered glass white boards have no frame.\n; [[Polypropylene]] film: Polypropylene film is temporary and uses [[static electricity]] to cling to existing surfaces. It works with dry whiteboard markers and wipes. Whiteboards are reusable and materials are recyclable.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Grease pencil]]\n*[[Flip chart]]\n*[[Album (Ancient Rome)]], a board chalked or painted white, on which public notices were inscribed in black\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Whiteboards}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Office equipment]]\n[[Category:Writing media]]\n[[Category:Educational devices]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTypes of whiteboards:fmt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whiteboard"}
{"title_page": "Ahmet \u00c7akar", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name   = Ahmet \u00c7akar\n| image     = \n| image_size     = \n| caption  =  \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1962|08|03|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation     = [[Medicine]],\n [[referee (association football)|football referee]]\n| spouse         = \n| parents        =\n| children       = 2\n}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name = Ahmet \u00c7akar\n| image =\n| caption =\n| role1 = Referee\n| league1 = [[S\u00fcper Lig|1. Lig]]\n| years1 = 1990\u20131999\n| internationalyears1 = 1992\u20131999\n| confederation1 = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA]]-listed\n| internationalrole1 = Referee\n}}\n\n'''Ahmet \u00c7akar''' (born August 3, 1962) is a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] [[sportscaster]] and a former [[football (soccer)|football]] referee.\n\n==Information==\nHe is famous for the abrasive manner<ref>{{cite news |title=Forget about athletics, I would rather see marbles |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/columnists/article-301424/Forget-athletics-I-marbles.html |work=[[Daily Mail]] |date=28 February 2004 |accessdate=8 January 2010 |location=London |first=Ian |last=Wooldridge}}</ref> in which he presents the [[Show TV]] sports programme ''[[Alt\u0131pas]]'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Former referee likens chicanery in football to Ergenekon affair |url=http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=138625 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120914064907/http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=138625 |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2012 |work=[[Today's Zaman]] |date=10 April 2008 |accessdate=8 January 2010}} </ref> being described as \"Turkey's most controversial football pundit\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Rockers relieved as groovy Glovers prepare for slipped disc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/feb/28/sport.comment6 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=28 February 2004 |accessdate=8 January 2010 |location=London |first=Paul |last=MacInnes}}</ref> He also writes sports articles for [[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]] newspaper.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00c7akar bikini giyecek mi? |url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/default.aspx?aType=SonDakika&ArticleID=501915 |work=[[Milliyet]] |date=5 March 2008 |accessdate=8 January 2010}}</ref> He is a medical doctor as well. Currently he is a commentator on the Turkish football television programme [[Beyaz Futbol]], on [[Beyaz TV]].\n\nOn March 2013, \u00c7akar appeared on TV claiming that the draws for the quarter-finals of [[UEFA]]'s club competitions had been fixed by those making the draw \"carry[ing] metal objects that sensed vibrations in the balls being selected\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1383191/ex-turkish-referee-claims-uefa-rigged-champions-league-draw?cc=5739 |title=Ex-Turkish ref claims UCL draw rigged |publisher=ESPN FC |date=21 March 2013 |accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]], he is one of the world's best referees of the quarter of a century<ref name=\"best refrees\">[http://www.iffhs.de/?20e43c03f32b00f31c13f32b17f7370eff3702bb1c2bbb6e08].</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in Istanbul in 1962. He completed his high school education at [[Istanbul Erkek Lisesi]] in 1980. Then he graduated from the Faculty of Medicine at [[Istanbul University]].\n\nIn 2004, he was shot and wounded in the groin and abdomen in Istanbul.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former soccer referee recovering after being shot five times |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-91492686.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102205912/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-91492686.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 November 2012 |work=AP Worldstream |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=26 February 2004 |accessdate=8 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Major matches refereed==\n* 18 June 1996 \u2013 [[Romania national football team|Romania]] \u2013 [[Spain national football team|Spain]] (1-2) [[UEFA Euro 1996]] 1. round<ref>{{cite news |title=Referees for Euro Soccer Championship Fixtures |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-17967652.html |work=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=25 March 1996 |accessdate=8 January 2010 |url-access=subscription}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n* 1 March 1995 \u2013 [[A.C. Milan]] \u2013 [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] (2-0) [[UEFA Champions League]] Quarterfinal<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acmilan.com/LM_Match.aspx?idIncontro=2135 |title=AC Milan and SL Benfica: past meetings |publisher=[[A.C. Milan]] |accessdate=8 January 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n* 5 April 1995 \u2013 [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] \u2013 [[Ajax Amsterdam]] (0-0) [[UEFA Champions League]] Semi Finals<ref>{{cite news |title=T\u00fcrk hakemli\u011finde 31 Mart vak'as\u0131! |url=http://www.zaman.com.tr/haber.do?haberno=272946 |work=[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]] |accessdate=8 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928214925/http://www.zaman.com.tr/haber.do?haberno=272946 |archivedate=28 September 2011}}</ref>\n* 20 March 1993 \u2013 [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] \u2013 [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] (1-2) World Youth Cup (U-20) Final<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/wyc93.html |title=World Youth Cup (U-20) 1993 (Australia, March 5-20) |work=Rsssf}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{TFF referee}}\n* {{WorldFootball.net referee}}\n* {{Soccerway referee|ahmet-cakar/222180}}\n\n{{UEFA Euro 1996 referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cakar, Ahmet}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sports commentators]]\n[[Category:Turkish journalists]]\n[[Category:Turkish football referees]]\n[[Category:Sabah (newspaper) people]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 referees]]\n\n\n{{Turkey-sport-bio-stub}}\n{{Turkey-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name   = Ahmet \u00c7akar\n| image     = \n| image_size     = \n| caption  =  \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1962|08|03|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation     = [[Medicine]],\n [[referee (association football)|football referee]]\n| spouse         = \n| parents        =\n| children       = 2\n}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name = Ahmet \u00c7akar\n| image =\n| caption =\n| role1 = Referee\n| league1 = [[S\u00fcper Lig|1. Lig]]\n| years1 = 1990\u20131999\n| internationalyears1 = 1992\u20131999\n| confederation1 = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA]]-listed\n| internationalrole1 = Referee\n}}\n'''Ahmet \u00c7akar''' (born August 3, 1962) is a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] [[sportscaster]] and a former [[football (soccer)|football]] referee.\n\n==Information==\nHe is famous for the abrasive manner<ref>{{cite news |title=Forget about athletics, I would rather see marbles |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/columnists/article-301424/Forget-athletics-I-marbles.html |work=[[Daily Mail]] |date=28 February 2004 |accessdate=8 January 2010 | location=London | first=Ian | last=Wooldridge}}</ref> in which he presents the [[Show TV]] sports programme ''[[Alt\u0131pas]]'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Former referee likens chicanery in football to Ergenekon affair |url=http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=138625 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120914064907/http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=138625 |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2012 |work=[[Today's Zaman]] |date=10 April 2008 |accessdate=8 January 2010 }} </ref> being described as \"Turkey's most controversial football pundit\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Rockers relieved as groovy Glovers prepare for slipped disc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/feb/28/sport.comment6 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=28 February 2004 |accessdate=8 January 2010 | location=London | first=Paul | last=MacInnes}}</ref> He also writes sports articles for [[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]] newspaper.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00c7akar bikini giyecek mi? |url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/default.aspx?aType=SonDakika&ArticleID=501915 |work=[[Milliyet]] |date=5 March 2008 |accessdate=8 January 2010 }}</ref> He is a medical doctor as well. Currently he is a commentator on the Turkish football television programme [[Beyaz Futbol]], on [[Beyaz TV]].\n\nOn March 2013, \u00c7akar appeared on TV claiming that the draws for the quarter-finals of [[UEFA]]'s club competitions had been fixed by those making the draw \"carry[ing] metal objects that sensed vibrations in the balls being selected\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1383191/ex-turkish-referee-claims-uefa-rigged-champions-league-draw?cc=5739 |title=Ex-Turkish ref claims UCL draw rigged |publisher=ESPN FC |date=21 March 2013 |accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]], he is one of the world's best referees of the quarter of a century<ref name=\"best refrees\">[http://www.iffhs.de/?20e43c03f32b00f31c13f32b17f7370eff3702bb1c2bbb6e08].</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in Istanbul in 1962. He completed his high school education at [[Istanbul Erkek Lisesi]] in 1980. Then he graduated from the Faculty of Medicine at [[Istanbul University]].\n\nIn 2004, he was shot and wounded in the groin and abdomen in Istanbul.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former soccer referee recovering after being shot five times |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-91492686.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102205912/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-91492686.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 November 2012 |work=AP Worldstream |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=26 February 2004 |accessdate=8 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Major matches refereed==\n* 18 June 1996 \u2013 [[Romania national football team|Romania]] \u2013 [[Spain national football team|Spain]] (1-2) [[UEFA Euro 1996]] 1. round<ref>{{cite news |title=Referees for Euro Soccer Championship Fixtures |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-17967652.html |work=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=25 March 1996 |accessdate=8 January 2010 |url-access=subscription  }}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n* 1 March 1995 \u2013 [[A.C. Milan]] \u2013 [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] (2-0) [[UEFA Champions League]] Quarterfinal<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acmilan.com/LM_Match.aspx?idIncontro=2135 |title=AC Milan and SL Benfica: past meetings |publisher=[[A.C. Milan]] |accessdate=8 January 2010 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n* 5 April 1995 \u2013 [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] \u2013 [[Ajax Amsterdam]] (0-0) [[UEFA Champions League]] Semi Finals<ref>{{cite news|title=T\u00fcrk hakemli\u011finde 31 Mart vak'as\u0131! |url=http://www.zaman.com.tr/haber.do?haberno=272946 |work=[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]] |accessdate=8 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928214925/http://www.zaman.com.tr/haber.do?haberno=272946 |archivedate=28 September 2011 }}</ref>\n* 20 March 1993 \u2013 [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] \u2013 [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] (1-2) World Youth Cup (U-20) Final<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/wyc93.html | title=World Youth Cup (U-20) 1993 (Australia, March 5-20) |  work=Rsssf}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{UEFA Euro 1996 referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cakar, Ahmet}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sports commentators]]\n[[Category:Turkish journalists]]\n[[Category:Turkish football referees]]\n[[Category:Sabah (newspaper) people]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 referees]]\n\n\n{{Turkey-sport-bio-stub}}\n{{Turkey-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ahmet_%C3%87akar"}
{"title_page": "Massacres of Albanians in the Balkan Wars", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Massacres of Albanians in the Balkan Wars\n| location    = [[Albania]], [[Kosovo Vilayet]]\n| target      = [[Albanians|Albanian]] population in the territories occupied by Serbia, especially in the regions of today's [[Kosovo]], Western [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] and Northern [[Albania]]\n| date        = 1912\u20131913\n| type        = [[Deportation]], [[mass murder]], [[death march]], others\n| fatalities = 20,000\u201325,000 \n| perps       = [[Kingdom of Serbia]], [[Kingdom of Montenegro]]\n}}\n\n[[File:NY Times Massacre of Albanians 1912.jpg|thumb|''[[The New York Times]]'', 31 December 1912]]\nA series of '''massacres of Albanians in the Balkan Wars''' were committed by the [[Montenegrin Army]], [[Serbian Army]]  and [[Chetniks|paramilitaries]], according to international reports.<ref>{{cite book |author=United States Department of State |title=Papers Relating to the Foreign Relations of the United States |date=1943 |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |page=115 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ADhGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA115&dq=Serbian+troops+atrocities+1913#v=onepage&q=Serbian%20troops%20atrocities%201913&f=false |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Report\"/> During the [[First Balkan War]] of 1912\u201313, [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbia]] and [[Kingdom of Montenegro|Montenegro]] during the war with the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] forces (many Albanians were among the Ottoman forces) and after expelling the official Ottoman Empire's forces in present-day [[Albania]] and [[Kosovo]] - committed numerous [[war crime]]s against the Albanian population, which were reported by the European, American and Serbian opposition press.<ref name=\"Golgotha\">[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_1.html Leo Freundlich: Albania's Golgotha] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531131757/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_1.html |date=31 May 2012 }}</ref> Most of the crimes happened between October 1912 and summer of 1913. The goal of the forced expulsions and massacres of ethnic Albanians was a statistic manipulation before the London Ambassadors Conference which was to decide on the new Balkan borders.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danas.rs/dodaci/vikend/otpor_okupaciji_i_modernizaciji.26.html?news_id=105029|title=Otpor okupaciji i modernizaciji|publisher=|accessdate=6 September 2016|date=9 March 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Hudson128\"/> According to contemporary accounts, between 20,000 and 25,000 Albanians were killed or died because of hunger and cold during that period.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/><ref name=\"Hudson128\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W4zndspbem4C|title=Justice, Intervention, and Force in International Relations: Reassessing Just War Theory in the 21st Century|first=Kimberly A.|last=Hudson|date=5 March 2009|publisher=Taylor & Francis|pages=128|accessdate=6 September 2016|via=Google Books|isbn=9780203879351}}</ref><ref name=\"Archbishop\">[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_6.html Archbishop Laz\u00ebr Mjeda: Report on the Serb Invasion of Kosova and Macedonia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303195950/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_6.html |date=3 March 2016 }}</ref> Many of the victims were children, women and old people and were part of an warfare of extermination.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bessel |first1=Richard |title=No Man's Land of Violence: Extreme Wars in the 20th Century |date=2006 |publisher=Wallstein Verlag |isbn=978-3-89244-825-9 |page=226 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wr-j5ibVgXsC&pg=PA229&dq=atrocities+against+Albanians+1912#v=onepage&q=atrocities%20against%20Albanians%201912&f=false |accessdate=24 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Aside from massacres, civilians had their lips and noses severed.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Tatum |first1=Dale C. |title=Genocide at the Dawn of the Twenty-First Century: Rwanda, Bosnia, Kosovo, and Darfur |date=2010 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-0-230-62189-3 |page=113 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=nWsbAQAAMAAJ&dq=Albanian+civilians+1912&q=massacred |accessdate=3 January 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Philip J. Cohen]], the [[Serbian Army]] generated such fear that some Albanian women killed their own children rather than let them fall into the hands of the Serbian soldiery.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cohen |first1=Philip J. |title=The Ideology and Historical Continuity of Serbia's Anti-Islamic Policy |journal=Islamic Studies |date=1997 |volume=36 |issue=2/3 |pages=361\u2013382 |publisher=Islamic Research Institute, International Islamic University |location=Islamabad |language=en |quote=Among the worst and most consistent offenders were the Serbs, who generated such fear that some women killed their own children, rather than let them fall into Serbian hands|jstor=23076201 }}</ref> In relation to Serbia and Montenegro, the Carnegie Commission, an international fact finding mission concluded that both its armies perpetrated large-scale violence that aimed at \"the entire transformation of the ethnic character of regions inhabited exclusively by Albanians\".<ref name=\"Kramer138\"/> Cohen also examined the report from the [[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]] stating that Serbian soldiers also tortured and mutilated the Albanian civil population by cutting off ears, noses, tongues and by couging out eyes.<ref>PHILIP J. COHEN, slamic Studies\nVol. 36, No. 2/3, Special Issue: ISLAM IN THE BALKANS , 1997, p. 4 out of 22</ref>\n\nAccording to the Committee of Kosovo, during this period, around 23 000 Albanians were killed or died in Serbian, Montenegrin and Greek prisons. According to an Albanian imam organization, there were around 21 000 simple graves in Kosovo where Albanians had been massacred by the Serb gender armies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Horvat, Dr. Jusuf Osmani |first1=Mislav |title=Jusuf Osmani - Kolonizimi Serbi Kosoves (The Serbian colonisation of Kosovo) |date=2010 |publisher=REND Prishtin\u00eb |location=Pristina |page=66 |edition= |url=https://www.academia.edu/27205754/Jusuf_Osmani_-_Kolonizimi_Serbi_Kosoves.pdf |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On August\u2013September 1913, Serbian forces destroyed 140 villages and forced 40 000 Albanians to flee.<ref>{{cite book |last1=N.Y.) |first1=Near East College Association (New York |title=The Near East |date=1921 |publisher=s.n. |page=45 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=gD8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA767&dq=The+suppressed+Albanian+lord+were+hostile+to+new+authority&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjniOLgjNHoAhVql4sKHSOaB8IQ6AEINzAC#v=onepage&q=Albanian&f=false |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to newsman William Howard in an interview titled \"Let Albanians Starve: They are Mohammmedans\", at the New York Globe, 1914, the Serbian army carried out [[modus operandi]]: \"''Serb regiments of 1100, led by General Carlos Popovitch, entered Albania with kerosene oil, force pumps and dynamite bombs. They captured such Albanian men as they could. Then they tied them together by the elbows and shot them down. The women were outraged. I believe that every woman who fell into the hands of the Serb troops fell a victim to them. Then they were locked up in the house and bombs planted in the walls. Kerosene oil would be sprayed over all and a fire started. When the flames reached the dynamite, the walls were shattered. Albania is filled with fire blackened heaps of stones that were once houses''\".<ref name=\"McFarland\">{{cite book |last1=Jacques |first1=Edwin E. |title=The Albanians: An Ethnic History from Prehistoric Times to the Present |date=1995 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-89950-932-7 |page=352 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=IJ2s9sQ9bGkC&pg=PA273&dq=1912+Shkodra+atrocities&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwior6O0ucXoAhXCrIsKHRTZABAQ6AEIQDAD#v=onepage&q=atrocities&f=false |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAmerican relief commissioner Mr Willar Howard stated in an interview with The Daily Mirror in 1914 that Popovitch would yell \"''Dont run away, we are brothers and friends. We dont mean to do any harm.''\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Archives |first1=British News Paper |title=\"Albanian Peasants Burned by Servians: New Rulers Task\" |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/BL/0000560/19140202/063/0009?browse=true |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk |agency=Daily Mirror |issue=p.9 \"A scene in a refugee camp. In the background are a woman and a boy who are slowly dying of hunger fever\". \"Mohammedan refugees at Scutari, who are among the sufferers.\" \"Where two women were burnt to death by Servians\". \"Wretched shelter in which a family are housed\". |publisher=The Daily Mirror |date=February 2, 1914}}</ref> Peasants who trusted the words were shot or burned to death, and elderly women unable to leave their homes were burned as well. Howard states that the atrocities were committed after the war had ended.\n\nAccording to the study ''Yugoslavia from a Historical Perspective'', published in Belgrade 2017 by the ''Helsinki Committee for Human Rights in Serbia'', when Serbo-Montenegrin forces invaded Kosovo in 1912, havoc was created where villages were burned to ashes, and Albanian Muslims were targeted and many were forced to flee. Some chronicles evidence the atrocities including [[decapitation]] and [[mutilation]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Biserko, Latinka Perovi\u0107, Drago Roksandi\u0107, Mitja Velikonja, Wolfgang Hoepken, Florian Bieber, Sheila Sofrenovi\u0107, Ivan Hra\u0161ovec |first1=Sonja |title=Yugoslavia from a Historical Perspective |date=2017 |publisher=Helsinki Committee for Human Rights in Serbia |location=Belgrade |isbn=978-86-7208-208-1 |pages=272\u201373 |edition=\"In the falls of 1912 and 1913, Kosovo and Albania were invaded by Serbia and Montenegro. The Balkan Wars had wreaked havoc on Kosovar Albanians whose villages were burned to ashes and whose residents that had managed to escape death were forced to flee their homes. Under such brutal wartime conditions, the Montenegrin and Serbian authorities targeted the Muslim population of Kosovo, the majority of which was Albanian. Some chronicles evidence the atrocities committed by the Montenegrins, including  against colonial status 273 decapitation and mutilation. The Balkan wars had cost the Kosovar Albanians thousands of dead and more destroyed houses. It is estimated that around 20\u201325.000 Albanians were killed up to the end of 1912 and about 20,000 emigrated from Kosovo\" |url=http://www.yuhistorija.com/doc/yugoslavia%20from%20a%20historical%20perspective.pdf |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe modern Albanian-Serbian conflict has its roots in the [[Expulsion of the Albanians 1877\u20131878|expulsion of the Albanians in 1877-1878 from areas that became incorporated into the]] [[Principality of Serbia]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Frantz|first=Eva Anne|title=Violence and its Impact on Loyalty and Identity Formation in Late Ottoman Kosovo: Muslims and Christians in a Period of Reform and Transformation|journal=Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs|volume=29|issue=4|year=2009|pages=460\u2013461|ref=harv|doi=10.1080/13602000903411366}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=M\u00fcller|first=Dietmar|title=Orientalism and Nation: Jews and Muslims as Alterity in Southeastern Europe in the Age of Nation-States, 1878\u20131941|journal=East Central Europe|volume=36|issue=1|year=2009|page=70|ref=harv|doi=10.1163/187633009x411485}}</ref> Prior to the outbreak of the First Balkan War, the [[Albanians|Albanian]] nation was fighting for a [[national state]]. In mid 1912, an [[Albanian revolt of 1912|Albanian revolt]] resulted in Ottoman recognition of the \"[[Hasan Prishtina#Albanian National Movement|14 points]]\", a list of demands that included the establishment of an autonomous [[Albanian vilayet]].<ref name=\"Dauti94\"/> The push for Albanian autonomy and Ottoman weakness were viewed at the time as directly threatening the Christian population of the region with extermination by regional Christian Balkan powers.<ref>''Report of the International Commission on the Balkan Wars''. p. 47.</ref> Albanian scholarship states the realisation of Albanian aspirations were received negatively by Bulgaria, Serbia, Montenegro and Greece.<ref name=\"Dauti94\"/> The [[Balkan League]] (comprising [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]], Greece and [[Bulgaria]]) jointly attacked the [[Ottoman Empire]] and during the next few months partitioned all Ottoman territory inhabited by Albanians.<ref name=\"Report\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/reportofinternat00inteuoft|title=Report of the International Commission to Inquire into the Causes and Conduct of the Balkan War|last1=International Commission to Inquire into the Causes and Conduct of the Balkan Wars|last2=Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. Division of Intercourse and Education|date=1 January 1914|publisher=Washington, D.C. : The Endowment|accessdate=6 September 2016|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> The [[Kingdom of Serbia]] and the [[Kingdom of Greece]] occupied most of the land of what is today Albania and other lands inhabited by Albanians on the [[Adriatic coast]]. Montenegro occupied a part of today's northern Albania around [[Shkod\u00ebr]]. The Serbian army in the region viewed its role as protecting local Orthodox Christian communities and avenging the medieval battle of Kosovo,<ref name=\"Batakovic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doiserbia.nb.rs/img/doi/0350-7653/2014/0350-76531445317B.pdf|title=Serbia, the Serbo-Albanian Conflict and the First Balkan War}} pp. 338-340; 343.</ref> though it forced Catholic Albanians to convert to Orthodox Christianity.<ref name=\"Mirdita\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hic.hr/books/jugoistocna-europa/mirdita.htm|title=Medjunarodni znanstveni skup \"Jugoistocna Europa 1918.-1995.\" Albanci u svjetlosti vanjske politike Srbije|last=Nadj|first=Danijela|website=|accessdate=6 September 2016}}</ref> Serbia also doubled its territory, according to Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107. A majority of Albanian historians state that Montenegro, Greece and Serbia did not recognise Albanian autonomy and the cause for the Balkan Wars was to stop its establishment on Ottoman lands they claimed.<ref name=\"Dauti94\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=94}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Serbo-Montenegrin forces invaded the Vilayet of Kosovo in 1912, much of the Albanian population was forced to flee due to the feared and actual violence that they experienced at the hands of the invading armies.<ref>{{cite book |title=Casebook on Insurgency and Revolutionary Warfare |date=2012 |publisher=United States Army Special Operations Command |page=270 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=SPZdWxjMd6cC&pg=PA270&dq=en+masse+#v=onepage&q=en%20masse&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> During the Serb military effort to conquer Kosovo, the armed conflict had overtones of extermination, due to Serb retaliation directed toward Albanians that affected children and women, involved the killing of women and men and homes razed.<ref name=\"Hopken226\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2006|p=226}}</ref> In this period, 235 villages were burned down in total, with 133 being burned by Serb forces and 102 by Montenegrin.<ref>ibid. p. 28</ref> Steven Schwarts states that during the capture of Durr\u00ebs, Shkod\u00ebr and Shengjin, Serbian soldiers massacred, pillaged and targeted poor Albanians.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schwartz |first1=Stephen |title=Kosovo: Background to a War |date=2000 |publisher=Anthem Press |isbn=978-1-898855-56-9 |page=55 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=jL4tAQAAIAAJ&dq=1912+Shkodra+atrocities&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=capture |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Albanian publicist Armend Bekaj states that the Serbian invasion of Kosovo was illegal.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bekaj |first1=Armend |title=The KLA and the Kosovo war |publisher=Berghof Transitions Series. Resistance/Liberation Movements and Transitions to Polticis. |location=Berlin |isbn=9783941514027 |page=9 |url=https://www.berghof-foundation.org/fileadmin/redaktion/Publications/Papers/Transitions_Series/transitions8_kosovo.pdf |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Massacres==\n===Vilayet of Scutari===\n====Mal\u00ebsia====\nDuring the Balkan Wars, multiple reports surfaced regarding violent persecutions by Montenegro of Catholic Albanians.<ref name=\"Treadway162\"/> In districts under Montenegrin military control, Catholic and Muslim Albanians were subjected to forced mass conversions to Orthodox Christianity, through a policy that aimed to dismantle identities based on a particular religion, and to sever other sociocultural links.<ref name=\"Pezo6566\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|pp=66-65}}</ref>\n\n====Shkod\u00ebr====\nWhen Serbo-Montenegrin soldiers invaded Shkod\u00ebr, around 10 000 Montenegrin lives were lost. In the city, they looted and massacred civilians, including the sick and wounded, women and children, many of whom were Christian.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Udovicki |first1=Jasminka |last2=Ridgeway |first2=James |title=Burn This House: The Making and Unmaking of Yugoslavia |date=2000 |publisher=Duke University Press |isbn=978-0-8223-8091-7 |page=30 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=DHMioF8-CewC&pg=PA42&dq=Leon+Trotsky+Kosovo#v=onepage&q=Leon%20Trotsky%20Kosovo&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In late 1913, international pressure resulted in the Serbian withdrawal of its forces from Shkod\u00ebr and the Austro-Hungarian consul general within the town reported that during the process, Serb troops killed some 600 Albanians.<ref name=\"Treadway162\">{{cite book|last=Treadway|first=John D.|title=The Falcon and the Eagle: Montenegro and Austria-Hungary, 1908-1914|year=1998|publisher=Purdue University Press|isbn=9781557531469|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JVJUk2cHkDcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Montenegrin+army+balkan+wars+albanians#v=onepage&q=albanians&f=false|pages=162|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n====Morin\u00eb====\nIn 1912, Serbian forces entered [[Qaf\u00eb Morin\u00eb]] where they massacred 15 civilians.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Qeriqi |first1=Ahmet |title=Dr. Sk\u00ebnder Demaliaj: N\u00eb 100 vjetorin e p\u00ebrfundimit t\u00eb Luft\u00ebs s\u00eb Par\u00eb Bot\u00ebrore - Radio Kosova e Lir\u00eb |url=https://www.radiokosovaelire.com/dr-skender-demaliaj-ne-100-vjetorin-e-perfundimit-te-luftes-se-pare-boterore/' |date=9 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Vilayet of Kosovo ===\n\nThe Belgrade consulate of Austria-Hungary reported that during February 1913, Serbian military forces executed all Albanian inhabitants from the villages of Kabash, T\u00ebrpez\u00eb, Lubisht and Gjylekar.<ref name=\"Michailidis331\">{{harvnb|Michailidis|2018|p=331.}}</ref>\n\n[[Chetniks]], a Serb irregular force razed the Albanian quarter of [[Skopje]] and killed a number of Albanian inhabitants from the city.<ref name=\"Michailidis330\">{{cite book|last=Michailidis|first=Iakovos D.|chapter=Cleansing the Nation: War related Demographic Changes in Macedonia|editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Wars of Yesterday: The Balkan Wars and the Emergence of Modern Military Conflict, 1912-13|year=2018|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=9781785337758|url=https://books.google.com/?id=okMtDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Wars+of+Yesterday:+The+Balkan+Wars+and+the+Emergence+of+Modern+Military+Conflict,+1912-13#v=snippet&q=burned&f=false|pages=330|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n====Prishtina====\nWhen villagers heard about the Serbian massacres of Albanians in the nearby villages, some houses took the desperate measure of raising white flag to protect themselves. In the cases the white flag was ignored during the attack of Serbian army on Prishtina in October 1912, the Albanians (led by Ottoman and Ottoman Albanian officers)  abused the [[white flag]], and attacked and killed all the Serbian soldiers.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> The Serbian army subsequently used this as an excuse for the brutal retaliation against civilians.\n\nThe Serbian army entered Pristina on October 22.<ref name=\"Trix\">{{cite book |last1=Trix |first1=Francis |title=Urban Muslim Migrants in Istanbul: Identity and Trauma Among Balkan Immigrants |date=2008 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=1786731088 |page=44 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBOMDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA44 |ref=Trix}}</ref> The events that followed, resulted in the destruction of Albanian and Turkish households, the massacre of children and women, widespread looting and violation of human rights.<ref name=\"Karoubi174\"/> Based in Skopje, a Danish journalist reported that the campaign of the Serbian army in Prishtina \"had taken on the character of a horrific massacring of the Albanian population\".<ref name=\"Trix\"/><ref name=\"Karoubi174\"/> The number of Albanians of Pristina killed in the early days after the Serbian army took over the town is estimated at 5,000.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/><ref name=\"Karoubi174\"/><ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/12/31/100385991.pdf|title=SERVIAN ARMY LEFT A TRAIL OF BLOOD; Thousands of Men, Women, and Children Massacred in March to Sea, Say Hungarian Reports.|accessdate=6 September 2016}}</ref> The events have been interpreted as an early policy that aimed to change the demographic status of the area.<ref name=\"Trix\"/>\n\nAfterwards, Serbian settlers were brought in the city and [[Nikola pasic|Nikola Pasic]], at the time the [[Prime Minister of Serbia]], bought 1,214 acres of land.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Banac |first1=Ivo |title=The National Question in Yugoslavia: Origins, History, Politics |date=1988 |publisher=Cornell University Press |isbn=978-0-8014-9493-2 |page=296 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KfqbujXqQBkC&pg=PA295&dq=slaughter+of+Albanians+1912#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the town, people who wore a [[Qeleshe|plis]] were targeted by the Serbian army and those who wore the Turkish [[fez]] remained safe. This caused the price of the fez in the town's market to skyrocket. On October 18, 1912, 82 Turkish [[fez]] could be bought for one Turkish lira. On November 10, 1912, at the same market, a fez could be bought for 82 lira.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Horvat, Dr. Jusuf Osmani |first1=Mislav |title=Jusuf Osmani - Kolonizimi Serbi Kosoves (The Serbian colonisation of Kosovo) |date=2010 |publisher=REND Prishtin\u00eb |location=Pristina |page=67 |edition=Se n\u00eb tregun e Prishtin\u00ebs, m\u00eb 18 tetor 1912 m\u00eb nj\u00eb lir\u00eb ari t\u00eb Turqis\u00eb mund t\u00eb bliheshin 82 fesa turq. M\u00eb 10 n\u00ebntor 1912, po n\u00eb k\u00ebt\u00eb treg, nj\u00eb fes mund t\u00eb blihej me 82 lira ari. Ngritja kaq e lart\u00eb e \u00e7mimit ishte b\u00ebr\u00eb p\u00ebr shkak se ushtria serbe likuidonte t\u00eb gjith\u00eb njer\u00ebzit me plisa t\u00eb bardh\u00eb, nd\u00ebrsa i kursente ata q\u00eb mbanin fesin turk n\u00eb krye. (Translation: On the 18th of October 1912, at the market of Pristina, 82 Turkish fez could be bought with a cheaper Turkish gold. On November 10, 1912, at the same market, a slice could be bought for 82 gold. The price hike was so high that the Serbian army liquidated all plis wearing people while saving those who held the Turkish fez at the top. |url=https://www.academia.edu/27205754/Jusuf_Osmani_-_Kolonizimi_Serbi_Kosoves.pdf |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Gazimestan====\nIn 1913, when Serb forces entered [[Gazimestan]], they massacred 5000 Albanians.<ref>Dr. Hakif Bajrami, \"Politika e shfarosjes s\u00eb shqiptar\u00ebve dhe kolonizimi serb I Kosov\u00ebs\" (1844-1945), Prishtin\u00eb, 1995, p. 17.</ref>\n\n====Gjakova====\n[[Gjakova]] was mentioned among the cities that suffered at the hands of the Serbian-Montenegrin army. ''The New York Times'' reported that people on the [[gallows]] hanged on both sides of the road, and that the way to Yakova became a \"gallows alley.\"<ref name=\"NY Times\"/> In the region of Yakova, the Montenegrin police-military formation ''Kraljevski \u017eandarmerijski kor'', known as krila\u0161i, committed many abuses and violence against the Albanian population.<ref>''Krila\u0161i'', Istorijski leksikon Crne Gore, Daily Press, Podgorica, 2006.</ref>\n\nIn Gjakova, Serbian priests carried out a violent conversion of Albanian [[Catholics]] to [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Serbian Orthodoxy]].<ref name=\"Mirdita\"/> Vienna ''[[Neue Freie Presse]]'' (20 March 1913) reported that Orthodox priests with the help of military force converted 300 Gjakova Catholics to the Orthodox faith, and that [[Franciscan Order|Franciscan]] Pater Angelus, who refused to renounce his faith, was tortured and then killed with [[bayonet]]s. The History Institute in Pristina has claimed that Montenegro converted over 1,700 Albanian Catholics to the Serbian Orthodox faith in the area of Gjakova in March 1913.<ref name=\"Institute II\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kosova.com/arkivi1997/expuls/chap2.htm|title=chapter 2|first=Edmond|last=Hajrullaaga|accessdate=6 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031192729/http://www.kosova.com/arkivi1997/expuls/chap2.htm|archivedate=31 October 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[Count Albert von Mensdorff-Pouilly-Dietrichstein]] also told [[Edward Grey, 1st Viscount Grey of Fallodon|Edward Grey]] in an interview on 10 March 1912, that the Serbian soldiers committed numerous atrocities on both Muslim an Catholic Albanians in Gjakova, acting in a \"barbarous way\".<ref>{{cite book |author=Great Britain Foreign Office |title=The Balkan wars. pt. 1. The prelude; the Tripoli war. pt. 2. The league and Turkey |date=1934 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Office |page=569 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=2TguIIjeeb0C&pg=PA1122&dq=Servian+atrocities#v=onepage&q=Servian%20atrocities&f=false |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Prizren====\nAfter the Serbian army achieved control over the city of [[Prizren]], it imposed repressive measures against the Albanian civilian population. Serbian detachments broke into houses, plundered, committed acts of violence, and killed indiscriminately.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> Around 400 people were \"eradicated\" in the first days of the Serbian military administration.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> During those days bodies were lying everywhere on the streets. According to witnesses, during those days around Prizren lay about 1,500 corpses of Albanians.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> Foreign reporters were not allowed to go to Prizren.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> After the operations of the Serbian military and paramilitary units, Prizren became one of the most devastated cities of the [[Kosovo vilayet]] and people called it \"the Kingdom of Death\".<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> Eventually, General [[Bo\u017eidar Jankovi\u0107]] forced surviving Albanian leaders of Prizren to sign a statement of gratitude to the Serbian king [[Peter I Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107]] for their [[liberty|liberation]].<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> It is estimated that 5,000 Albanians was massacred in the area of Prizren.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> [[British people|British]] traveller [[Edith Durham]] and a [[British Armed Forces|British military attach\u00e9]] were supposed to visit Prizren in October 1912, however the trip was prevented by the authorities. Durham stated \"I asked wounded Montengrins [Soldiers] why I was not allowed to go and they laughed and said 'We have not left a [[Human nose|nose]] on an Albanian up there!' Not a pretty sight for a British officer.\"<ref name=\"Karoubi174\">{{cite book|last=Karoubi|first=Mohammad Taghi|title=Just or Unjust War?: International Law and Unilateral Use of Armed Force by States at the Turn of the 20th Century|year=2017|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351154666|url=https://books.google.com/?id=v_dADwAAQBAJ&pg=PT268&dq=archbishop+skopje+massacres#v=onepage&q=archbishop%20skopje%20massacres&f=false|pages=174|ref=harv}}</ref> Eventually Durham visited a northern Albanian outpost in Kosovo where she met captured Ottoman soldiers whose [[upper lip]]s and noses had been cut off.<ref name=\"malcolm p253\">{{cite book|last1=[[Noel Malcolm]]|title=Kosovo: A Short History|date=1998|publisher=papermac|location=London|isbn=9780330412247|page=253}}</ref>\n\nThe town of Prizren offered no resistance to Serb forces, but this did not avert a bloodbath there. After Prishtina, Prizren was the hardest hit of the Albanian towns. The local population called it the \"Kingdom of Death\". Serb forces forced their way into homes and beat up anyone and everyone in their way, irrespective of age or sex. Corpses lined the streets for days while the Serbian victors continued with brutality, and the native population which had survived did not dare to venture out of their homes. The attacks continued night after night throughout the town and region. Up to 400 people perished in the first few days of the Serbian occupation. When the Serbian troops were about to set off westwards, they could not find any horses to transport their equipment so they used 200 Albanians and forced them to carry the goods. Most of them collapsed during the journey and the Serbian commander expressed his satisfaction and approval of the action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_1.html |title=1913 {{!}} Leo Freundlich: Albania's Golgotha: Indictment of the Exterminators of the Albanian People |accessdate=17 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531131757/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_1.html |archivedate=31 May 2012 |publisher=albanianhistory.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IHgtAQAAIAAJ|title=Albania's Golgotha: indictments of the exterminators of the Albanian people|first=Leo|last=Freundlich|date=1 January 1998|publisher=Juka Pub. Co.|accessdate=6 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n====Rugova====\nIn 1913, General [[Janko Vukoti\u0107|Janko Vukotic]] told British traveler [[Edith Durham]] that his soldiers had committed atrocities against the civilian population of Rugova; in response to her protests, he reportedly said \"but they are beasts, savage animals. We have done very well\",<ref name=jezernik>{{cite book |last1=Jezernik |first1=Bo\u017eidar |title=Wild Europe: The Balkans in the Gaze of Western Travellers |date=2004 |publisher=Saqi |isbn=978-0-86356-574-8 |page=109 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ji5pAAAAMAAJ&dq=Janko+Vukotic+Rugova&q=Rugova |accessdate=21 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> which Slovene author Bo\u017eidar Jezernik interprets as an attestation of the Montenegrin goal of removing local Muslims from their newly captured territories, and resettling the lands.<ref name=jezernik/>\n\n====Ferizaj====\nThe capture of ''Ferizovik'' as the town was known in Ottoman times by the Serbian army and the events that followed were documented in contemporary accounts. The entry of the Serbian army was followed by a massacre of the population.<ref name=\"Trix\"/> Leo Freundlich recorded on his [[Albania's Golgotha]] the existing reports about the situation in Ferizaj at the time. The Italian war correspondent of ''[[Il Messaggero]]'' of Rome reported that the town was destroyed and most of its inhabitants were killed.<ref name=\"Freundlich\">{{cite book |last1=Freundlich |first1=Leo |editor1-last=Elsie |editor1-first=Robert |editor2-last=Destani |editor2-first=Bejtullah |title=Kosovo, A Documentary History: From the Balkan Wars to World War II |url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/1913_Freundlich_Golgotha/index.html |accessdate=29 March 2020 |ref=Freundlich}}</ref> A Catholic priest in the region reported that resistance had been strong for three days against the advancing Serbian army. When the town was finally taken, the locals who were fleeing the town were invited back in the town on the condition that they surrendered their arms. After the surrender of arms, the army went on to kill about 300 to 400 people. Only a few Muslim families remained in the town after this event.<ref name=\"Freundlich\"/> Freundlich put the total number of deaths at 1,200.<ref name=\"Freundlich\"/>\n\nAnother source of first-hand accounts in the region was [[Leon Trotsky]], who at the time was a war correspondent for the Kiev newspaper ''Kievskaya Misl''. His reports about Ferizaj describe the killings and looting which took place after the town was captured by the Serbian army.<ref name=\"Trotsky\">{{cite web |last1=Trotsky |first1=Leon |title=Behind the Curtains of the Balkan Wars |url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/1912_Trotsky/index.html |accessdate=29 March 2020 |ref=Trotsky}}</ref>\n\n====Luma====\n[[File:Krahina e Lum\u00ebs - (Luma region).png|thumb|150x150px|Luma region]]\nDuring the [[Balkan wars]] (1912-1913), Serb military forces attempting to assert their control of the region entered [[Luma (region)|Luma]] and attacked local inhabitants, killed tribal chieftains, removed livestock belonging to the population and razed villages.<ref name=\"Levene107\"/> The actions resulted in a local uprising by Albanians.<ref name=\"Levene107\"/> Serb forces retaliated through a scorched earth policy and massacres of the population ranging from the young to elderly, both men and women such as barricading people in mosques and houses and then firing upon or burning them.<ref name=\"Levene107\"/> Following the events, 25,000 people fled to Kosovo and western Macedonia.<ref name=\"Levene107\"/> The events have been considered by scholar Mark Levine as constituting a \"localized genocide\".<ref name=\"Levene107\">{{cite book|last=Levene|first=Mark|title=The Crisis of Genocide. Volume I: Devastation: The European Rimlands 1912\u20131938|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199683031|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RRgbAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA107&dq=Luma+genocide#v=onepage&q=Luma%20genocide&f=false|pages=107|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nWhen General Jankovi\u0107 saw that the Albanians of [[Lum\u00eb (region)|Luma]] would not allow Serbian forces to continue the advance to the Adriatic Sea, he ordered the troops to continue their brutality.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> The Serbian army massacred an entire population of men, women and children, not sparing anyone, and burned down 100-200houses and 27 villages in the area of Luma.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> Reports spoke of the atrocities by the Serbian army, including the burning of women and children bound to stacks of hay, within the sight of their fathers.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> Subsequently, about 400 men from Luma surrendered to Serbian authorities, but were taken to [[Prizren]], where they were murdered.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> The ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote that \"all the horrors of history have been outdone by the atrocious conduct of the troops of General Jankovic\".<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/>\n\nThe second Luma massacre was committed the following year (1913). After the London Ambassador Conference decided that Luma should be within the Albanian state, the Serbian army initially refused to withdraw. Albanians raised a great rebellion in September 1913, after which Luma once again suffered harsh retaliation from the Serbian army. A report of the International Commission cited a letter of a Serbian soldier, who described the punitive expedition against the rebel Albanians:<ref name=\"Report\"/>\n\n{{quote|My dear Friend, I have no time to write to you at length, but I can tell you that appalling things are going on here. I am terrified by them, and constantly ask myself how men can be so barbarous as to commit such cruelties. It is horrible. I dare not tell you more, but I may say that Luma (an Albanian region along the river of the same name), no longer exists. There is nothing but corpses, dust and ashes. There are villages of 100, 150, 200 houses, where there is no longer a single man, literally not one. We collect them in bodies of forty to fifty, and then we pierce them with our bayonets to the last man. Pillage is going on everywhere. The officers told the soldiers to go to Prizren and sell the things they had stolen.\"}}\n\nItalian daily newspaper ''Corriere delle Puglie'' wrote in December 1913 about official report that was sent to the Great Powers with details of the slaughter of Albanians in Luma and [[Debar]], executed after the proclamation of the amnesty by Serbian authorities. The report listed the names of people killed by Serbian units in addition to the causes of death: by burning, slaughtering, bayonets, etc. The report also provided a detailed list of the burned and looted villages in the area of Luma and Has.<ref name=\"Dibra\">[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_4.html Dole in Dibra: Official Report Submitted to the Great Powers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518073341/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_4.html |date=18 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nA [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] priest who visited Luma reported seeing \"[[Infanticide|poor bayonetted babies]]\" on the streets.<ref name=\"Twenty Years Of Balkan Tangle\">{{cite book |last1=Edith |first1=Durham |title=Twenty Years Of Balkan Tangle |date=1920 |page=246 |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.234333/page/n245/mode/2up/search/shala |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Kumanovo====\nBritish army officer [[Christopher Birdwood Thomson]] was told by a Serbian general in Belgrade in 1913 that after the [[Battle of Kumanovo|3rd Serbian Army]] defeated the Turkish forces in Kumanovo, they entered the city and wiped out entire villages, massacring men, women and children in their homes, forcing others to flee resulting in death due to famine and cold. In 1920, he writes: \n{{Quote|text=Nothing more terrible has taken place in any part of the world, or in the whole history of war.|sign=Christopher Birdwood Thomson|source=Old Europe's Suicide: The Building of a Pyramid of Errors. Library of Alexandria, 1920}}\n\n====Gostivar====\nAfter the [[Battle of Kumanovo]] on October 23\u201324, 1912, the Serbian army [[First Army (Serbia)|Morava division]] entered [[Gostivar]], where hundreds of Albanians were massacred, which resulted in protests from Vienna. [[Leopold Berchtold]] was appalled by the massacres and asked Belgrade to withdraw from Albanian territory.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brook-Shepherd |first1=Gordon |title=The Austrians: A Thousand-Year Odyssey |date=2009 |publisher=Basic Books |isbn=978-0-7867-3066-7 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=z3s4DgAAQBAJ&pg=PT128&lpg=PT128&dq=leopold+berchtold+massacre+Albanians&source=bl&ots=uzwEmwMQMZ&sig=ACfU3U2wtSRdxvsZLkyijUoELSNxv8892w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjqqreRz73oAhUBw8QBHRU6AxUQ6AEwCXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=massacred&f=false |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On November 21, 1912, he wrote letters to Paris, London, Berlin, Rome and Petrograd where he stated: \u201cThe behavior of the Serbian army towards the Albanian people does not belong to any international human rights norm, but after the occupation of the countries they choose no means of dealing with it anymore. They acted brutally against the innocent and defenseless population\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pajaziti |first1=Ali |title=SHQIPTAR\u00cbT E REK\u00cbS S\u00cb EP\u00cbRME |pages=132\u2013133 |edition=\"Pas pushtimit t\u00eb trevave shqiptare nga ana e ushtris\u00eb serbe, fillon nj\u00eb faz\u00eb tjet\u00ebr shum\u00eb e tmerrshme dhe e dhembshme p\u00ebr shqiptar\u00ebt, nga shkaku se ushtria serbe beri masakra n\u00eb t\u00eb gjitha viset e pushtuara. K\u00ebto masakra t\u00eb egra dhe barbare u v\u00ebrejt\u00ebn edhe nga ana e Fuqive t\u00eb M\u00ebdha, por reagoi vet\u00ebm Vjena. N\u00eb letr\u00ebn e Berhtoldit d\u00ebrguar Parisit, Londr\u00ebs, Berlinit, Rom\u00ebs dhe Petrogradit thuhet: \u201cSjellja e ushtris\u00eb serbe ndaj popullit shqiptar nuk i p\u00ebrket asnj\u00eb norme nd\u00ebrkomb\u00ebtare p\u00ebr t\u00eb drejtat e njeriut, por ato pas pushtimit t\u00eb vendeve nuk zgjedhin mjete sesi me u sjell\u00eb m\u00eb brutalisht ndaj popullat\u00ebs s\u00eb pafajshme dhe t\u00eb pambrojtur\" |url=https://www.academia.edu/23459558/SHQIPTAR\u00cbT_E_REK\u00cbS_S\u00cb_EP\u00cbRME |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>HHStA-PAA Letters of Berchtold sent to the Great Powers. Dok. Nr. 4545</ref>\n\n====Mitrovica====\nOn 18 November 1912, Sir F. Cartwright sent a letter to Sir Edward Grey explaining how the Serbian army entered Mitrovica and arrested the Austrian consul and held him prisoner for 15 days until he escaped to Budapest after he had witnessed atrocities being committed on Albanian civilians.<ref>{{cite book |author=Great Britain Foreign Office |title=The Balkan wars. pt. 1. The prelude; the Tripoli war. pt. 2. The league and Turkey |date=1934 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Office |page=168 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=2TguIIjeeb0C&pg=PA1122&dq=Servian+atrocities#v=onepage&q=Servian%20atrocities&f=false |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> According to an article in the ''Japan Times & Mail'' in 1912, the reason for the arrest of the consuls of Prizren and Mitrovica was the Serbian government did not want news to reach Austria that the Serbian soldiers had massacred Albanian civilians.<ref>{{cite book |title=Japan Times & Mail |date=1912 |page=352 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=bIQ-AQAAMAAJ&q=massacre+Mitrovitza&dq=massacre+Mitrovitza |accessdate=31 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Vusthrri====\nOn August 13, 1913, 17 Albanian civilians were massacred by Serbian soldiers when they entered [[Vushtrri]]. The event was despatched from the British Vice Consul W.D. Peckham in Skopje to the British Ambassador [[Sir Ralph Paget]] in Belgrade.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Elsie |first1=Robert |last2=Destani |first2=Bejtullah D. |title=Kosovo, A Documentary History: From the Balkan Wars to World War II |date=2018 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1-78673-354-2 |page=169 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=dbqKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR14&lpg=PR14&dq=Leopold+Berchtold+Serbia+Kosovo&source=bl&ots=CoskfT5R0L&sig=ACfU3U0RA3EIxP9EdMuObGpgZa5pC5uejw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj1x-2F0r3oAhVkw4sKHaLwBAAQ6AEwDHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=massacre&f=false |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Peja====\nIn 1912, the Serbian army bombarded the city of Peja and razed village after village, and were aided by Chetnik paramilitaries.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Remzije Sherifi (1955) |first1=Ibrahim Rugova |title=La Question Du Kosovo (The Shadow Behind The Sun|location=Prishtina |page=53 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=RIruxQEACAAJ&dq=Shadow+Behind+The+Sun+Remzije+Sherifi&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjp1JTkubroAhUotYsKHdMBA4MQ6AEIKDAA|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n[[Edith Durham]] writes about refugees from Peja after the Serbian army entered in 1913: \n\"An Ipek man, well educated and of high standing, told of what happened there. \"Every day the telal cried in the streets 'To-day the Government will shoot ten (or more men! No one knew which men they would be, or why they were shot. They were stood in a trench, which was to be their grave. Twelve soldiers fired and as the victims fell the earth was shovellwed over them, wether living or dead. Baptisms were forcd by torture. Men were plunged into the ice-cold river, and then half roased till they cried for mercy\". Many, terrorized into baptism, came to me\".<ref name=\"Twenty Years Of Balkan Tangle\"/>\n\n====Gusinje and Plav====\nAfter the [[armistice]], Serbian troops bombarded the villages of Gusinje and Plav, rushed them and threw hand grenades, burning the villages, resulting an exodus of Albanian women and children fleeing to the mountains with many dying in the snow. An English doctor in Scutari examined the bands of refugees and travelled to Gusinje to examine the area and was immediately arrested by Serbian soldiers.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Saturday Review of Politics, Literature, Science and Art |date=1920 |publisher=Saturday Review |pages=276, 330 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-xs8AQAAMAAJ&dq=bombarding+at+Gusinje&q=bombarded |accessdate=31 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Novi Pazar====\nCaptain Carlo Papa di Castiglione d'Asti (1869-1955) was an Italian Major and military attach\u00e9 in Belgrade and Bucharest between 1908 and 1913 who observed the advancing Serbian Army. He reported that the Serbian army exterminated the Albanian population of Novi Pazar in order to facilitate Serbian domination.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rudi\u0107 |first1=Sr\u0111an |last2=Biagini |first2=Antonello |title=Serbian-Italian Relations: History and Modern Times : Collection of Works |date=2015 |publisher=The Institute of History, Belgrade / Sapienza University of Rome, Research center CEMAS |isbn=978-86-7743-109-9 |pages=79\u201380 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_7RPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA80&dq=Serbian+army+massacred+Albanians+1913#v=onepage&q=Albanians&f=false |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Serb troops entered Sandzak, they massacred hundreds of civilians.<ref>Rugova, Sherifi, La Question Du Kosovo, The Shadow Behind The Sun, p. 53</ref>\n\nWhen the Ibar Army, commanded by General Mihailo Zivkovic, entered the town, he pacified the Albanian population with the method of \"soletudinem facient pacem appelant\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Richard C. |title=The Balkan Wars 1912-1913: Prelude to the First World War |date=2002 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-134-58362-1 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=DziCAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT231&lpg=PT231&dqXoECA0QLw#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Vilayet of Monastir ===\n\nIn the town of [[Ohrid]], Serbian forces killed 500 people consisting of Albanians and Turks.<ref name=\"Kramer138\">{{harvnb|Kramer|2008|p=138}}</ref>\n\n====Dibra====\nOn 20 September, the [[Serbian army]] carried off all the cattle of the Mal\u00ebsia of Dibra. The herdsmen were compelled to defend themselves, and to struggle, but they were all killed. The Serbians also killed two chieftains of the [[Lum\u00eb (region)|Luma]] clan, [[Mehmed Edem]] and [[Djafer Eleuz]], and the began pillaging and burning all the villages on their way: [[Peshkopi]], [[Blli\u00e7\u00eb]], and [[Dohoshisht]] in lower Dibra; and another seven villages in upper Dibra. In all these villages the Serbians committed acts of horrible massacres and outrage on women, children and old people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/reportofinternat00inteuoft#page/150/mode/2up|title=Report of the International Commission to Inquire into the Causes and Conduct of the Balkan War|accessdate=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs the Serbian Army invaded Albania through Dibra, Elbasan and Shkod\u00ebr, they bombarded cities and villages with artillery. The Albanian government telegraphed their delegates in Paris stating that the aim was the suppression of the Albanian state and the extermination of the Albanian population.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Nation |date=1920 |publisher=Nation Publishing Company Limited |page=626 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=cfFQAQAAMAAJ&dq=In+response%2C+during+the+fall+of+1913%2C+Serbian+troops+further+razed+Albanian+villages&q=bombarded |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an article in The Daily Mirror from 1914, interviewing Mr William Howard, an American relief commissioner, he states that in Dibra the Serbian troops destroyed 100 villages with 12,000 houses, and between 4000-8000 Albanians were burned, bayonetted or shot to death.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Archives |first1=British News Paper |title=\"Albanian Peasants Tortured and Burned Alive by Servians\" |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/BL/0000560/19140202/063/0009?browse=true |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk |agency=Daily Mirror |issue=Page 4 and 9 |publisher=The Daily Mirror |date=February 2, 1914}}</ref>\n\n====Pelagonia====\nIn September 1912, Serb majors M. Vasi\u0107 and [[Vasilije Trbi\u0107]] gathered 30 [[Chetniks]] and travelled to the village of [[Desovo]] where they shot 111 Albanian men and razed the village.<ref name=\"Timofeev271\"/> In nearby [[Brailovo]], Trbi\u0107 executed 60 Albanians.<ref name=\"Timofeev271\">{{cite book|last=Timofeev|first=Alexey|chapter=Serbian Chetniks: Traditions of Irregular Warfare|editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Wars of Yesterday: The Balkan Wars and the Emergence of Modern Military Conflict, 1912-13|year=2018|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=9781785337758|url=https://books.google.com/?id=okMtDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Wars+of+Yesterday:+The+Balkan+Wars+and+the+Emergence+of+Modern+Military+Conflict,+1912-13#v=snippet&q=Desovo&f=false|pages=271|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n====Porcasi and Sulp====\nIn these villages Porcasi and Sulp, Serbian soldiers took all the men out and asked the women to pay for their release. After payment, they were put inside a mosque which was blown up. In Sulp, 73 Albanians were murdered as well.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Prifti |first1=Kristaq |title=The Truth on Kosova |date=1993 |publisher=Encyclopaedia Publishing House |page=173 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YBq5AAAAIAAJ&dq=the+greatest+massacres+of+the+Albanian+population&q=massacred |accessdate=24 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Eyewitness accounts and reports==\nFor 12 years, the British anthropologist [[Edith Durham]] traveled to the region and became deeply interested in and knowledgeable of Albania and Albanians.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/><ref name=\"Hopken229\"/> In August 1912, Durham was in Montenegro and saw firsthand Montenegrin preparations for war along the border and altered the British press.<ref name=\"Dauti9495\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|pp=94-94}}</ref> She thought Montenegro was attempting to provoke the Ottomans into a conflict and Durham witnessed the outbreak of hostilities when Montenegrin king [[Nicholas I of Montenegro|Nikola]] directed his army to fire artillery shots into Albania.<ref name=\"Dauti95\"/> As the war began, Durham dispatched the news to the British press and for a prolonged period was the only war correspondent from the Montenegrin area.<ref name=\"Dauti95\"/> Newspapers sought her reports and Durham wrote over the course of many days for the [[Evening Chronicle|Chronicle]] and [[Manchester Guardian]], later she ceased after finding out they \"were cutting and even doctoring her articles\".<ref name=\"Dauti95\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=95}}</ref>\n\nEarly on in the conflict Durham, as a nurse, was involved in humanitarian relief work with the Red Cross and became aware of the atrocities.<ref name=\"Dauti97\"/><ref name=\"Hopken229\"/> Durham was close to the theatre of war and described the razed villages, the refugees and their dire plight, such as some resorting to sheltering in outhouses.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> She wrote a strongly worded indictment on the behavior of Serbs and Montenegrins.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/> Durham recounted in one instance that she went to see over thousand families whose homes were razed and referred to the negative views Montenegrins held against Albanians.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/> She encountered people from the frontlines like a Serb officer who viewed his time in Kosovo as \"heroism\" and \"nearly choked with laughter\" as he talked about how he \"bayoneted the women and children of Luma\".<ref name=\"Dauti97\"/> Durham heard sentiments from more officers about how \"no one would dare speak the dirty language\" (Albanian) in the newly acquired territories.<ref name=\"Dauti97\"/> Speaking in an open manner, they told Durham of the violence used to convert Catholic and Muslim Albanians into Orthodox Christianity.<ref name=\"Dauti97\"/> At the Montenegrin-Albanian frontier, Durham in her accounts described mutilation of \"nose cutting\" and other body parts sliced for \"their commanders\".<ref name=\"Hopken229\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2006|p=229}}</ref> The events of the war made Durham end her friendship with King Nikola due to the actions of the Montenegrin army.<ref name=\"Dauti959699\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|pp=95\u201396, 99}}</ref> At the time, the Albanian leadership used reports by Durham as firm evidence to strengthen their own nationalist rhetoric and put forward a position that objected to the violence committed by various armed forces present in the region, due to the war.<ref name=\"Dauti99\"/>\n\n[[Leon Trotsky]], later one of the leading figures of the Russian revolution, was at the time sent by a socialist Kiev newspaper as its wartime journalist to cover the Balkan Wars and he reported on the violence committed toward Albanians.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/><ref name=\"Trix42\"/> In the space of a few days after Skopje came under Serb control, Trotsky described the situation in and surrounding the city.<ref name=\"Trix42\"/> Trotsky was not present directly in the theatre of war, and he compiled his information from discussions he had with witnesses such as a Serbian friend who referred to \"horrors\" in the region of Macedonia.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/> The same friend had gained a military pass to travel to Skopje and told Trotsky:<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/><ref name=\"Trix42\"/>\n\n{{quotation|...the horrors actually began as soon as we crossed the old frontier. By five p.m. we were approaching Kumanovo. The sun had set, it was starting to get dark. But the darker the sky became, the more brightly the fearful illumination of the fires stood out against it. Burning was going on all around us. Entire Albanian villages had been turned into pillars of fire... In all its fiery monotony this picture was repeated the whole way to Skopje... For two days before my arrival in Skopje the inhabitants had woken up in the morning to the sight, under the principal bridge over the Vardar- that is, in the very centre of the town- of heaps of Albanian corpses with severed heads. Some said that these were local Albanians, killed by the ''komitadjis'' [''cjetniks''], others that the corpses were brought down to the bridge by the waters of the Vardar. What was clear was that these headless men had not been killed in battle.<ref name=\"Glenny234\">{{cite book|last=Glenny|first=Misha|title=The Balkans, 1804\u20132012: Nationalism, War and the Great Powers|publisher=Granta Books|isbn=9781847087720|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BVdheJDLWnkC&pg=PT6&dq=The+Balkans,+1804%E2%80%932012:+Nationalism,+War+and+the+Great+Powers#v=onepage&q=the%20horrors%20actually%20began%20as%20soon%20as%20we%20crossed&f=false|pages=234|ref=harv|date=November 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/><ref name=\"Trix42\"/>}}\n\nThe account given to Trotsky by the Serbian friend referred to the actions of Serb troops and their responsibility in Skopje for looting, fires, and in one example, the torture of local Albanian inhabitants of whom they spoke publicly about their deeds.<ref name=\"Vourkoutiotis1112\">{{cite book|last=Vourkoutiotis|first=Vasilis|title=Reform in Revolutionary Times: The Civil-military Relationship in Early Soviet Russia|year=2009|publisher=|isbn=978-1-4331-0210-3|url=https://books.google.com/?id=g0C3kXGeGQIC&pg=PA11&dq=Albanian+civilians+1912#v=onepage&q=Albanian%20civilians%201912&f=false|pages=11\u201312|ref=harv}}</ref> Many of the events in Skopje took place at night by Serb paramilitaries and in the morning, hundreds of headless Albanian corpses were in the Vardar river at the main bridge.<ref name=\"Trix42\"/> There was certainty that the bodies were not casualties from warfare and ambiguity on whether they were Albanians from the area or had flowed down from the upstream part of the Vardar.<ref name=\"Trix42\"/> The destruction of villages through arson resulted in the loss of homes and amassed wealth of targeted Albanians, whereas irregular troops entered homes to kill and steal.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/> Trotsky's Serbian friend described that Skopje had turned into a military camp and among the troops there were Serb peasants engaged in looting food, livestock and the doors and windows from Albanian houses.<ref name=\"Trix42\"/>\n\nIn observations of Serbian officers, the informant expressed disgust with their brutality and in moments of confrontation regarding their behavior, a corporal said to him that they differed from the komitajis (paramilitaries).<ref name=\"Trix42\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|p=42}}</ref> The corporal stated that the army \"would not kill anyone younger than twelve years of age\", whereas \"the komitajis engage in murder, robbery and violence as a savage sport\".<ref name=\"Trix4243\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|pp=42\u201343}}</ref> Authorities from the army responded by sending some komitajis home, due to the embarrassment they caused to the military.<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> The Serb informant wrote to Trotsky that \"meat is rotting, human flesh as well as the flesh of oxen\" and that the conflict \"brutalized\" people and made them lose \"their human aspect\".<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> Trotsky's Serbian friend also encountered a corporal in Kosovo who after being questioned about his actions responded \"Roasting chickens and killing Arnauts [Albanians]. But we're tired of it.\"<ref name=\"Lieberman59\">{{harvnb|Lieberman|2013|p=59}}</ref> In his report sent to Kiev newspaper ''Kievskaya Misl'' Trotsky writes about many \"atrocities committed against the Albanians of Macedonia and Kosovo in the wake of the Serbian invasion of October 1912\".<ref name=\"albanianhistory.net\">Robert Elsie, [http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1912_2.html Leo Trotsky: Behind the Curtains of the Balkan Wars] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212030202/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1912_2.html |date=12 December 2013 }}</ref> Trotsky reported that when [[Peter I of Serbia]] was on a tour at the frontlines, he said that Albanians ought to be clubbed till death as they did not deserve the ammunition.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mojzes |first1=Paul |title=Balkan Genocides: Holocaust and Ethnic Cleansing in the Twentieth Century |date=2011 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1-4422-0663-2 |page=32 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KwW2O7v7CUcC&pg=PA211&dq=how+many+Albanians+have+the+Servians+massacred#v=onepage&q=1912&f=false |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Qirezi46\">{{cite book|last=Qirezi|first=Arben|chapter=Settling the self-determination dispute in Kosovo|editor1-last=Mehmeti|editor1-first=Leandrit I.|editor2-last=Radelji\u0107|editor2-first=Branislav|title=Kosovo and Serbia: Contested Options and Shared Consequences|year=2017|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press|isbn=9780822981572|chapter-url=https://books.google.se/books?id=IWMqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT74&dq=chetniks+cruelty+Kosovo&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiOi-vg09joAhUypIsKHXwcBy0Q6AEIMjAB#v=snippet&q=1912&f=false|pages=46|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nAmong other instances he tells a shocking case of drunken Serbian soldiers torturing two young Albanians.\n\n<blockquote>Four soldiers held their bayonets in readiness and in their midst stood two young Albanians with their white felt caps on their heads. A drunken sergeant \u2013 a komitadji \u2013 was holding a kama (a Macedonian dagger) in one hand and a bottle of cognac in the other. The sergeant ordered: 'On your knees!' The petrified Albanians fell to their knees. 'To your feet!' They stood up. This was repeated several times. Then the sergeant, threatening and cursing, put the dagger to the necks and chests of his victims and forced them to drink some cognac, and then\u2026 he kissed them... Drunk with power, cognac and blood, he was having fun, playing with them as a cat would with mice. The same gestures and the same psychology behind them. The other three soldiers, who were not drunk, stood by and took care that the Albanians did not escape or try to resist, so that the sergeant could enjoy his moment of rapture. 'They're Albanians,' said one of the soldiers to me dispassionately. 'Hell soon put them out of their misery.',</blockquote>\n\nTrotsky wrote several dispatches and sent them home where he described the atrocities saying ''\"an individual, a group, a party of a class that is capable of 'objectively' picking its nose while it watches men drunk with blood, and incited from above, massacring defenceless people is condemned by history to rot and become worm-eaten while it is still alive\".''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Trotsky |first1=Leon |title=The Balkan Wars, 1912-13: The War Correspondence of Leon Trotsky |date=1980 |publisher=Resistance Books |isbn=978-0-909196-08-0 |page=293 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=tEJmenVPZ-IC&pg=PA293&dq=Leon+Trotsky++an+individual,+a+group,+a+party+of+a+class+that+is+capable+of+%27objectively%27+picking+its+nose+while+it+watches+men+drunk+with+blood,+and+incited+from+above,+massacring+defenceless+people+is+condemned+by+history+to+rot+and+become+worm-eaten+while+it+is+still+alive#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn report by the British Foreign Office, a description of a telegram by the Italian consul in Skopje stated that \"atrocities being committed by Serbian troops and their evident intention of extirpating as many of the Albanian inhabitants as possible\".<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> A Swiss engineer, employed as an overseer for the Oriental railway submitted a report to the British embassy in Belgrade that gave details regarding Skopje following the arrival of Serbian soldiers.<ref name=\"Trix43241\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|pp=43, 241}}</ref> The report described that the conduct of Serbs against the Muslim population was \"cruel in every way\" and appeared to \"have for its object their complete extermination\".<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> The Swiss engineer had written that the sound of arms discharged began from early in the day and continued till late, and prisoners were treated badly such as officers shot without trials.<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> The report described that \"an order was issued to soldiers in certain places to kill all Albanians from the age of eight years upwards with a view to extermination. The Serbians have ill treated the sick, women and children.\"<ref name=\"Trix43\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|p=43}}</ref> Other details in the report described that mosques were destroyed, villages razed in their entirety and that the number of bodies floating in the Vardar were some 500.<ref name=\"Trix4344\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|pp=43\u201344}}</ref> The Swiss engineer summed up the situation and said that \"the Albanians were \"desperate\".<ref name=\"Trix44\"/>\n\n=== Historicity of information ===\nScholarship treats wartime correspondences from the entire Balkan Wars as first-hand evidence and historian Wolfgang H\u00f6pken says those sources need to be handled with care.<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/> H\u00f6pken states that reporters, such as Trotsky who provided first hand data were not near the theatre of war,<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/> however, his accounts of the Balkan Wars were \"some of the most brilliant and most analytical war reports\".<ref name=\"Hopken234\"/>\n\nJournalists of the time based in the Balkans like Richard von Mach from K\u00f6lnische Zeitung described that the accounts were often either data from a third party or \"even pure fiction\".<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/> Writers such as Carl Pauli attained their data from nameless witnesses or gathered evidence from the extensive compilation of information by Leo Freundlich, who wrote about the situation in the Albanian conflict zone and expressed empathy for Albanian victims.<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/> H\u00f6pken states that these sources have significance, although the information given \"can hardly be taken for granted\".<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/>\n\nThe report by the International Carnegie Commission, often cited by the prosecution as an important witness and quoted multiple times, \"cannot\" says H\u00f6pken, \"be read without a due deconstructative effort on the part of the historian\".<ref name=\"Hopken41\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2018|p=41}}</ref> Historian Alan Kramer regards the Carnegie Commission report as a \"remarkably well-documented and impartial investigation, coolly sceptical of exaggerated claims, reached conclusions that have not been improved to this day.\"<ref name=\"Kramer138\"/> Diplomatic missions located in the Balkans repeatedly sent reports  on the rumors and news regarding violent actions committed by all participants in the Balkan Wars.<ref name=\"Hopken4142\"/> On multiple occasions they made complaints about being unable to get first-hand data.<ref name=\"Hopken4142\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2018|pp=41\u201342}}</ref> Reports from British consuls described many examples of violent actions perpetrated by Serb irregular forces in Kosovo and Macedonia following their capture during 1912-1913 by the Serbian military.<ref name=\"Hopken234\">{{cite book|last=H\u00f6pken|first=Wolfgang|chapter=Preforming Violence: Soldiers, Paramilitaries and Civilians in the Twentieth-Century Balkan Wars|editor1-last=L\u00fcdtke|editor1-first=Alf|editor2-last=Weisbrod|editor2-first=Bernd|title=No Man's Land of Violence: Extreme Wars in the 20th Century|year=2006|publisher=Wallstein Verlag|isbn=9783892448259|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wr-j5ibVgXsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=No+Man%27s+Land+of+Violence:+Extreme+Wars+in+the+20th+Century#v=onepage&q=balkan%20wars%20albanians%20killed&f=false|pages=234|ref=harv}}</ref> The British government was suspicious about the authenticity of the complaints and reports that made them hesitant to undertake any political action.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/>\n\nAt a time when political relations were tense with Serbia, Austro-Hungary took a keen interest to gather together details of Serbian atrocities and  subjected their sources to critical scrutiny and to determine whether informants were reliable.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> Austro-Hungarians described that often there was \"a great deal of exaggeration\" of certain data that came into their possession.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> They also stated that accounts from witnesses whose reliability was verified, confirmed that heavy use of violence occurred such as the killings of children and women, wide scale theft and the razing of villages and houses.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> For example, in Skopje, Macedonia, the Austro-Hungarian consul Heimroth sent his assistants multiple times out into the field to closely examine news of atrocities before sending reports such as Gausamkeiten der Serben gegen Albaner back to Vienna.<ref name=\"Hopken70\"/>\n\nAn extensive report by Catholic bishop [[Laz\u00ebr Mjeda]] regarding Serbian violence toward Skopje Muslim and Albanian inhabitants was the subject of detailed discussion in the Austro-Hungarian consulate.<ref name=\"Hopken70\"/> Afterward they came to the conclusion that it was well founded in the overall depiction of the situation it portrayed.<ref name=\"Hopken70\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2018|p=70}}</ref> In a long report on what he witnessed, Consul Heimroth stated that at a bare minimum, Serbian forces ought to be held to account for not halting the violence committed against Muslims after their arrival into Skopje.<ref name=\"Hopken43\"/> Heimroth described that in this war he heard more complaints regarding wartime violence then in the [[Russo-Japanese war]] and that the conflict whose aim was liberating fellow Christians concluded with an attempt to exterminate non-Orthodox inhabitants.<ref name=\"Hopken43\">{{cite book|last=H\u00f6pken|first=Wolfgang|chapter='Modern Wars' and 'Backward Societies': The Balkan Wars in the History of Twentieth-Century European Warfare|editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Wars of Yesterday: The Balkan Wars and the Emergence of Modern Military Conflict, 1912-13|year=2018|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=9781785337758|url=https://books.google.com/?id=okMtDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Wars+of+Yesterday:+The+Balkan+Wars+and+the+Emergence+of+Modern+Military+Conflict,+1912-13#v=snippet&q=heimroth&f=false|pages=43|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nAccounts given by nonpartisan witnesses from the Balkan Wars of what they saw included foreign workers and engineers from the Oriental Railway and the local and foreign Christian clergy.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> For some observers, they suspected that forced population movements (ethnic cleansing) were part of an organised effort of extermination.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> H\u00f6pken states there is insufficient support for that position in the sources, and instead, those events \"radicalised\" the continuing course toward homogenising populations along ethnic lines.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> Historian [[Mark Mazower]] states despite the \"careless talk of 'exterminating' the Albanian population\", the killing of \"perhaps thousands of civilians\" by Serbian armed forces in the provinces of Kosovo and Monastir was \"prompted more by revenge than genocide\".<ref name=\"Mazower\">{{cite book |last1= Mazower |first1= Mark |authorlink1= Mark Mazower |title= The Balkans, From the End of Byzantium to the Present Day |trans-title=  |chapter-url= http://www.orionbooks.co.uk/books/the-balkans-paperback |year= 2001 |origyear= 2000 |publisher= Phoenix Press |location= Great Britain |isbn= 978-1-84212-544-1 |chapter= Building the nation-state. |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/balkansuniversal00mark }}\"In the former Ottoman districts of Kosovo and Monastir, in particular, the conquering Serbian army killed perhaps thousands of civilians. Despite some Serbian officer's careless talk of \"exterminating\" the Albanian population, this was killing prompted more by revenge than genocide.\"</ref>\n\nEdwin E. Jacques quotes the French [[L'Ind\u00e9pendance Belge|L'Ind\u00e9pendance Albanaise]] stating in an article from Mars 15, 1915 that the atrocities were committed in cold blood.<ref name=\"McFarland\"/>\n\nThe information gathered from observations by individuals or \"reliable\" and \"non-partisan\" informants who witnessed the events \"left no doubt\", H\u00f6pken says, that extensive violence took place against people, like the razing of homes and villages and forced population movements.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> Separate to what H\u00f6pken calls \"suspicious slaughter narratives\" from second and third hand accounts, medical physicians and nurses verified from what they witnessed in hospitals that the \"conflict had gone beyond all rules and regulations\".<ref name=\"Hopken42\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2018|p=42}}</ref>\n\nIn literature and scholarship among Albanians, the actions and conduct described in Durham's accounts are the outcome of intentional anti-Albanian policies that the Serb government organised to \"exterminate Albanians\".<ref name=\"Dauti97\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=97}}</ref> Scholar Daut Dauti states that Durham's wartime reports \"amounted to atrocity testimonies committed against Albanians\".<ref name=\"Dauti99\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=99}}</ref> The accounts given by Durham came under criticism from individuals such as [[Rebecca West]], a fellow traveler of the region and author.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> West stated that Durham showed naivety and mocked her support of a report from 1912 that claimed falsely the Austrian consul was castrated by the Serbs at Prizren.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> Historian Benjamin Lieberman wrote that West also has been accused of showing a preference toward Serbs in her works.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> Lieberman said that Durham was an eyewitness to the conflict and in the interviews Trotsky conducted with Serbs, his informants lacked a motive to portray their fellow troops and citizens in a negative manner.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> In the accounts recorded by Trotsky, Durham and other people of the time, Lieberman states they are consistent and corroborated by additional sources such as from Catholic Church officials who referred to multiple massacres.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\">{{cite book|last=Lieberman|first=Benjamin|title=Terrible Fate: Ethnic Cleansing in the Making of Modern Europe|year=2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781442230385|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UXlfAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Terrible+Fate:+Ethnic+Cleansing+in+the+Making+of+Modern+Europe#v=onepage&q=balkan%20wars%20catholic%20reports%20durham&f=false|pages=60|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions to the killings==\nAccording to Misha Glenny, on the eve of war, Serbian press published banner headlines encouraging patriotic hysteria with messages such as \"Get ready for war! The joint Serbo-Bulgarian offensive will start any minute now!\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Glenny |first1=Misha |title=The Balkans, 1804\u20132012: Nationalism, War and the Great Powers |date=2012 |publisher=Granta Publications |isbn=978-1-84708-772-0 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=BVdheJDLWnkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Balkans+Glenny&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH48Xu_djoAhWhtIsKHWl0D-QQ6AEIMDAB#v=snippet&q=1912&f=false |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrench General [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric-Georges Herr]] reported on January 3, 1913, that \u201din the Albanian massif, the numerous massacres that bloodied this region reduced the population to strong proportions. Many villages were destroyed and the land remained barren\u201d.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Murzaku |first1=Thoma |title=Politika e Serbis\u00eb kundrejt Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb gjat\u00eb luft\u00ebs Ballkanike: 1912-1913 |date=1987 |publisher=Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb, Instituti i Historis\u00eb |page=140 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=YqC4AAAAIAAJ&q=masakrat+1912&dq=masakrat+1912&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcwM7nnsLoAhXQxIsKHXrNB1s4ChDoAQgnMAA&fbclid=IwAR0n0ebBWzEeiRkDVoLOIGos014U1csl356HsFZnYPECcLu55sjvC9opvXU |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=sq}}</ref>\n\nEdith Durham, along with European socialists Leo Freundlich, Leon Trotsky, and Serbian socialists like Kosta Novakovi\u0107, [[Dragi\u0161a Lap\u010devi\u0107]], Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107 and others shared the same stance of condemning the atrocities perpetrated on Albanians and all supported Albanian self determination.<ref name=\"Dauti90\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=90}}</ref>\n\nIn a letter written by [[Edith Durham|Durham]] in regards to [[Isa Boletini]] she writes how [[Dragutin Dimitrijevi\u0107|Dragutin Dimitrijevi\u0107 Apis]] and his friends betrayed the Albanians after they successfully revolted against the Ottomans: \"Having used their ammunition in the recent rebellions, the bulk of the Albanians were practically unarmed, and were pitilessly massacred by the invading armies. Apis and his friends who had posed as friends of the Albanians now spared neither man, woman nor child. How many were massacred in Kosovo vilayet will never be known\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Images |first1=Fm |title=Edith Durham: Note on Serb action with regard to ISA BOLETIN by M.E. Durham. US 55. |url=https://www.fmimages.net/edith-durham-ja-si-e-tradhetuan-serbet-isa-boletinin/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=FM Images |agency=FM Images Albania |issue=\"Having used their ammunition i nthe recent rebellions to bulk of the Albanians were practically unarmed, and were pitilessly massacred by the invading armies. Apis and his friends who had posed as friends of the Albanians now spared neither man, woman nor child. How many were massacred in Kosovo vilayet will never be known\". |date=22 December 2019 |language=sq}}</ref>\n\nIn order to investigate the crimes, the [[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]] formed a special commission, which was sent to the [[Balkans]] in 1913. Summing the situation in Albanian areas, the Commission concludes:\n\n{{quotation|Houses and whole villages reduced to ashes, unarmed and innocent populations massacred en masse, incredible acts of violence, pillage and brutality of every kind \u2013 such were the means which were employed and are still being employed by the Serbo-Montenegrin soldiery, with a view to the entire transformation of the ethnic character of regions inhabited exclusively by Albanians.<ref name=\"Report\"/><ref name=\"Pezo67\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|p=67}}</ref>|[[Report of the International Commission on the Balkan Wars]]}}\n\nSerbian territorial claims upon the region were complicated by the issue of war crimes perpetrated by Serbian military forces that were part of an investigation by the Carnegie Commission for the Balkan Wars.<ref name=\"Jovanovic41\"/> The report was received negatively by Serb historians and officials, even though the Serbian side was treated with restraint in comparison to others who had partaken in the conflict.<ref name=\"Jovanovic41\"/> The socialist press in Serbia referred to crimes, such as the prominent Serbian socialist Dimtrije Tucovi\u0107 who wrote about the Serbian campaign in Kosovo and northern Albania.<ref name=\"Jovanovic41\">{{harvnb|Jovanovi\u0107|2019|p=41.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Captain Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107.jpg|thumb|150px|Captain [[Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107]]]]\n{{quote|We have carried out the attempted [[premeditated murder]] of an entire nation. We were caught in that criminal act and have been obstructed. Now we have to suffer the punishment.... In the Balkan Wars, Serbia not only doubled its territory, but also its external enemies.<ref>{{cite book |first=T. |last=Gallagher |title=The Balkans in the New Millennium: In the Shadow of War and Peace |publisher=Routledge |year=2006 |isbn=0-415-34940-0}}</ref>|[[Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107]]}}\n\nTucovi\u0107 described the events as \"barbarian crematoria in which hundreds of women and children were burned\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Karadjis |first1=Michael |title=Kosova and the right of oppressed nations to self-determination |edition=\"Serbian Marxist Dimitrije Tucovic witnessed \"barbaric crematoria in which hundreds of women and children are burnt alive\" |url=https://www.academia.edu/2613683 |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Clark |first1=Howard |title=Civil Resistance in Kosovo |date=2000 |publisher=Pluto Press |isbn=978-0-7453-1569-0 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=OTW9XKUmrxsC&pg=PA9&dq=Dimitrije+Tucovic+women+and+children#v=onepage&q=Dimitrije%20Tucovic%20women%20and%20children&f=false |accessdate=15 December 2019 |language=en|page=9}}</ref> \nIn 1913, Tucovi\u0107 tried to remind his Serbian readers with [[Karl Marx|Marx's]] \"prophetic\" quote ''\"the nation that oppresses another nation forges its own chains\"'', however, this proved ineffective as the [[Serbian Orthodox Church in Kosovo|Serbian Orthodox Church]] had whipped up nationalist hatred towards Albanians.<ref>{{cite book |last1=MacShane |first1=Denis |title=Why Kosovo Matters |date=2012 |publisher=Haus Publishing |isbn=978-1-907822-51-3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=F1grDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT19&dq=Leon+Trotsky+Kosovo#v=onepage&q=Tucovic&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In his book ''Srbija i Arbanija'', Tucovi\u0107 writes:<ref>{{cite book |title=The South Slav Journal |date=1985 |publisher=Dositey Obradovich Circle. |page=29 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=axoWAQAAMAAJ&dq=Dimitrije+Tucovic+crematoria&q=barbarian+crematoria |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The bourgeois press called for merciless annihilation and the army acted upon this. Albanian villages, from which the men had fled in time, were reduced to ashes. At the same time, these were barbarian crematoria in which hundreds of women and children were burned. | Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107<ref name=\"Dedijer590\">{{cite book|last=Dedijer|first=Vladimir|title=Novi prilozi za biografiju Josipa Broza Tita, Vol. I|year=1981|publisher=Liburnija|url=https://books.google.com/?id=L7EfAQAAMAAJ&q=Tucovi%C4%87+krematorijumi&dq=Tucovi%C4%87+krematorijumi|pages=590|ref=harv}} \"Bur\u017eoaska \u0161tampa je tra\u017eila istrebljenje bez milosti, a vojska je izvr\u0161ivala. Arbanaska sela iz kojih su ljudi bili blagovremeno izbegli behu pretvorena u zgari\u0161ta. To behu u isto vreme varvarski krematorijumi u kojima je sagorelo stotinama \u017eivih \u017eena i deca\"</ref>}}\n\nIn the second half of the twentieth century, historian [[Vladimir Dedijer]] conducted research into Serbian foreign relations of the era.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> Dedijer stated that he was convinced by the information from Tucovi\u0107 and equated the actions of the Serbian military to European colonial armies engaged in Africa, South America and Africa.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> For example, Prime Minister [[Nikola Pa\u0161i\u0107]] at the time attempted to portray the whole narrative of crimes by the Serbian army to international powers as fabricated propaganda from foreign sources.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> The press in Britain and Germany kept printing articles about the large numbers of Albanian deaths in Albania and Kosovo, and the attempts by the Serbian government to conceal the reality from its people through censorship.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> In an issue from 18 January 1913, the most resolute charges of wrongdoing came from the London Times where it described that 25,000 Albanians were killed in northeastern Albania by Serbian forces.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/>\n\nRussia played a significant part in the territorial division of Albanian areas and the propaganda regarding crimes committed by Serbs.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> Russian Foreign Minister [[Sergey Sazonov]] warned Pa\u0161i\u0107 on multiple occasions through the Serbian representative in St.Petersburg about the need to disavow every single case, as in Gjakova, where Serbian forces were alleged to have shot 300 Albanian individuals.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> Sazonov repeatedly told Serbs that the Austrians were prepared to accept Gjakova as part of Serbia, so long as no alleged casualties occurred.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> At the same time, Russia assisted Serbia in gaining the towns of Debar, Prizren and Pec from Albania and undertook similar efforts to gain Gjakova for the Serbs, while Austria-Hungary attempted to retain the remaining territory for Albania.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/>\n\nThe Serbian social democrat paper ''Radnica novice'' wrote that Albanians were robbed and plundered and the villages devastated and that no one had felt the fury of liberators so strongly as the innocent Albanians.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Prifti |first1=Kristaq |title=The Truth on Kosova |date=1993 |publisher=Encyclopaedia Publishing House |page=140 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YBq5AAAAIAAJ&dq=atrocities+against+Albanians+1912&q=radnica |accessdate=24 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1913, the Russian paper [[Novoye Vremya (newspaper)|''Novoye vremya'']] refused to acknowledge the Serbian atrocities against Albanian civilians in Skopje and Prizren and instead began citing local Catholic priests who said that the Serb army had not committed a single act of violence against the civil population.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Boeckh |first1=Katrin |last2=Rutar |first2=Sabine |title=The Balkan Wars from Contemporary Perception to Historic Memory |date=2017 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-3-319-44642-4 |page=127 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aIXgDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA73&dq=atrocities+Albanians+1913#v=onepage&q=atrocities%20Albanians%201913&f=false |accessdate=28 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAn American relief agent named B. Peele Willett wrote in his report ''The Christian Work Fall'' from 1914 that:<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jacques |first1=Edwin E. |title=The Albanians: An Ethnic History from Prehistoric Times to the Present |date=1995 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-89950-932-7 |page=341 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=IJ2s9sQ9bGkC&pg=PA273&dq=1912+Shkodra+atrocities&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwior6O0ucXoAhXCrIsKHRTZABAQ6AEIQDAD#v=onepage&q=Shkodra&f=false |language=en}}</ref>\n{{quotation|...\"Serbian and Montenegrin troops destroyed one hundred villages in northern Albania without warning, without provocation, without excuse. ... 12,000 homes were burned and dynamited, 8,000 farm folk killed or burned to death, 125,000 made homeless. All livestock has been driven off. Corn fresh from the harvest has been carried away. Like hunted animals the farm folk fled to Elbasan, Tirana, Scutari and outlying villages. I have returned from a 400-mile journey, partly on foot, through these stricken regions. I saw the destroyed villages, the burned and dynamited houses. I saw the starving refugees. I saw women and children dying of hunger.\"<ref>Quoted from \"The Christian Work Fall\" from 1914. p.477</ref>}}\n\nThe Habsburg envoy in Belgrade at the time stated that the Serbian authorities were sponsoring and tolerating harsh treatments of Albanians specifically through pillaging, arson, and executions in the \"liberated lands\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=B\u00f6hler |first1=Jochen |last2=Borodziej |first2=Wlodzimierz |last3=Puttkamer |first3=Joachim von |title=Legacies of Violence: Eastern Europe's First World War |date=2014 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn=978-3-486-85756-6 |page=45 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jXnpBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA42&dq=Serbian+army+atrocities+1912#v=onepage&q=Albanian&f=false |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe German newspaper ''[[Frankfurter Zeitung]]'' wrote it had obtained reports whose plausibility was corroborated by observers from Europe with an impartial stance, that massacres were committed in Albania and the region of Macedonia by Bulgarians, Serbs and Greeks.<ref name=\"Kramer137\"/> The newspaper stated that the position of the Serbs was the Albanian population \"must be eradicated\".<ref name=\"Kramer137\">{{cite book|last=Kramer|first=Alan|title=Dynamic of destruction: Culture and Mass killing in the First World War|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780191580116|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6Gbgs1XFKTcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Dynamic+of+Destruction:+Culture+and+Mass+Killing+in+the+First+World+War#v=onepage&q=albanians&f=false|pages=137|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn 1921, ''The Near East'' published an article of the Albanian deputies who had spoken on 28 July on the Ambassadors Conference in Tirana stating that between 1913 and 1920, Serbian forces had killed approximately 85 676 Albanian civilians in Kosovo, with numerous villages being burned. They also stated that the [[Black Hand (Serbia)|The Black Hand]] had brought Russian colonists to settle in the areas where Albanians had been killed or expelled in Kosovo.<ref>{{cite book |author=Near East College Association (New York, N.Y.) |title=The Near East |date=1921 |publisher=s.n. |location=Tirana |page=199 |edition=Albanians at the Ambassador Conference in Tirana, 1 August. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=gD8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA763&dq=Serbian+tyranny#v=snippet&q=massacred&f=false |accessdate=31 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 1913, British official Mr. Dayrell Crackanthorpe sent a letter to Edward Grey from Belgrade mentioning an Albanian uprising against Serbian forces which the Austrians stated was due to the fact that Serbian army had not withdrawn their forces from Albania and that they had committed massacres on the civilian population.<ref>{{cite book |author=Great Britain Foreign Office |title=pt. 1. The Near and Middle East on the eve of war. pt. 2. The last years of Peace |date=1936 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Office |page=14 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=GxCamBG25ZsC&pg=PA15&dq=Servian+raids+on+Albanians+1913#v=onepage&q=Albanians&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A third reason was that the Serbian authorities had closed the borders thus cutting off important food markets necessary to the local population.\n\nA Romanian doctor named Leonte wrote in the Bucharest paper Adevarul on 6 January 1913, that the horrors inflicted by the Serbian Army in Kosovo were ''\"much more frightening than one could imagine\"''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schwartz |first1=Stephen |title=Kosovo: Background to a War |date=2000 |publisher=Anthem Press |isbn=978-1-898855-56-9 |page=59 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jL4tAQAAIAAJ&q=Adeverul+Serbian+Army+1913&dq=Adeverul+Serbian+Army+1913 |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHenrik August Angel, a [[Norwegian people|Norwegian]] military officer and writer who personally followed the trail of the [[Ottoman army]] and army of [[Kingdom of Serbia]], in his work<ref>{{Citation |last1=Henrik August|first1=Angel |title=Kada se jedan mali narod bori za \u017eivot: Srpske vojni\u010dke pri\u010de |publisher=Haka |year=1995|isbn=978-86-81635-01-8 }}</ref> described \"[[demonization]] of [[Serbs]]\" in texts published in English language newspapers, and especially in German language newspapers from [[Germany]] and [[Austria-Hungary]], as \"shameful injustice\".<ref>{{cite news| title       = Istorija \u2013 mit i zablude| first       = Dragan| last        = Vlahovi\u0107 | newspaper   = [[Politika]] | publisher   = Politika Newspapers and Magazines | location    = Belgrade | date        = 25 December 2010 | language    = Serbian |trans-title=History \u2013 myth and misconceptions | quote       = Igrom slu\u010daja.... prejahao popri\u0161te i sopstvenim nogama i\u0161ao tragom turske i srpske vojske...  Srbima naneta sramotna nepravda... sanjao dopisnik iz Budimpe\u0161te}}</ref><sup>{{Unreliable source?|date=March 2020}}</sup>\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn scholarship, reliable numbers exist for military casualties of the Balkan Wars.<ref name=\"Pezo67\"/> A research gap exists on civilian victims, often from a targeted ethnic or religious group, due to the statistics being interpreted and used for nationalist purposes.<ref name=\"Pezo67\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|p=67}}</ref> The Balkan Wars resulted in numerous people becoming refugees and some fled to [[Istanbul]] or [[Anatolia]].<ref name=\"Pezo70\"/> Following the creation of Albania, Albanian refugees, in particular of the Muslim religion sought shelter in the country.<ref name=\"Pezo70\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|p=70}}</ref> In late 1913, Serbian control was challenged by an insurgency in the [[Ohrid\u2013Debar uprising]] and its defeat by Serbian forces resulted in tens of thousands of Albanian refugees arriving in Albania from Western Macedonia.<ref name=\"Pezo667071\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|pp=66, 70\u201371}}</ref> At the time, news reports by Freundlich stated that in the town of Shkod\u00ebr, the Albanian refugee population numbered 8,000-10,000, 7,000 in the [[Shala (region)|Shala]] region and 7,000 in the [[Iball\u00eb]] area.<ref name=\"Pezo7071\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|pp=70\u201371}}</ref> As a large number of refugees were located in northern Albania, scholar Edvin Pezo says that part of the population likely arrived from the Kosovo area.<ref name=\"Pezo71\"/> A lack of assistance from the new Albanian government and Albanian immigration restrictions by the Ottomans, drove many refugees to return to their place of origin, often finding their houses were destroyed.<ref name=\"Pezo71\">{{cite book|last=Pezo|first=Edvin|chapter=Violence, Forced Migration, and Population Policies During and After the Balkan Wars (1912-14) |editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Balkan Wars from Contemporary Perception to Historic Memory|year=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319446424|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aIXgDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Balkan+Wars+from+Contemporary+Perception+to+Historic+Memory#v=onepage&q=Montenegrin%20army%20balkan%20wars%20albanians&f=false|pages=71|ref=harv}}</ref> People that lived through violent events of the Balkan Wars, such as those in Skopje, often did not talk about their experiences.<ref name=\"Trix44\"/>\n\nAs a result of the [[Treaty of London, 1913|Treaty of London]] in 1913 which designated the former Ottoman lands to Serbia, Montenegro and Greece (namely, the large part of the Vilayet of Kosovo being awarded to Serbia), an independent Albania was recognised. As such, Greece, Serbia and Montenegro agreed to withdraw from the territory of the new [[Principality of Albania]]. The principality however included only about half of the territory populated by ethnic Albanians and a large number of Albanians remained in neighboring countries.<ref name=\"Elsie\">[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_2.html Robert Elsie, The Conference of London 1913] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.albanianhistory.net%2Ftexts20_1%2FAH1913_2.html&date=2011-02-11 |date=11 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe previous two Serbian Army invasions into Albania, one in 1913 and the second in May 1915, made many Albanian locals take revenge through sniper attacks upon the [[Great Retreat (Serbian)|retreating Serb army during World War One]], in part as retribution for Serbian brutality in the First Balkan War.<ref name=\"Mojzes42198\">{{cite book|last=Mojzes|first=Paul|title=Balkan Genocides: Holocaust and Ethnic Cleansing in the Twentieth Century|year=2011|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-4422-0663-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=m5bDUFZXQ5sC&pg=PA198&dq=Serbian+army+retreat+albania+revenge#v=onepage&q=Serbian%20retreat%20albania%20revenge&f=false|pages=42, 198|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Majstorovic178\">{{cite book|last=Majstorovic|first=Steven|chapter=Autonomy of the Sacred: The Endgame in Kosovo|editor1-last=M\u00e1iz|editor1-first=Ram\u00f3n|editor2-last=William|editor2-first=Safran|title=Identity and Territorial Autonomy in Plural Societies|year=2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135303945|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=MvqiAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT184&dq=Serbian+army+retreat+albania+revenge&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwie253Utf7lAhWA73MBHRtUAVEQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q=Serbian%20army%20retreat%20albania%20revenge&f=false|pages=8178|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Ramet48\">{{cite book|last=Ramet|first=Sabrina P.|title=The Three Yugoslavias: State-building and Legitimation, 1918-2005|year=2006|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253346568|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FTw3lEqi2-oC&pg=PA48&dq=Serbian+army+retreat+albania+revenge#v=onepage&q=Serbian%20army%20retreat%20albania%20revenge&f=false|pages=48|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe Balkan wars resulted in Serbian forces viewing themselves as a \"liberator\", whereas non-Serbs became concerned about the future and their integration into the new reality.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> The current Serbian position of the Balkan Wars is that it was a \"final\" freedom struggle to liberate \"the cradle of Serbdom and occupied brothers.\"<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\">{{cite book|last=Jovanovi\u0107|first=Vladan|chapter=\"Reconquista of Old Serbia\": On the continuity of territorial and demographic policy in Kosovo|editor1-last=Pavlovi\u0107|editor1-first=Aleksandar|editor2-last=Dra\u0161ko|editor2-first=Gazela Pudar|editor3-last=Halili|editor3-first=Rigels|title=Rethinking Serbian-Albanian Relations: Figuring out the Enemy|year=2019|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351273145|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?hl=en&lr=&id=YCCeDwAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA39&dq=%22Reconquista+of+Old+Serbia%22:+On+the+continuity+of+territorial+and+demographic+policy+in+Kosovo&ots=8MENqkhlj4&sig=o0cIcr9ymyIzHKV8zcic8TKe-Gg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=balkan%20wars%2025%2C000%20Albanians&f=false|pages=42|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn Macedonian and Yugoslav books on history, accounts of violent events such as those that occurred in Skopje are not mentioned.<ref name=\"Trix44\">{{cite book|last=Trix|first=Frances|title=Urban Muslim migrants in Istanbul: Identity and trauma among Balkan immigrants|year=2016|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=9781786731081|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=KBOMDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=Albanians&f=false|pages=44|ref=harv}}</ref> The majority of history books in Albania and Kosovo present the notion of attacking the Ottoman state to liberate Greeks, Serbs and Albanians from government misrule as a positive move.<ref name=\"Dauti96\"/> They interpret the arrival and conduct by Serbian, Greek and Montenegrin military forces in Albania, as \"chauvinist\" and unwarranted.<ref name=\"Dauti96\"/> The \"liberation\" of the Albanian population by military forces, especially Serbian and Montenegrin armies belonging to the Balkan League is described as the \"invasion of enemies\", or that of longstanding \"foes\".<ref name=\"Dauti96\"/> In Albania and Kosovo, this particular understanding of the Balkan Wars prevails within school textbooks and the education curriculum.<ref name=\"Dauti96\">{{cite book|last=Dauti|first=Daut|chapter=Gjergj Fishta, the \"Albanian Homer,\" and Edith Durham, the \"Albanian Mountain Queen\": Observers of Albania's Road to Statehood|editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Balkan Wars from Contemporary Perception to Historic Memory|year=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319446424|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aIXgDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Balkan+Wars+from+Contemporary+Perception+to+Historic+Memory#v=onepage&q=Montenegrin%20army%20balkan%20wars%20albanians&f=false|pages=96|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n[[War crimes in Kosovo|In 1998-9]]9, similar war crimes to those committed in 1912 against the Albanian population would occur.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Booth |first1=Ken |title=The Kosovo Tragedy: The Human Rights Dimensions |date=2012 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-136-33476-4 |page=106 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=e4MsBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA73&dq=#v=onepage&q=1912&f=false |accessdate=8 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThese events have greatly contributed to the growth of the Serbian-Albanian conflict.<ref>[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1914_1.html Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107: Serbien und Albanien: ein kritischer Beitrag zur Unterdr\u00fcckungspolitik der serbischen Bourgeoisie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617232534/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1914_1.html |date=17 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Albania's Golgotha]]''\n* [[Albania during the Balkan Wars]]\n* [[Albanophobia]]\n* [[Attacks on Serbs during the Serbian\u2013Ottoman War (1876\u201378)]]\n* [[Expulsion of the Albanians 1877\u20131878]]\n* [[1901 massacres of Serbs]]\n* [[War crimes in the Kosovo War|War crimes in the Kosovo War (1999)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.org/details/reportofinternat00inteuoft Report of the International Commission to Inquire into the Causes and Conduct of the Balkan War]\n*{{cite book|last1=Tucovi\u0107|first1=Dimitrije|title=Srbija i Arbanija. Jedan prilog kritici zavojeva\u010dke politike srpske bur\u017eoazije|date=1946 |publisher=Kultura|location=Beograd \u2013 Zagreb|url=https://vdocuments.mx/dimitrije-tucovic-srbija-i-albanija.html}}\n\n[[Category:1912 in Albania]]\n[[Category:1913 in Albania]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Serbia|Albanians in the Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Albania|Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:20th century in Albania]]\n[[Category:20th century in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Serbian war crimes in the Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Anti-Albanian sentiment]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Kosovo|Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Massacres in the Ottoman Empire|Albanians in the Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1912]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1913]]\n[[Category:1912 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:1913 murders in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Massacres of Albanians in the Balkan Wars\n| location    = [[Albania]], [[Kosovo Vilayet]]\n| target      = [[Albanians|Albanian]] population in the territories occupied by Serbia, especially in the regions of today's [[Kosovo]], Western [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] and Northern [[Albania]]\n| date        = 1912\u20131913\n| type        = [[Deportation]], [[mass murder]], [[death march]], others\n| fatalities = 20,000\u201325,000 \n| perps       = [[Kingdom of Serbia]], [[Kingdom of Montenegro]]\n}}\n\n[[File:NY Times Massacre of Albanians 1912.jpg|thumb|''[[The New York Times]]'', 31 December 1912]]\nA series of '''massacres of Albanians in the Balkan Wars''' were committed by the [[Montenegrin Army]], [[Serbian Army]]  and [[Chetniks|paramilitaries]], according to international reports.<ref>{{cite book |author=United States Department of State |title=Papers Relating to the Foreign Relations of the United States |date=1943 |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |page=115 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ADhGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA115&dq=Serbian+troops+atrocities+1913#v=onepage&q=Serbian%20troops%20atrocities%201913&f=false |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Report\"/> During the [[First Balkan War]] of 1912-13, [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbia]] and [[Kingdom of Montenegro|Montenegro]] during the war with the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] forces (many Albanians were among the Ottoman forces) and after expelling the official Ottoman Empire's forces in present-day [[Albania]] and [[Kosovo]] - committed numerous [[war crime]]s against the Albanian population, which were reported by the European, American and Serbian opposition press.<ref name=\"Golgotha\">[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_1.html Leo Freundlich: Albania's Golgotha] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531131757/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_1.html |date=31 May 2012 }}</ref> Most of the crimes happened between October 1912 and summer of 1913. The goal of the forced expulsions and massacres of ethnic Albanians was a statistic manipulation before the London Ambassadors Conference which was to decide on the new Balkan borders.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danas.rs/dodaci/vikend/otpor_okupaciji_i_modernizaciji.26.html?news_id=105029|title=Otpor okupaciji i modernizaciji|publisher=|accessdate=6 September 2016|date=9 March 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Hudson128\"/> According to contemporary accounts, between 20,000 and 25,000 Albanians were killed or died because of hunger and cold during that period.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/><ref name=\"Hudson128\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W4zndspbem4C|title=Justice, Intervention, and Force in International Relations: Reassessing Just War Theory in the 21st Century|first=Kimberly A.|last=Hudson|date=5 March 2009|publisher=Taylor & Francis|pages=128|accessdate=6 September 2016|via=Google Books|isbn=9780203879351}}</ref><ref name=\"Archbishop\">[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_6.html Archbishop Laz\u00ebr Mjeda: Report on the Serb Invasion of Kosova and Macedonia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303195950/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_6.html |date=3 March 2016 }}</ref> Many of the victims were children, women and old people and were part of an warfare of extermination.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bessel |first1=Richard |title=No Man's Land of Violence: Extreme Wars in the 20th Century |date=2006 |publisher=Wallstein Verlag |isbn=978-3-89244-825-9 |page=226 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wr-j5ibVgXsC&pg=PA229&dq=atrocities+against+Albanians+1912#v=onepage&q=atrocities%20against%20Albanians%201912&f=false |accessdate=24 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Aside from massacres, civilians had their lips and noses severed.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Tatum |first1=Dale C. |title=Genocide at the Dawn of the Twenty-First Century: Rwanda, Bosnia, Kosovo, and Darfur |date=2010 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-0-230-62189-3 |page=113 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=nWsbAQAAMAAJ&dq=Albanian+civilians+1912&q=massacred |accessdate=3 January 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Philip J. Cohen]], the [[Serbian Army]] generated such fear that some Albanian women killed their own children rather than let them fall into the hands of the Serbian soldiery.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cohen |first1=Philip J. |title=The Ideology and Historical Continuity of Serbia's Anti-Islamic Policy |journal=Islamic Studies |date=1997 |volume=36 |issue=2/3 |pages=361\u2013382 |publisher=Islamic Research Institute, International Islamic University |location=Islamabad |language=en |quote=Among the worst and most consistent offenders were the Serbs, who generated such fear that some women killed their own children, rather than let them fall into Serbian hands|jstor=23076201 }}</ref> In relation to Serbia and Montenegro, the Carnegie Commission, an international fact finding mission concluded that both its armies perpetrated large-scale violence that aimed at \"the entire transformation of the ethnic character of regions inhabited exclusively by Albanians\".<ref name=\"Kramer138\"/> Cohen also examined the report from the [[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]] stating that Serbian soldiers also tortured and mutilated the Albanian civil population by cutting off ears, noses, tounges and by couging out eyes.<ref>PHILIP J. COHEN, slamic Studies\nVol. 36, No. 2/3, Special Issue: ISLAM IN THE BALKANS , 1997, p. 4 out of 22</ref> \n\nAccording to the Committee of Kosovo, during this period, around 23 000 Albanians were killed or died in Serbian, Montenegrin and Greek prisons. According to an Albanian imam organization, there were around 21 000 simple graves in Kosovo where Albanians had been massacred by the Serb gender armies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Horvat, Dr. Jusuf Osmani |first1=Mislav |title=Jusuf Osmani - Kolonizimi Serbi Kosoves (The Serbian colonisation of Kosovo) |date=2010 |publisher=REND Prishtin\u00eb |location=Pristina |page=66 |edition= |url=https://www.academia.edu/27205754/Jusuf_Osmani_-_Kolonizimi_Serbi_Kosoves.pdf |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On August-September 1913, Serbian forces destroyed 140 villages and forced 40 000 Albanians to flee.<ref>{{cite book |last1=N.Y.) |first1=Near East College Association (New York |title=The Near East |date=1921 |publisher=s.n. |page=45 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=gD8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA767&dq=The+suppressed+Albanian+lord+were+hostile+to+new+authority&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjniOLgjNHoAhVql4sKHSOaB8IQ6AEINzAC#v=onepage&q=Albanian&f=false |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>  \n\nAccording to newsman William Howard in an interview titled \"Let Albanians Starve: They are Mohammmedans\", at the New York Globe, 1914, the Serbian army carried out [[Modus operandi|modus operandi]]: \"''Serb regiments of 1100, led by General Carlos Popovitch, entered Albania with kerosene oil, force pumps and dynamite bombs. They captured such Albanian men as they could. Then they tied them together by the elbows and shot them down. The women were outraged. I believe that every woman who fell into the hands of the Serb troops fell a victim to them. Then they were locked up in the house and bombs planted in the walls. Kerosene oil would be sprayed over all and a fire started. When the flames reached the dynamite, the walls were shattered. Albania is filled with fire blackened heaps of stones that were once houses''\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jacques |first1=Edwin E. |title=The Albanians: An Ethnic History from Prehistoric Times to the Present |date=1995 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-89950-932-7 |page=352 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=IJ2s9sQ9bGkC&pg=PA273&dq=1912+Shkodra+atrocities&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwior6O0ucXoAhXCrIsKHRTZABAQ6AEIQDAD#v=onepage&q=atrocities&f=false |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAmerican relief commissioner Mr Willar Howard stated in an interview with The Daily Mirror in 1914 that Popovitch would yell \"''Dont run away, we are brothers and friends. We dont mean to do any harm.''\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Archives |first1=British News Paper |title=\"Albanian Peasants Burned by Servians: New Rulers Task\" |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/BL/0000560/19140202/063/0009?browse=true |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk |agency=Daily Mirror |issue=p.9 \"A scene in a refugee camp. In the background are a woman and a boy who are slowly dying of hunger fever\". \"Mohammedan refugees at Scutari, who are among the sufferers.\" \"Where two women were burnt to death by Servians\". \"Wretched shelter in which a family are housed\". |publisher=The Daily Mirror |date=February 2, 1914}}</ref> Peasants who trusted the words were shot or burned to death, and elderly women unable to leave their homes were burned as well. Howard states that the atrocities were committed after the war had ended.\n\nAccording to the study ''Yugoslavia from a Historical Perspective'', published in Belgrade 2017 by the ''Helsinki Committee for Human Rights in Serbia'', when Serbo-Montenegrin forces invaded Kosovo in 1912, havoc was created where villages were burned to ashes, and Albanian Muslims were targeted and many were forced to flee. Some chronicles evidence the atrocities including [[Decapitation|decapitation]] and [[Mutilation|mutilation]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Biserko, Latinka Perovi\u0107, Drago Roksandi\u0107, Mitja Velikonja, Wolfgang Hoepken, Florian Bieber, Sheila Sofrenovi\u0107, Ivan Hra\u0161ovec |first1=Sonja |title=Yugoslavia from a Historical Perspective |date=2017 |publisher=Helsinki Committee for Human Rights in Serbia |location=Belgrade |isbn=978-86-7208-208-1 |pages=272-73 |edition=\"In the falls of 1912 and 1913, Kosovo and Albania were invaded by Serbia and Montenegro. The Balkan Wars had wreaked havoc on Kosovar Albanians whose villages were burned to ashes and whose residents that had managed to escape death were forced to flee their homes. Under such brutal wartime conditions, the Montenegrin and Serbian authorities targeted the Muslim population of Kosovo, the majority of which was Albanian. Some chronicles evidence the atrocities committed by the Montenegrins, including  against colonial status 273 decapitation and mutilation. The Balkan wars had cost the Kosovar Albanians thousands of dead and more destroyed houses. It is estimated that around 20\u201325.000 Albanians were killed up to the end of 1912 and about 20,000 emigrated from Kosovo\" |url=http://www.yuhistorija.com/doc/yugoslavia%20from%20a%20historical%20perspective.pdf |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Background==\nThe modern Albanian-Serbian conflict has its roots in the [[Expulsion of the Albanians 1877\u20131878|expulsion of the Albanians in 1877-1878 from areas that became incorporated into the]] [[Principality of Serbia]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Frantz|first=Eva Anne|title=Violence and its Impact on Loyalty and Identity Formation in Late Ottoman Kosovo: Muslims and Christians in a Period of Reform and Transformation|journal=Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs|volume=29|issue=4|year=2009|pages=460\u2013461|ref=harv|doi=10.1080/13602000903411366}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=M\u00fcller|first=Dietmar|title=Orientalism and Nation: Jews and Muslims as Alterity in Southeastern Europe in the Age of Nation-States, 1878\u20131941|journal=East Central Europe|volume=36|issue=1|year=2009|page=70|ref=harv|doi=10.1163/187633009x411485}}</ref> Prior to the outbreak of the First Balkan War, the [[Albanians|Albanian]] nation was fighting for a [[national state]]. In mid 1912, an [[Albanian revolt of 1912|Albanian revolt]] resulted in Ottoman recognition of the \"[[Hasan Prishtina#Albanian National Movement|14 points]]\", a list of demands that included the establishment of an autonomous [[Albanian vilayet]].<ref name=\"Dauti94\"/> The push for Albanian autonomy and Ottoman weakness were viewed at the time as directly threatening the Christian population of the region with extermination by regional Christian Balkan powers.<ref>''Report of the International Commission on the Balkan Wars''. p. 47.</ref> Albanian scholarship states the realisation of Albanian aspirations were received negatively by Bulgaria, Serbia, Montenegro and Greece.<ref name=\"Dauti94\"/> The [[Balkan League]] (comprising [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]], Greece and [[Bulgaria]]) jointly attacked the [[Ottoman Empire]] and during the next few months partitioned all Ottoman territory inhabited by Albanians.<ref name=\"Report\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/reportofinternat00inteuoft|title=Report of the International Commission to Inquire into the Causes and Conduct of the Balkan War|last1=International Commission to Inquire into the Causes and Conduct of the Balkan Wars|last2=Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. Division of Intercourse and Education|date=1 January 1914|publisher=Washington, D.C. : The Endowment|accessdate=6 September 2016|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> The [[Kingdom of Serbia]] and the [[Kingdom of Greece]] occupied most of the land of what is today Albania and other lands inhabited by Albanians on the [[Adriatic coast]]. Montenegro occupied a part of today's northern Albania around [[Shkod\u00ebr]]. The Serbian army in the region viewed its role as protecting local Orthodox Christian communities and avenging the medieval battle of Kosovo,<ref name=\"Batakovic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doiserbia.nb.rs/img/doi/0350-7653/2014/0350-76531445317B.pdf|title=Serbia, the Serbo-Albanian Conflict and the First Balkan War}} pp. 338-340; 343.</ref> though it forced Catholic Albanians to convert to Orthodox Christianity.<ref name=\"Mirdita\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hic.hr/books/jugoistocna-europa/mirdita.htm|title=Medjunarodni znanstveni skup \"Jugoistocna Europa 1918.-1995.\" Albanci u svjetlosti vanjske politike Srbije|last=Nadj|first=Danijela|website=|accessdate=6 September 2016}}</ref> Serbia also doubled its territory, according to Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107. A majority of Albanian historians state that Montenegro, Greece and Serbia did not recognise Albanian autonomy and the cause for the Balkan Wars was to stop its establishment on Ottoman lands they claimed.<ref name=\"Dauti94\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=94}}</ref>.\n\nWhen the Serbo-Montenegrin forces invaded the Vilayet of Kosovo in 1912, much of the Albanian population was forced to flee due to the feared and actual violence that they experienced at the hands of the invading armies.<ref>{{cite book |title=Casebook on Insurgency and Revolutionary Warfare |date=2012 |publisher=United States Army Special Operations Command |page=270 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=SPZdWxjMd6cC&pg=PA270&dq=en+masse+#v=onepage&q=en%20masse&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> During the Serb military effort to conquer Kosovo, the armed conflict had overtones of extermination, due to Serb retaliation directed toward Albanians that affected children and women, involved the killing of women and men and homes razed.<ref name=\"Hopken226\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2006|p=226}}</ref> In this period, 235 villages were burned down in total, with 133 being burned by Serb forces and 102 by Montenegrin.<ref>ibid. p. 28</ref> Steven Schwarts states that during the capture of Durr\u00ebs, Shkod\u00ebr and Shengjin, Serbian soldiers massacred, pillaged and targeted poor Albanians.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schwartz |first1=Stephen |title=Kosovo: Background to a War |date=2000 |publisher=Anthem Press |isbn=978-1-898855-56-9 |page=55 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=jL4tAQAAIAAJ&dq=1912+Shkodra+atrocities&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=capture |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Albanian publicist Armend Bekaj states that the Serbian invasion of Kosovo was illegal.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bekaj |first1=Armend |title=The KLA and the Kosovo war |publisher=Berghof Transitions Series. Resistance/Liberation Movements and Transitions to Polticis. |location=Berlin |isbn=9783941514027 |page=9 |url=https://www.berghof-foundation.org/fileadmin/redaktion/Publications/Papers/Transitions_Series/transitions8_kosovo.pdf |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Massacres==\n===Vilayet of Scutari===\n====Mal\u00ebsia====\nDuring the Balkan Wars, multiple reports surfaced regarding violent persecutions by Montenegro of Catholic Albanians.<ref name=\"Treadway162\"/> In districts under Montenegrin military control, Catholic and Muslim Albanians were subjected to forced mass conversions to Orthodox Christianity, through a policy that aimed to dismantle identities based on a particular religion, and to sever other sociocultural links.<ref name=\"Pezo6566\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|pp=66-65}}</ref>\n\n====Shkod\u00ebr====\nWhen Serbo-Montenegrin soldiers invaded Shkod\u00ebr, around 10 000 Montenegrin lives were lost. In the city, they looted and massacred civilians, including the sick and wounded, women and children, many of whom were Christian.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Udovicki |first1=Jasminka |last2=Ridgeway |first2=James |title=Burn This House: The Making and Unmaking of Yugoslavia |date=2000 |publisher=Duke University Press |isbn=978-0-8223-8091-7 |page=30 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=DHMioF8-CewC&pg=PA42&dq=Leon+Trotsky+Kosovo#v=onepage&q=Leon%20Trotsky%20Kosovo&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In late 1913, international pressure resulted in the Serbian withdrawal of its forces from Shkod\u00ebr and the Austro-Hungarian consul general within the town reported that during the process, Serb troops killed some 600 Albanians.<ref name=\"Treadway162\">{{cite book|last=Treadway|first=John D.|title=The Falcon and the Eagle: Montenegro and Austria-Hungary, 1908-1914|year=1998|publisher=Purdue University Press|isbn=9781557531469|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JVJUk2cHkDcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Montenegrin+army+balkan+wars+albanians#v=onepage&q=albanians&f=false|pages=162|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n====Morin\u00eb====\nIn 1912, Serbian forces entered [[Qaf\u00eb Morin\u00eb]] where they massacred 15 civilians.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Qeriqi |first1=Ahmet |title=Dr. Sk\u00ebnder Demaliaj: N\u00eb 100 vjetorin e p\u00ebrfundimit t\u00eb Luft\u00ebs s\u00eb Par\u00eb Bot\u00ebrore - Radio Kosova e Lir\u00eb |url=https://www.radiokosovaelire.com/dr-skender-demaliaj-ne-100-vjetorin-e-perfundimit-te-luftes-se-pare-boterore/' |date=9 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Vilayet of Kosovo ===\n\nThe Belgrade consulate of Austria-Hungary reported that during February 1913, Serbian military forces executed all Albanian inhabitants from the villages of Kabash, T\u00ebrpez\u00eb, Lubisht and Gjylekar.<ref name=\"Michailidis331\">{{harvnb|Michailidis|2018|p=331.}}</ref>\n\n[[Chetniks]], a Serb irregular force razed the Albanian quarter of [[Skopje]] and killed a number of Albanian inhabitants from the city.<ref name=\"Michailidis330\">{{cite book|last=Michailidis|first=Iakovos D.|chapter=Cleansing the Nation: War related Demographic Changes in Macedonia|editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Wars of Yesterday: The Balkan Wars and the Emergence of Modern Military Conflict, 1912-13|year=2018|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=9781785337758|url=https://books.google.com/?id=okMtDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Wars+of+Yesterday:+The+Balkan+Wars+and+the+Emergence+of+Modern+Military+Conflict,+1912-13#v=snippet&q=burned&f=false|pages=330|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n====Prishtina====\nWhen villagers heard about the Serbian massacres of Albanians in the nearby villages, some houses took the desperate measure of raising white flag to protect themselves. In the cases the white flag was ignored during the attack of Serbian army on Prishtina in October 1912, the Albanians (led by Ottoman and Ottoman Albanian officers)  abused the [[white flag]], and attacked and killed all the Serbian soldiers.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> The Serbian army subsequently used this as an excuse for the brutal retaliation against civilians.\n\nThe Serbian army entered Pristina on October 22.<ref name=\"Trix\">{{cite book |last1=Trix |first1=Francis |title=Urban Muslim Migrants in Istanbul: Identity and Trauma Among Balkan Immigrants |date=2008 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=1786731088 |page=44 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBOMDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA44 |ref=Trix}}</ref> The events that followed, resulted in the destruction of Albanian and Turkish households, the massacre of children and women, widespread looting and violation of human rights.<ref name=\"Karoubi174\"/> Based in Skopje, a Danish journalist reported that the campaign of the Serbian army in Prishtina \"had taken on the character of a horrific massacring of the Albanian population\".<ref name=\"Trix\"/><ref name=\"Karoubi174\"/> The number of Albanians of Pristina killed in the early days after the Serbian army took over the town is estimated at 5,000.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/><ref name=\"Karoubi174\"/><ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/12/31/100385991.pdf|title=SERVIAN ARMY LEFT A TRAIL OF BLOOD; Thousands of Men, Women, and Children Massacred in March to Sea, Say Hungarian Reports.|accessdate=6 September 2016}}</ref> The events have been interpreted as an early policy that aimed to change the demographic status of the area.<ref name=\"Trix\"/>\n\nAfterwards, Serbian settlers were brought in the city and [[Nikola pasic|Nikola Pasic]], at the time the [[Prime Minister of Serbia]], bought 1,214 acres of land.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Banac |first1=Ivo |title=The National Question in Yugoslavia: Origins, History, Politics |date=1988 |publisher=Cornell University Press |isbn=978-0-8014-9493-2 |page=296 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KfqbujXqQBkC&pg=PA295&dq=slaughter+of+Albanians+1912#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the town, people who wore a [[Qeleshe|plis]] were targetted by the Serbian army and those who wore the Turkish [[Fez|fez]] remained safe. This caused the price of the fez in the town's market to skyrocket. On October 18, 1912, 82 Turkish [[Fez|fez]] could be bought for one Turkish lira. On November 10, 1912, at the same market, a fez could be bought for 82 lira.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Horvat, Dr. Jusuf Osmani |first1=Mislav |title=Jusuf Osmani - Kolonizimi Serbi Kosoves (The Serbian colonisation of Kosovo) |date=2010 |publisher=REND Prishtin\u00eb |location=Pristina |page=67 |edition=Se n\u00eb tregun e Prishtin\u00ebs, m\u00eb 18 tetor 1912 m\u00eb nj\u00eb lir\u00eb ari t\u00eb Turqis\u00eb mund t\u00eb bliheshin 82 fesa turq. M\u00eb 10 n\u00ebntor 1912, po n\u00eb k\u00ebt\u00eb treg, nj\u00eb fes mund t\u00eb blihej me 82 lira ari. Ngritja kaq e lart\u00eb e \u00e7mimit ishte b\u00ebr\u00eb p\u00ebr shkak se ushtria serbe likuidonte t\u00eb gjith\u00eb njer\u00ebzit me plisa t\u00eb bardh\u00eb, nd\u00ebrsa i kursente ata q\u00eb mbanin fesin turk n\u00eb krye. (Translation: On the 18th of October 1912, at the market of Pristina, 82 Turkish fez could be bought with a cheaper Turkish gold. On November 10, 1912, at the same market, a slice could be bought for 82 gold. The price hike was so high that the Serbian army liquidated all plis wearing people while saving those who held the Turkish fez at the top. |url=https://www.academia.edu/27205754/Jusuf_Osmani_-_Kolonizimi_Serbi_Kosoves.pdf |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Gazimestan====\nIn 1913, when Serb forces entered [[Gazimestan]], they massacred 5000 Albanians.<ref>Dr. Hakif Bajrami, \"Politika e shfarosjes s\u00eb shqiptar\u00ebve dhe kolonizimi serb I Kosov\u00ebs\" (1844-1945), Prishtin\u00eb, 1995, p. 17.</ref> \n\n====Gjakova====\n[[Gjakova]] was mentioned among the cities that suffered at the hands of the Serbian-Montenegrin army. ''The New York Times'' reported that people on the [[gallows]] hanged on both sides of the road, and that the way to Yakova became a \"gallows alley.\"<ref name=\"NY Times\"/> In the region of Yakova, the Montenegrin police-military formation ''Kraljevski \u017eandarmerijski kor'', known as krila\u0161i, committed many abuses and violence against the Albanian population.<ref>''Krila\u0161i'', Istorijski leksikon Crne Gore, Daily Press, Podgorica, 2006.</ref>\n\nIn Gjakova, Serbian priests carried out a violent conversion of Albanian [[Catholics]] to [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Serbian Orthodoxy]].<ref name=\"Mirdita\"/> Vienna ''[[Neue Freie Presse]]'' (20 March 1913) reported that Orthodox priests with the help of military force converted 300 Gjakova Catholics to the Orthodox faith, and that [[Franciscan Order|Franciscan]] Pater Angelus, who refused to renounce his faith, was tortured and then killed with [[bayonet]]s. The History Institute in Pristina has claimed that Montenegro converted over 1,700 Albanian Catholics to the Serbian Orthodox faith in the area of Gjakova in March 1913.<ref name=\"Institute II\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kosova.com/arkivi1997/expuls/chap2.htm|title=chapter 2|first=Edmond|last=Hajrullaaga|accessdate=6 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031192729/http://www.kosova.com/arkivi1997/expuls/chap2.htm|archivedate=31 October 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[Count Albert von Mensdorff-Pouilly-Dietrichstein]] also told [[Edward Grey, 1st Viscount Grey of Fallodon|Edward Grey]] in an interview on 10 March 1912, that the Serbian soldiers committed numerous atrocities on both Muslim an Catholic Albanians in Gjakova, acting in a \"barbarous way\".<ref>{{cite book |author=Great Britain Foreign Office |title=The Balkan wars. pt. 1. The prelude; the Tripoli war. pt. 2. The league and Turkey |date=1934 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Office |page=569 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=2TguIIjeeb0C&pg=PA1122&dq=Servian+atrocities#v=onepage&q=Servian%20atrocities&f=false |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Prizren====\nAfter the Serbian army achieved control over the city of [[Prizren]], it imposed repressive measures against the Albanian civilian population. Serbian detachments broke into houses, plundered, committed acts of violence, and killed indiscriminately.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> Around 400 people were \"eradicated\" in the first days of the Serbian military administration.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> During those days bodies were lying everywhere on the streets. According to witnesses, during those days around Prizren lay about 1,500 corpses of Albanians.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> Foreign reporters were not allowed to go to Prizren.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> After the operations of the Serbian military and paramilitary units, Prizren became one of the most devastated cities of the [[Kosovo vilayet]] and people called it \"the Kingdom of Death\".<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> Eventually, General [[Bo\u017eidar Jankovi\u0107]] forced surviving Albanian leaders of Prizren to sign a statement of gratitude to the Serbian king [[Peter I Kara\u0111or\u0111evi\u0107]] for their [[liberty|liberation]].<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> It is estimated that 5,000 Albanians was massacred in the area of Prizren.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> [[British people|British]] traveller [[Edith Durham]] and a [[British Armed Forces|British military attach\u00e9]] were supposed to visit Prizren in October 1912, however the trip was prevented by the authorities. Durham stated \"I asked wounded Montengrins [Soldiers] why I was not allowed to go and they laughed and said 'We have not left a [[Human nose|nose]] on an Albanian up there!' Not a pretty sight for a British officer.\"<ref name=\"Karoubi174\">{{cite book|last=Karoubi|first=Mohammad Taghi|title=Just or Unjust War?: International Law and Unilateral Use of Armed Force by States at the Turn of the 20th Century|year=2017|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351154666|url=https://books.google.com/?id=v_dADwAAQBAJ&pg=PT268&dq=archbishop+skopje+massacres#v=onepage&q=archbishop%20skopje%20massacres&f=false|pages=174|ref=harv}}</ref> Eventually Durham visited a northern Albanian outpost in Kosovo where she met captured Ottoman soldiers whose [[upper lip]]s and noses had been cut off.<ref name=\"malcolm p253\">{{cite book|last1=[[Noel Malcolm]]|title=Kosovo: A Short History|date=1998|publisher=papermac|location=London|isbn=9780330412247|page=253}}</ref>\n\nThe town of Prizren offered no resistance to Serb forces, but this did not avert a bloodbath there. After Prishtina, Prizren was the hardest hit of the Albanian towns. The local population called it the \"Kingdom of Death\". Serb forces forced their way into homes and beat up anyone and everyone in their way, irrespective of age or sex. Corpses lined the streets for days while the Serbian victors continued with brutality, and the native population which had survived did not dare to venture out of their homes. The attacks continued night after night throughout the town and region. Up to 400 people perished in the first few days of the Serbian occupation. When the Serbian troops were about to set off westwards, they could not find any horses to transport their equipment so they used 200 Albanians and forced them to carry the goods. Most of them collapsed during the journey and the Serbian commander expressed his satisfaction and approval of the action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_1.html |title=1913 {{!}} Leo Freundlich: Albania's Golgotha: Indictment of the Exterminators of the Albanian People |accessdate=17 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531131757/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_1.html |archivedate=31 May 2012 |publisher=albanianhistory.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IHgtAQAAIAAJ|title=Albania's Golgotha: indictments of the exterminators of the Albanian people|first=Leo|last=Freundlich|date=1 January 1998|publisher=Juka Pub. Co.|accessdate=6 September 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n====Rugova====\nIn 1913, General [[Janko Vukoti\u0107|Janko Vukotic]] told British traveler [[Edith Durham]] that his soldiers had committed atrocities against the civilian population of Rugova; in response to her protests, he reportedly said \"but they are beasts, savage animals. We have done very well\",<ref name=jezernik>{{cite book |last1=Jezernik |first1=Bo\u017eidar |title=Wild Europe: The Balkans in the Gaze of Western Travellers |date=2004 |publisher=Saqi |isbn=978-0-86356-574-8 |page=109 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ji5pAAAAMAAJ&dq=Janko+Vukotic+Rugova&q=Rugova |accessdate=21 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> which Slovene author Bo\u017eidar Jezernik interprets as an attestation of the Montenegrin goal of removing local Muslims from their newly captured territories, and resettling the lands.<ref name=jezernik/>\n\n====Ferizaj====\nThe capture of ''Ferizovik'' as the town was known in Ottoman times by the Serbian army and the events that followed were documented in contemporary accounts. The entry of the Serbian army was followed by a massacre of the population.<ref name=\"Trix\"/> Leo Freundlich recorded on his [[Albania's Golgotha]] the existing reports about the situation in Ferizaj at the time. The Italian war correspondent of ''[[Il Messaggero]]'' of Rome reported that the town was destroyed and most of its inhabitants were killed.<ref name=\"Freundlich\">{{cite book |last1=Freundlich |first1=Leo |editor1-last=Elsie |editor1-first=Robert |editor2-last=Destani |editor2-first=Bejtullah |title=Kosovo, A Documentary History: From the Balkan Wars to World War II |url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/1913_Freundlich_Golgotha/index.html |accessdate=29 March 2020 |ref=Freundlich}}</ref> A Catholic priest in the region reported that resistance had been strong for three days against the advancing Serbian army. When the town was finally taken, the locals who were fleeing the town were invited back in the town on the condition that they surrendered their arms. After the surrender of arms, the army went on to kill about 300 to 400 people. Only a few Muslim families remained in the town after this event.<ref name=\"Freundlich\"/> Freundlich put the total number of deaths at 1,200.<ref name=\"Freundlich\"/>\n\nAnother source of first-hand accounts in the region was [[Leon Trotsky]], who at the time was a war correspondent for the Kiev newspaper ''Kievskaya Misl''. His reports about Ferizaj describe the killings and looting which took place after the town was captured by the Serbian army.<ref name=\"Trotsky\">{{cite web |last1=Trotsky |first1=Leon |title=Behind the Curtains of the Balkan Wars |url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/1912_Trotsky/index.html |accessdate=29 March 2020 |ref=Trotsky}}</ref>\n\n====Luma====\n[[File:Krahina e Lum\u00ebs - (Luma region).png|thumb|150x150px|Luma region]]\nDuring the [[Balkan wars]] (1912-1913), Serb military forces attempting to assert their control of the region entered [[Luma (region)|Luma]] and attacked local inhabitants, killed tribal chieftains, removed livestock belonging to the population and razed villages.<ref name=\"Levene107\"/> The actions resulted in a local uprising by Albanians.<ref name=\"Levene107\"/> Serb forces retaliated through a scorched earth policy and massacres of the population ranging from the young to elderly, both men and women such as barricading people in mosques and houses and then firing upon or burning them.<ref name=\"Levene107\"/> Following the events, 25,000 people fled to Kosovo and western Macedonia.<ref name=\"Levene107\"/> The events have been considered by scholar Mark Levine as constituting a \"localized genocide\".<ref name=\"Levene107\">{{cite book|last=Levene|first=Mark|title=The Crisis of Genocide. Volume I: Devastation: The European Rimlands 1912\u20131938|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199683031|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RRgbAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA107&dq=Luma+genocide#v=onepage&q=Luma%20genocide&f=false|pages=107|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nWhen General Jankovi\u0107 saw that the Albanians of [[Lum\u00eb (region)|Luma]] would not allow Serbian forces to continue the advance to the Adriatic Sea, he ordered the troops to continue their brutality.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> The Serbian army massacred an entire population of men, women and children, not sparing anyone, and burned down 100-200houses and 27 villages in the area of Luma.<ref name=\"Archbishop\"/> Reports spoke of the atrocities by the Serbian army, including the burning of women and children bound to stacks of hay, within the sight of their fathers.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> Subsequently, about 400 men from Luma surrendered to Serbian authorities, but were taken to [[Prizren]], where they were murdered.<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/> The ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote that \"all the horrors of history have been outdone by the atrocious conduct of the troops of General Jankovic\".<ref name=\"Golgotha\"/>\n\nThe second Luma massacre was committed the following year (1913). After the London Ambassador Conference decided that Luma should be within the Albanian state, the Serbian army initially refused to withdraw. Albanians raised a great rebellion in September 1913, after which Luma once again suffered harsh retaliation from the Serbian army. A report of the International Commission cited a letter of a Serbian soldier, who described the punitive expedition against the rebel Albanians:<ref name=\"Report\"/>\n\n{{quote|My dear Friend, I have no time to write to you at length, but I can tell you that appalling things are going on here. I am terrified by them, and constantly ask myself how men can be so barbarous as to commit such cruelties. It is horrible. I dare not tell you more, but I may say that Luma (an Albanian region along the river of the same name), no longer exists. There is nothing but corpses, dust and ashes. There are villages of 100, 150, 200 houses, where there is no longer a single man, literally not one. We collect them in bodies of forty to fifty, and then we pierce them with our bayonets to the last man. Pillage is going on everywhere. The officers told the soldiers to go to Prizren and sell the things they had stolen.\"}}\n\nItalian daily newspaper ''Corriere delle Puglie'' wrote in December 1913 about official report that was sent to the Great Powers with details of the slaughter of Albanians in Luma and [[Debar]], executed after the proclamation of the amnesty by Serbian authorities. The report listed the names of people killed by Serbian units in addition to the causes of death: by burning, slaughtering, bayonets, etc. The report also provided a detailed list of the burned and looted villages in the area of Luma and Has.<ref name=\"Dibra\">[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_4.html Dole in Dibra: Official Report Submitted to the Great Powers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518073341/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_4.html |date=18 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nA [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] priest who visited Luma reported seeing \"[[Infanticide|poor bayonetted babies]]\" on the streets.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Edith |first1=Durham |title=Twenty Years Of Balkan Tangle |date=1920 |page=246 |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.234333/page/n245/mode/2up/search/shala |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Kumanovo====\nBritish army officer [[Christopher Birdwood Thomson]] was told by a Serbian general in Belgrade in 1913 that after the [[Battle of Kumanovo|3rd Serbian Army]] defeated the Turkish forces in Kumanovo, they entered the city and wiped out entire villages, massacring men, women and children in their homes, forcing others to flee resulting in death due to famine and cold. In 1920, he writes: \n{{Quote|text=Nothing more terrible has taken place in any part of the world, or in the whole history of war.|sign=Christopher Birdwood Thomson|source=Old Europe's Suicide: The Building of a Pyramid of Errors. Library of Alexandria, 1920}}\n\n====Gostivar====\nAfter the [[Battle of Kumanovo]] on October 23-24, 1912, the Serbian army [[First Army (Serbia)|Morava division]] entered [[Gostivar]], where hundreds of Albanians were massacred, which resulted in protests from Vienna. [[Leopold Berchtold]] was appalled by the massacres and asked Belgrade to withdraw from Albanian territory.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brook-Shepherd |first1=Gordon |title=The Austrians: A Thousand-Year Odyssey |date=2009 |publisher=Basic Books |isbn=978-0-7867-3066-7 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=z3s4DgAAQBAJ&pg=PT128&lpg=PT128&dq=leopold+berchtold+massacre+Albanians&source=bl&ots=uzwEmwMQMZ&sig=ACfU3U2wtSRdxvsZLkyijUoELSNxv8892w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjqqreRz73oAhUBw8QBHRU6AxUQ6AEwCXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=massacred&f=false |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On November 21, 1912, he wrote letters to Paris, London, Berlin, Rome and Petrograd where he stated: \u201cThe behavior of the Serbian army towards the Albanian people does not belong to any international human rights norm, but after the occupation of the countries they choose no means of dealing with it anymore. They acted brutally against the innocent and defenseless population\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pajaziti |first1=Ali |title=SHQIPTAR\u00cbT E REK\u00cbS S\u00cb EP\u00cbRME |pages=132-133 |edition=\"Pas pushtimit t\u00eb trevave shqiptare nga ana e ushtris\u00eb serbe, fillon nj\u00eb faz\u00eb tjet\u00ebr shum\u00eb e tmerrshme dhe e dhembshme p\u00ebr shqiptar\u00ebt, nga shkaku se ushtria serbe beri masakra n\u00eb t\u00eb gjitha viset e pushtuara. K\u00ebto masakra t\u00eb egra dhe barbare u v\u00ebrejt\u00ebn edhe nga ana e Fuqive t\u00eb M\u00ebdha, por reagoi vet\u00ebm Vjena. N\u00eb letr\u00ebn e Berhtoldit d\u00ebrguar Parisit, Londr\u00ebs, Berlinit, Rom\u00ebs dhe Petrogradit thuhet: \u201cSjellja e ushtris\u00eb serbe ndaj popullit shqiptar nuk i p\u00ebrket asnj\u00eb norme nd\u00ebrkomb\u00ebtare p\u00ebr t\u00eb drejtat e njeriut, por ato pas pushtimit t\u00eb vendeve nuk zgjedhin mjete sesi me u sjell\u00eb m\u00eb brutalisht ndaj popullat\u00ebs s\u00eb pafajshme dhe t\u00eb pambrojtur\" |url=https://www.academia.edu/23459558/SHQIPTAR\u00cbT_E_REK\u00cbS_S\u00cb_EP\u00cbRME |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>HHStA-PAA Letters of Berchtold sent to the Great Powers. Dok. Nr. 4545</ref>\n\n====Mitrovica====\nOn 18 November 1912, Sir F. Cartwright sent a letter to Sir Edward Grey explaining how the Serbian army entered Mitrovica and arrested the Austrian consul and held him prisoner for 15 days until he escaped to Budapest after he had witnessed atrocities being committed on Albanian civilians.<ref>{{cite book |author=Great Britain Foreign Office |title=The Balkan wars. pt. 1. The prelude; the Tripoli war. pt. 2. The league and Turkey |date=1934 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Office |page=168 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=2TguIIjeeb0C&pg=PA1122&dq=Servian+atrocities#v=onepage&q=Servian%20atrocities&f=false |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> According to an article in the ''Japan Times & Mail'' in 1912, the reason for the arrest of the consuls of Prizren and Mitrovica was the Serbian government did not want news to reach Austria that the Serbian soldiers had massacred Albanian civilians.<ref>{{cite book |title=Japan Times & Mail |date=1912 |page=352 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=bIQ-AQAAMAAJ&q=massacre+Mitrovitza&dq=massacre+Mitrovitza |accessdate=31 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Vusthrri====\nOn August 13, 1913, 17 Albanian civilians were massacred by Serbian soldiers when they entered [[Vushtrri]]. The event was despatched from the British Vice Consul W.D. Peckham in Skopje to the British Ambassador [[Sir Ralph Paget]] in Belgrade.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Elsie |first1=Robert |last2=Destani |first2=Bejtullah D. |title=Kosovo, A Documentary History: From the Balkan Wars to World War II |date=2018 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1-78673-354-2 |page=169 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=dbqKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR14&lpg=PR14&dq=Leopold+Berchtold+Serbia+Kosovo&source=bl&ots=CoskfT5R0L&sig=ACfU3U0RA3EIxP9EdMuObGpgZa5pC5uejw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj1x-2F0r3oAhVkw4sKHaLwBAAQ6AEwDHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=massacre&f=false |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Peja====\nIn 1912, the Serbian army bombarded the city of Peja and razed village after village, and were aided by Chetnik paramilitaries.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Remzije Sherifi (1955) |first1=Ibrahim Rugova |title=La Question Du Kosovo (The Shadow Behind The Sun|location=Prishtina |page=53 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=RIruxQEACAAJ&dq=Shadow+Behind+The+Sun+Remzije+Sherifi&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjp1JTkubroAhUotYsKHdMBA4MQ6AEIKDAA|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n[[Edith Durham]] writes about refugees from Peja after the Serbian army entered in 1913: \n\"An Ipek man, well educated and of high standing, told of what happened there. \"Every day the telal cried in the streets 'To-day the Government will shoot ten (or more men! No one knew which men they would be, or why they were shot. They were stood in a trench, which was to be their grave. Twelve soldiers fired and as the victims fell the earth was shovellwed over them, wether living or dead. Baptisms were forcd by torture. Men were plunged into the ice-cold river, and then half roased till they cried for mercy\". Many, terrorized into baptism, came to me\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Edith |first1=Durham |title=Twenty Years Of Balkan Tangle |date=1920 |page=246 |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.234333/page/n245/mode/2up/search/shala |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Gusinje and Plav====\nAfter the [[armistice]], Serbian troops bombarded the villages of Gusinje and Plav, rushed them and threw hand grenades, burning the villages, resulting an exodus of Albanian women and children fleeing to the mountains with many dying in the snow. An English doctor in Scutari examined the bands of refugees and travelled to Gusinje to examine the area and was immediately arrested by Serbian soldiers.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Saturday Review of Politics, Literature, Science and Art |date=1920 |publisher=Saturday Review |pages=276, 330 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-xs8AQAAMAAJ&dq=bombarding+at+Gusinje&q=bombarded |accessdate=31 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Novi Pazar====\nCaptain Carlo Papa di Castiglione d'Asti (1869-1955) was an Italian Major and military attach\u00e9 in Belgrade and Bucharest between 1908 and 1913 who observed the advancing Serbian Army. He reported that the Serbian army exterminated the Albanian population of Novi Pazar in order to facilitate Serbian domination.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rudi\u0107 |first1=Sr\u0111an |last2=Biagini |first2=Antonello |title=Serbian-Italian Relations: History and Modern Times : Collection of Works |date=2015 |publisher=The Institute of History, Belgrade / Sapienza University of Rome, Research center CEMAS |isbn=978-86-7743-109-9 |pages=79\u201380 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_7RPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA80&dq=Serbian+army+massacred+Albanians+1913#v=onepage&q=Albanians&f=false |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nWhen the Serb troops entered Sandzak, they massacred hundreds of civilians.<ref>Rugova, Sherifi, La Question Du Kosovo, The Shadow Behind The Sun, p. 53</ref>\n\nWhen the Ibar Army, commanded by General Mihailo Zivkovic, entered the town, he pacified the Albanian population with the method of \"soletudinem facient pacem appelant\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Richard C. |title=The Balkan Wars 1912-1913: Prelude to the First World War |date=2002 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-134-58362-1 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=DziCAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT231&lpg=PT231&dqXoECA0QLw#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Vilayet of Monastir ===\n\nIn the town of [[Ohrid]], Serbian forces killed 500 people consisting of Albanians and Turks.<ref name=\"Kramer138\">{{harvnb|Kramer|2008|p=138}}</ref>\n\n====Dibra====\nOn 20 September, the [[Serbian army]] carried off all the cattle of the Mal\u00ebsia of Dibra. The herdsmen were compelled to defend themselves, and to struggle, but they were all killed. The Serbians also killed two chieftains of the [[Lum\u00eb (region)|Luma]] clan, [[Mehmed Edem]] and [[Djafer Eleuz]], and the began pillaging and burning all the villages on their way: [[Peshkopi]], [[Blli\u00e7\u00eb]], and [[Dohoshisht]] in lower Dibra; and another seven villages in upper Dibra. In all these villages the Serbians committed acts of horrible massacres and outrage on women, children and old people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/reportofinternat00inteuoft#page/150/mode/2up|title=Report of the International Commission to Inquire into the Causes and Conduct of the Balkan War|accessdate=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs the Serbian Army invaded Albania through Dibra, Elbasan and Shkod\u00ebr, they bombarded cities and villages with artillery. The Albanian government telegraphed their delegates in Paris stating that the aim was the suppression of the Albanian state and the extermination of the Albanian population.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Nation |date=1920 |publisher=Nation Publishing Company Limited |page=626 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=cfFQAQAAMAAJ&dq=In+response%2C+during+the+fall+of+1913%2C+Serbian+troops+further+razed+Albanian+villages&q=bombarded |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an article in The Daily Mirror from 1914, interviewing Mr William Howard, an American relief commissioner, he states that in Dibra the Serbian troops destroyed 100 villages with 12,000 houses, and between 4000-8000 Albanians were burned, bayonetted or shot to death.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Archives |first1=British News Paper |title=\"Albanian Peasants Tortured and Burned Alive by Servians\" |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/BL/0000560/19140202/063/0009?browse=true |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk |agency=Daily Mirror |issue=Page 4 and 9 |publisher=The Daily Mirror |date=February 2, 1914}}</ref>\n\n====Pelagonia====\nIn September 1912, Serb majors M. Vasi\u0107 and [[Vasilije Trbi\u0107]] gathered 30 [[Chetniks]] and travelled to the village of [[Desovo]] where they shot 111 Albanian men and razed the village.<ref name=\"Timofeev271\"/> In nearby [[Brailovo]], Trbi\u0107 executed 60 Albanians.<ref name=\"Timofeev271\">{{cite book|last=Timofeev|first=Alexey|chapter=Serbian Chetniks: Traditions of Irregular Warfare|editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Wars of Yesterday: The Balkan Wars and the Emergence of Modern Military Conflict, 1912-13|year=2018|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=9781785337758|url=https://books.google.com/?id=okMtDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Wars+of+Yesterday:+The+Balkan+Wars+and+the+Emergence+of+Modern+Military+Conflict,+1912-13#v=snippet&q=Desovo&f=false|pages=271|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n====Porcasi and Sulp====\nIn these villages Porcasi and Sulp, Serbian soldiers took all the men out and asked the women to pay for their release. After payment, they were put inside a mosque which was blown up. In Sulp, 73 Albanians were murdered as well.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Prifti |first1=Kristaq |title=The Truth on Kosova |date=1993 |publisher=Encyclopaedia Publishing House |page=173 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YBq5AAAAIAAJ&dq=the+greatest+massacres+of+the+Albanian+population&q=massacred |accessdate=24 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Eyewitness accounts and reports==\nFor 12 years, the British anthropologist [[Edith Durham]] traveled to the region and became deeply interested in and knowledgeable of Albania and Albanians.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/><ref name=\"Hopken229\"/> In August 1912, Durham was in Montenegro and saw firsthand Montenegrin preparations for war along the border and altered the British press.<ref name=\"Dauti9495\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|pp=94-94}}</ref> She thought Montenegro was attempting to provoke the Ottomans into a conflict and Durham witnessed the outbreak of hostilities when Montenegrin king [[Nicholas I of Montenegro|Nikola]] directed his army to fire artillery shots into Albania.<ref name=\"Dauti95\"/> As the war began, Durham dispatched the news to the British press and for a prolonged period was the only war correspondent from the Montenegrin area.<ref name=\"Dauti95\"/> Newspapers sought her reports and Durham wrote over the course of many days for the [[Evening Chronicle|Chronicle]] and [[Manchester Guardian]], later she ceased after finding out they \"were cutting and even doctoring her articles\".<ref name=\"Dauti95\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=95}}</ref>\n\nEarly on in the conflict Durham, as a nurse, was involved in humanitarian relief work with the Red Cross and became aware of the atrocities.<ref name=\"Dauti97\"/><ref name=\"Hopken229\"/> Durham was close to the theatre of war and described the razed villages, the refugees and their dire plight, such as some resorting to sheltering in outhouses.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> She wrote a strongly worded indictment on the behavior of Serbs and Montenegrins.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/> Durham recounted in one instance that she went to see over thousand families whose homes were razed and referred to the negative views Montenegrins held against Albanians.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/> She encountered people from the frontlines like a Serb officer who viewed his time in Kosovo as \"heroism\" and \"nearly choked with laughter\" as he talked about how he \"bayoneted the women and children of Luma\".<ref name=\"Dauti97\"/> Durham heard sentiments from more officers about how \"no one would dare speak the dirty language\" (Albanian) in the newly acquired territories.<ref name=\"Dauti97\"/> Speaking in an open manner, they told Durham of the violence used to convert Catholic and Muslim Albanians into Orthodox Christianity.<ref name=\"Dauti97\"/> At the Montenegrin-Albanian frontier, Durham in her accounts described mutilation of \"nose cutting\" and other body parts sliced for \"their commanders\".<ref name=\"Hopken229\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2006|p=229}}</ref> The events of the war made Durham end her friendship with King Nikola due to the actions of the Montenegrin army.<ref name=\"Dauti959699\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|pp=95\u201396, 99}}</ref> At the time, the Albanian leadership used reports by Durham as firm evidence to strengthen their own nationalist rhetoric and put forward a position that objected to the violence committed by various armed forces present in the region, due to the war.<ref name=\"Dauti99\"/>\n\n[[Leon Trotsky]], later one of the leading figures of the Russian revolution, was at the time sent by a socialist Kiev newspaper as its wartime journalist to cover the Balkan Wars and he reported on the violence committed toward Albanians.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/><ref name=\"Trix42\"/> In the space of a few days after Skopje came under Serb control, Trotsky described the situation in and surrounding the city.<ref name=\"Trix42\"/> Trotsky was not present directly in the theatre of war, and he compiled his information from discussions he had with witnesses such as a Serbian friend who referred to \"horrors\" in the region of Macedonia.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/> The same friend had gained a military pass to travel to Skopje and told Trotsky:<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/><ref name=\"Trix42\"/>\n\n{{quotation|...the horrors actually began as soon as we crossed the old frontier. By five p.m. we were approaching Kumanovo. The sun had set, it was starting to get dark. But the darker the sky became, the more brightly the fearful illumination of the fires stood out against it. Burning was going on all around us. Entire Albanian villages had been turned into pillars of fire... In all its fiery monotony this picture was repeated the whole way to Skopje... For two days before my arrival in Skopje the inhabitants had woken up in the morning to the sight, under the principal bridge over the Vardar- that is, in the very centre of the town- of heaps of Albanian corpses with severed heads. Some said that these were local Albanians, killed by the ''komitadjis'' [''cjetniks''], others that the corpses were brought down to the bridge by the waters of the Vardar. What was clear was that these headless men had not been killed in battle.<ref name=\"Glenny234\">{{cite book|last=Glenny|first=Misha|title=The Balkans, 1804\u20132012: Nationalism, War and the Great Powers|publisher=Granta Books|isbn=9781847087720|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BVdheJDLWnkC&pg=PT6&dq=The+Balkans,+1804%E2%80%932012:+Nationalism,+War+and+the+Great+Powers#v=onepage&q=the%20horrors%20actually%20began%20as%20soon%20as%20we%20crossed&f=false|pages=234|ref=harv|date=November 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/><ref name=\"Trix42\"/>}}\n\nThe account given to Trotsky by the Serbian friend referred to the actions of Serb troops and their responsibility in Skopje for looting, fires, and in one example, the torture of local Albanian inhabitants of whom they spoke publicly about their deeds.<ref name=\"Vourkoutiotis1112\">{{cite book|last=Vourkoutiotis|first=Vasilis|title=Reform in Revolutionary Times: The Civil-military Relationship in Early Soviet Russia|year=2009|publisher=|isbn=978-1-4331-0210-3|url=https://books.google.com/?id=g0C3kXGeGQIC&pg=PA11&dq=Albanian+civilians+1912#v=onepage&q=Albanian%20civilians%201912&f=false|pages=11\u201312|ref=harv}}</ref> Many of the events in Skopje took place at night by Serb paramilitaries and in the morning, hundreds of headless Albanian corpses were in the Vardar river at the main bridge.<ref name=\"Trix42\"/> There was certainty that the bodies were not casualties from warfare and ambiguity on whether they were Albanians from the area or had flowed down from the upstream part of the Vardar.<ref name=\"Trix42\"/> The destruction of villages through arson resulted in the loss of homes and amassed wealth of targeted Albanians, whereas irregular troops entered homes to kill and steal.<ref name=\"Lieberman59\"/> Trotsky's Serbian friend described that Skopje had turned into a military camp and among the troops there were Serb peasants engaged in looting food, livestock and the doors and windows from Albanian houses.<ref name=\"Trix42\"/>\n\nIn observations of Serbian officers, the informant expressed disgust with their brutality and in moments of confrontation regarding their behavior, a corporal said to him that they differed from the komitajis (paramilitaries).<ref name=\"Trix42\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|p=42}}</ref> The corporal stated that the army \"would not kill anyone younger than twelve years of age\", whereas \"the komitajis engage in murder, robbery and violence as a savage sport\".<ref name=\"Trix4243\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|pp=42\u201343}}</ref> Authorities from the army responded by sending some komitajis home, due to the embarrassment they caused to the military.<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> The Serb informant wrote to Trotsky that \"meat is rotting, human flesh as well as the flesh of oxen\" and that the conflict \"brutalized\" people and made them lose \"their human aspect\".<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> Trotsky's Serbian friend also encountered a corporal in Kosovo who after being questioned about his actions responded \"Roasting chickens and killing Arnauts [Albanians]. But we're tired of it.\"<ref name=\"Lieberman59\">{{harvnb|Lieberman|2013|p=59}}</ref> In his report sent to Kiev newspaper ''Kievskaya Misl'' Trotsky writes about many \"atrocities committed against the Albanians of Macedonia and Kosovo in the wake of the Serbian invasion of October 1912\".<ref name=\"albanianhistory.net\">Robert Elsie, [http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1912_2.html Leo Trotsky: Behind the Curtains of the Balkan Wars] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212030202/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1912_2.html |date=12 December 2013 }}</ref> Trotsky reported that when [[Peter I of Serbia]] was on a tour at the frontlines, he said that Albanians ought to be clubbed till death as they did not deserve the ammunition.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mojzes |first1=Paul |title=Balkan Genocides: Holocaust and Ethnic Cleansing in the Twentieth Century |date=2011 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1-4422-0663-2 |page=32 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KwW2O7v7CUcC&pg=PA211&dq=how+many+Albanians+have+the+Servians+massacred#v=onepage&q=1912&f=false |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Qirezi46\">{{cite book|last=Qirezi|first=Arben|chapter=Settling the self-determination dispute in Kosovo|editor1-last=Mehmeti|editor1-first=Leandrit I.|editor2-last=Radelji\u0107|editor2-first=Branislav|title=Kosovo and Serbia: Contested Options and Shared Consequences|year=2017|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press|isbn=9780822981572|chapter-url=https://books.google.se/books?id=IWMqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT74&dq=chetniks+cruelty+Kosovo&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiOi-vg09joAhUypIsKHXwcBy0Q6AEIMjAB#v=snippet&q=1912&f=false|pages=46|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nAmong other instances he tells a shocking case of drunken Serbian soldiers torturing two young Albanians.\n\n<blockquote>Four soldiers held their bayonets in readiness and in their midst stood two young Albanians with their white felt caps on their heads. A drunken sergeant \u2013 a komitadji \u2013 was holding a kama (a Macedonian dagger) in one hand and a bottle of cognac in the other. The sergeant ordered: 'On your knees!' The petrified Albanians fell to their knees. 'To your feet!' They stood up. This was repeated several times. Then the sergeant, threatening and cursing, put the dagger to the necks and chests of his victims and forced them to drink some cognac, and then\u2026 he kissed them... Drunk with power, cognac and blood, he was having fun, playing with them as a cat would with mice. The same gestures and the same psychology behind them. The other three soldiers, who were not drunk, stood by and took care that the Albanians did not escape or try to resist, so that the sergeant could enjoy his moment of rapture. 'They're Albanians,' said one of the soldiers to me dispassionately. 'Hell soon put them out of their misery.',</blockquote>\n\nTrotsky wrote several dispatches and sent them home where he described the atrocities saying ''\"an individual, a group, a party of a class that is capable of 'objectively' picking its nose while it watches men drunk with blood, and incited from above, massacring defenceless people is condemned by history to rot and become worm-eaten while it is still alive\".''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Trotsky |first1=Leon |title=The Balkan Wars, 1912-13: The War Correspondence of Leon Trotsky |date=1980 |publisher=Resistance Books |isbn=978-0-909196-08-0 |page=293 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=tEJmenVPZ-IC&pg=PA293&dq=Leon+Trotsky++an+individual,+a+group,+a+party+of+a+class+that+is+capable+of+%27objectively%27+picking+its+nose+while+it+watches+men+drunk+with+blood,+and+incited+from+above,+massacring+defenceless+people+is+condemned+by+history+to+rot+and+become+worm-eaten+while+it+is+still+alive#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn report by the British Foreign Office, a description of a telegram by the Italian consul in Skopje stated that \"atrocities being committed by Serbian troops and their evident intention of extirpating as many of the Albanian inhabitants as possible\".<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> A Swiss engineer, employed as an overseer for the Oriental railway submitted a report to the British embassy in Belgrade that gave details regarding Skopje following the arrival of Serbian soldiers.<ref name=\"Trix43241\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|pp=43, 241}}</ref> The report described that the conduct of Serbs against the Muslim population was \"cruel in every way\" and appeared to \"have for its object their complete extermination\".<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> The Swiss engineer had written that the sound of arms discharged began from early in the day and continued till late, and prisoners were treated badly such as officers shot without trials.<ref name=\"Trix43\"/> The report described that \"an order was issued to soldiers in certain places to kill all Albanians from the age of eight years upwards with a view to extermination. The Serbians have ill treated the sick, women and children.\"<ref name=\"Trix43\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|p=43}}</ref> Other details in the report described that mosques were destroyed, villages razed in their entirety and that the number of bodies floating in the Vardar were some 500.<ref name=\"Trix4344\">{{harvnb|Trix|2016|pp=43\u201344}}</ref> The Swiss engineer summed up the situation and said that \"the Albanians were \"desperate\".<ref name=\"Trix44\"/>\n\n=== Historicity of information ===\nScholarship treats wartime correspondences from the entire Balkan Wars as first-hand evidence and historian Wolfgang H\u00f6pken says those sources need to be handled with care.<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/> H\u00f6pken states that reporters, such as Trotsky who provided first hand data were not near the theatre of war,<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/> however, his accounts of the Balkan Wars were \"some of the most brilliant and most analytical war reports\".<ref name=\"Hopken234\"/>\n\nJournalists of the time based in the Balkans like Richard von Mach from K\u00f6lnische Zeitung described that the accounts were often either data from a third party or \"even pure fiction\".<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/> Writers such as Carl Pauli attained their data from nameless witnesses or gathered evidence from the extensive compilation of information by Leo Freundlich, who wrote about the situation in the Albanian conflict zone and expressed empathy for Albanian victims.<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/> H\u00f6pken states that these sources have significance, although the information given \"can hardly be taken for granted\".<ref name=\"Hopken41\"/>\n\nThe report by the International Carnegie Commission, often cited by the prosecution as an important witness and quoted multiple times, \"cannot\" says H\u00f6pken, \"be read without a due deconstructative effort on the part of the historian\".<ref name=\"Hopken41\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2018|p=41}}</ref> Historian Alan Kramer regards the Carnegie Commission report as a \"remarkably well-documented and impartial investigation, coolly sceptical of exaggerated claims, reached conclusions that have not been improved to this day.\"<ref name=\"Kramer138\"/> Diplomatic missions located in the Balkans repeatedly sent reports  on the rumors and news regarding violent actions committed by all participants in the Balkan Wars.<ref name=\"Hopken4142\"/> On multiple occasions they made complaints about being unable to get first-hand data.<ref name=\"Hopken4142\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2018|pp=41\u201342}}</ref> Reports from British consuls described many examples of violent actions perpetrated by Serb irregular forces in Kosovo and Macedonia following their capture during 1912-1913 by the Serbian military.<ref name=\"Hopken234\">{{cite book|last=H\u00f6pken|first=Wolfgang|chapter=Preforming Violence: Soldiers, Paramilitaries and Civilians in the Twentieth-Century Balkan Wars|editor1-last=L\u00fcdtke|editor1-first=Alf|editor2-last=Weisbrod|editor2-first=Bernd|title=No Man's Land of Violence: Extreme Wars in the 20th Century|year=2006|publisher=Wallstein Verlag|isbn=9783892448259|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wr-j5ibVgXsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=No+Man%27s+Land+of+Violence:+Extreme+Wars+in+the+20th+Century#v=onepage&q=balkan%20wars%20albanians%20killed&f=false|pages=234|ref=harv}}</ref> The British government was suspicious about the authenticity of the complaints and reports that made them hesitant to undertake any political action.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/>\n\nAt a time when political relations were tense with Serbia, Austro-Hungary took a keen interest to gather together details of Serbian atrocities and  subjected their sources to critical scrutiny and to determine whether informants were reliable.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> Austro-Hungarians described that often there was \"a great deal of exaggeration\" of certain data that came into their possession.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> They also stated that accounts from witnesses whose reliability was verified, confirmed that heavy use of violence occurred such as the killings of children and women, wide scale theft and the razing of villages and houses.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> For example, in Skopje, Macedonia, the Austro-Hungarian consul Heimroth sent his assistants multiple times out into the field to closely examine news of atrocities before sending reports such as Gausamkeiten der Serben gegen Albaner back to Vienna.<ref name=\"Hopken70\"/>\n\nAn extensive report by Catholic bishop [[Laz\u00ebr Mjeda]] regarding Serbian violence toward Skopje Muslim and Albanian inhabitants was the subject of detailed discussion in the Austro-Hungarian consulate.<ref name=\"Hopken70\"/> Afterward they came to the conclusion that it was well founded in the overall depiction of the situation it portrayed.<ref name=\"Hopken70\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2018|p=70}}</ref> In a long report on what he witnessed, Consul Heimroth stated that at a bare minimum, Serbian forces ought to be held to account for not halting the violence committed against Muslims after their arrival into Skopje.<ref name=\"Hopken43\"/> Heimroth described that in this war he heard more complaints regarding wartime violence then in the [[Russo-Japanese war]] and that the conflict whose aim was liberating fellow Christians concluded with an attempt to exterminate non-Orthodox inhabitants.<ref name=\"Hopken43\">{{cite book|last=H\u00f6pken|first=Wolfgang|chapter='Modern Wars' and 'Backward Societies': The Balkan Wars in the History of Twentieth-Century European Warfare|editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Wars of Yesterday: The Balkan Wars and the Emergence of Modern Military Conflict, 1912-13|year=2018|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=9781785337758|url=https://books.google.com/?id=okMtDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Wars+of+Yesterday:+The+Balkan+Wars+and+the+Emergence+of+Modern+Military+Conflict,+1912-13#v=snippet&q=heimroth&f=false|pages=43|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nAccounts given by nonpartisan witnesses from the Balkan Wars of what they saw included foreign workers and engineers from the Oriental Railway and the local and foreign Christian clergy.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> For some observers, they suspected that forced population movements (ethnic cleansing) were part of an organised effort of extermination.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> H\u00f6pken states there is insufficient support for that position in the sources, and instead, those events \"radicalised\" the continuing course toward homogenising populations along ethnic lines.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> Historian [[Mark Mazower]] states despite the \"careless talk of 'exterminating' the Albanian population\", the killing of \"perhaps thousands of civilians\" by Serbian armed forces in the provinces of Kosovo and Monastir was \"prompted more by revenge than genocide\".<ref name=\"Mazower\">{{cite book |last1= Mazower |first1= Mark |authorlink1= Mark Mazower |title= The Balkans, From the End of Byzantium to the Present Day |trans-title=  |chapter-url= http://www.orionbooks.co.uk/books/the-balkans-paperback |year= 2001 |origyear= 2000 |publisher= Phoenix Press |location= Great Britain |isbn= 978-1-84212-544-1 |chapter= Building the nation-state. |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/balkansuniversal00mark }}\"In the former Ottoman districts of Kosovo and Monastir, in particular, the conquering Serbian army killed perhaps thousands of civilians. Despite some Serbian officer's careless talk of \"exterminating\" the Albanian population, this was killing prompted more by revenge than genocide.\"</ref> \n\nEdwin E. Jacques quotes the French [[L'Ind\u00e9pendance Belge|L'Ind\u00e9pendance Albanaise]] stating in an article from Mars 15, 1915 that the atrocities were committed in cold blood.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jacques |first1=Edwin E. |title=The Albanians: An Ethnic History from Prehistoric Times to the Present |date=1995 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-89950-932-7 |page=352 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=IJ2s9sQ9bGkC&pg=PA273&dq=1912+Shkodra+atrocities&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwior6O0ucXoAhXCrIsKHRTZABAQ6AEIQDAD#v=onepage&q=atrocities&f=false |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nThe information gathered from observations by individuals or \"reliable\" and \"non-partisan\" informants who witnessed the events \"left no doubt\", H\u00f6pken says, that extensive violence took place against people, like the razing of homes and villages and forced population movements.<ref name=\"Hopken42\"/> Separate to what H\u00f6pken calls \"suspicious slaughter narratives\" from second and third hand accounts, medical physicians and nurses verified from what they witnessed in hospitals that the \"conflict had gone beyond all rules and regulations\".<ref name=\"Hopken42\">{{harvnb|H\u00f6pken|2018|p=42}}</ref>\n\nIn literature and scholarship among Albanians, the actions and conduct described in Durham's accounts are the outcome of intentional anti-Albanian policies that the Serb government organised to \"exterminate Albanians\".<ref name=\"Dauti97\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=97}}</ref> Scholar Daut Dauti states that Durham's wartime reports \"amounted to atrocity testimonies committed against Albanians\".<ref name=\"Dauti99\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=99}}</ref> The accounts given by Durham came under criticism from individuals such as [[Rebecca West]], a fellow traveler of the region and author.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> West stated that Durham showed naivety and mocked her support of a report from 1912 that claimed falsely the Austrian consul was castrated by the Serbs at Prizren.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> Historian Benjamin Lieberman wrote that West also has been accused of showing a preference toward Serbs in her works.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> Lieberman said that Durham was an eyewitness to the conflict and in the interviews Trotsky conducted with Serbs, his informants lacked a motive to portray their fellow troops and citizens in a negative manner.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\"/> In the accounts recorded by Trotsky, Durham and other people of the time, Lieberman states they are consistent and corroborated by additional sources such as from Catholic Church officials who referred to multiple massacres.<ref name=\"Lieberman60\">{{cite book|last=Lieberman|first=Benjamin|title=Terrible Fate: Ethnic Cleansing in the Making of Modern Europe|year=2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781442230385|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UXlfAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Terrible+Fate:+Ethnic+Cleansing+in+the+Making+of+Modern+Europe#v=onepage&q=balkan%20wars%20catholic%20reports%20durham&f=false|pages=60|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions to the killings==\nAccording to Misha Glenny, on the eve of war, Serbian press published banner headlines encouraging patriotic hysteria with messages such as \"Get ready for war! The joint Serbo-Bulgarian offensive will start any minute now!\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Glenny |first1=Misha |title=The Balkans, 1804\u20132012: Nationalism, War and the Great Powers |date=2012 |publisher=Granta Publications |isbn=978-1-84708-772-0 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=BVdheJDLWnkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Balkans+Glenny&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH48Xu_djoAhWhtIsKHWl0D-QQ6AEIMDAB#v=snippet&q=1912&f=false |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrench General [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric-Georges Herr]] reported on January 3, 1913, that \u201din the Albanian massif, the numerous massacres that bloodied this region reduced the population to strong proportions. Many villages were destroyed and the land remained barren\u201d.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Murzaku |first1=Thoma |title=Politika e Serbis\u00eb kundrejt Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb gjat\u00eb luft\u00ebs Ballkanike: 1912-1913 |date=1987 |publisher=Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb, Instituti i Historis\u00eb |page=140 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=YqC4AAAAIAAJ&q=masakrat+1912&dq=masakrat+1912&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcwM7nnsLoAhXQxIsKHXrNB1s4ChDoAQgnMAA&fbclid=IwAR0n0ebBWzEeiRkDVoLOIGos014U1csl356HsFZnYPECcLu55sjvC9opvXU |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=sq}}</ref>\n\nEdith Durham, along with European socialists Leo Freundlich, Leon Trotsky, and Serbian socialists like Kosta Novakovi\u0107, [[Dragi\u0161a Lap\u010devi\u0107]], Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107 and others shared the same stance of condemning the atrocities perpetrated on Albanians and all supported Albanian self determination.<ref name=\"Dauti90\">{{harvnb|Dauti|2017|p=90}}</ref>\n\nIn a letter written by [[Edith Durham|Durham]] in regards to [[Isa Boletini]] she writes how [[Dragutin Dimitrijevi\u0107|Dragutin Dimitrijevi\u0107 Apis]] and his friends betrayed the Albanians after they successfully revolted against the Ottomans: \"Having used their ammunition in the recent rebellions, the bulk of the Albanians were practically unarmed, and were pitilessly massacred by the invading armies. Apis and his friends who had posed as friends of the Albanians now spared neither man, woman nor child. How many were massacred in Kosovo vilayet will never be known\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Images |first1=Fm |title=Edith Durham: Note on Serb action with regard to ISA BOLETIN by M.E. Durham. US 55. |url=https://www.fmimages.net/edith-durham-ja-si-e-tradhetuan-serbet-isa-boletinin/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=FM Images |agency=FM Images Albania |issue=\"Having used their ammunition i nthe recent rebellions to bulk of the Albanians were practically unarmed, and were pitilessly massacred by the invading armies. Apis and his friends who had posed as friends of the Albanians now spared neither man, woman nor child. How many were massacred in Kosovo vilayet will never be known\". |date=22 December 2019 |language=sq}}</ref> \n\nIn order to investigate the crimes, the [[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]] formed a special commission, which was sent to the [[Balkans]] in 1913. Summing the situation in Albanian areas, the Commission concludes:\n\n{{quotation|Houses and whole villages reduced to ashes, unarmed and innocent populations massacred en masse, incredible acts of violence, pillage and brutality of every kind \u2013 such were the means which were employed and are still being employed by the Serbo-Montenegrin soldiery, with a view to the entire transformation of the ethnic character of regions inhabited exclusively by Albanians.<ref name=\"Report\"/><ref name=\"Pezo67\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|p=67}}</ref>|[[Report of the International Commission on the Balkan Wars]]}}\n\nSerbian territorial claims upon the region were complicated by the issue of war crimes perpetrated by Serbian military forces that were part of an investigation by the Carnegie Commission for the Balkan Wars.<ref name=\"Jovanovic41\"/> The report was received negatively by Serb historians and officials, even though the Serbian side was treated with restraint in comparison to others who had partaken in the conflict.<ref name=\"Jovanovic41\"/> The socialist press in Serbia referred to crimes, such as the prominent Serbian socialist Dimtrije Tucovi\u0107 who wrote about the Serbian campaign in Kosovo and northern Albania.<ref name=\"Jovanovic41\">{{harvnb|Jovanovi\u0107|2019|p=41.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Captain Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107.jpg|thumb|150px|Captain [[Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107]]]]\n{{quote|We have carried out the attempted [[premeditated murder]] of an entire nation. We were caught in that criminal act and have been obstructed. Now we have to suffer the punishment.... In the Balkan Wars, Serbia not only doubled its territory, but also its external enemies.<ref>{{cite book |first=T. |last=Gallagher |title=The Balkans in the New Millennium: In the Shadow of War and Peace |publisher=Routledge |year=2006 |isbn=0-415-34940-0}}</ref>|[[Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107]]}}\n\nTucovi\u0107 described the events as \"barbarian crematoria in which hundreds of women and children were burned\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Karadjis |first1=Michael |title=Kosova and the right of oppressed nations to self-determination |edition=\"Serbian Marxist Dimitrije Tucovic witnessed \"barbaric crematoria in which hundreds of women and children are burnt alive\" |url=https://www.academia.edu/2613683 |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Clark |first1=Howard |title=Civil Resistance in Kosovo |date=2000 |publisher=Pluto Press |isbn=978-0-7453-1569-0 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=OTW9XKUmrxsC&pg=PA9&dq=Dimitrije+Tucovic+women+and+children#v=onepage&q=Dimitrije%20Tucovic%20women%20and%20children&f=false |accessdate=15 December 2019 |language=en|page=9}}</ref> \nIn 1913, Tucovi\u0107 tried to remind his Serbian readers with [[Karl Marx|Marx's]] \"prophetic\" quote ''\"the nation that oppresses another nation forges its own chains\"'', however, this proved ineffective as the [[Serbian Orthodox Church in Kosovo|Serbian Orthodox Church]] had whipped up nationalist hatred towards Albanians.<ref>{{cite book |last1=MacShane |first1=Denis |title=Why Kosovo Matters |date=2012 |publisher=Haus Publishing |isbn=978-1-907822-51-3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=F1grDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT19&dq=Leon+Trotsky+Kosovo#v=onepage&q=Tucovic&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In his book ''Srbija i Arbanija'', Tucovi\u0107 writes:<ref>{{cite book |title=The South Slav Journal |date=1985 |publisher=Dositey Obradovich Circle. |page=29 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=axoWAQAAMAAJ&dq=Dimitrije+Tucovic+crematoria&q=barbarian+crematoria |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The bourgeois press called for merciless annihilation and the army acted upon this. Albanian villages, from which the men had fled in time, were reduced to ashes. At the same time, these were barbarian crematoria in which hundreds of women and children were burned. | Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107<ref name=\"Dedijer590\">{{cite book|last=Dedijer|first=Vladimir|title=Novi prilozi za biografiju Josipa Broza Tita, Vol. I|year=1981|publisher=Liburnija|url=https://books.google.com/?id=L7EfAQAAMAAJ&q=Tucovi%C4%87+krematorijumi&dq=Tucovi%C4%87+krematorijumi|pages=590|ref=harv}} \"Bur\u017eoaska \u0161tampa je tra\u017eila istrebljenje bez milosti, a vojska je izvr\u0161ivala. Arbanaska sela iz kojih su ljudi bili blagovremeno izbegli behu pretvorena u zgari\u0161ta. To behu u isto vreme varvarski krematorijumi u kojima je sagorelo stotinama \u017eivih \u017eena i deca\"</ref>}}\n\nIn the second half of the twentieth century, historian [[Vladimir Dedijer]] conducted research into Serbian foreign relations of the era.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> Dedijer stated that he was convinced by the information from Tucovi\u0107 and equated the actions of the Serbian military to European colonial armies engaged in Africa, South America and Africa.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> For example, Prime Minister [[Nikola Pa\u0161i\u0107]] at the time attempted to portray the whole narrative of crimes by the Serbian army to international powers as fabricated propaganda from foreign sources.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> The press in Britain and Germany kept printing articles about the large numbers of Albanian deaths in Albania and Kosovo, and the attempts by the Serbian government to conceal the reality from its people through censorship.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> In an issue from 18 January 1913, the most resolute charges of wrongdoing came from the London Times where it described that 25,000 Albanians were killed in northeastern Albania by Serbian forces.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/>\n\nRussia played a significant part in the territorial division of Albanian areas and the propaganda regarding crimes committed by Serbs.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> Russian Foreign Minister [[Sergey Sazonov]] warned Pa\u0161i\u0107 on multiple occasions through the Serbian representative in St.Petersburg about the need to disavow every single case, as in Gjakova, where Serbian forces were alleged to have shot 300 Albanian individuals.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> Sazonov repeatedly told Serbs that the Austrians were prepared to accept Gjakova as part of Serbia, so long as no alleged casualties occurred.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> At the same time, Russia assisted Serbia in gaining the towns of Debar, Prizren and Pec from Albania and undertook similar efforts to gain Gjakova for the Serbs, while Austria-Hungary attempted to retain the remaining territory for Albania.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/>\n\nThe Serbian social democrat paper ''Radnica novice'' wrote that Albanians were robbed and plundered and the villages devestated and that no one had felt the fury of liberators so strongly as the innocent Albanians.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Prifti |first1=Kristaq |title=The Truth on Kosova |date=1993 |publisher=Encyclopaedia Publishing House |page=140 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YBq5AAAAIAAJ&dq=atrocities+against+Albanians+1912&q=radnica |accessdate=24 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1913, the Russian paper [[Novoye Vremya (newspaper)|''Novoye vremya'']] refused to acknowledge the Serbian atrocities against Albanian civilians in Skopje and Prizren and instead began citing local Catholic priests who said that the Serb army had not committed a single act of violence against the civil population.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Boeckh |first1=Katrin |last2=Rutar |first2=Sabine |title=The Balkan Wars from Contemporary Perception to Historic Memory |date=2017 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-3-319-44642-4 |page=127 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aIXgDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA73&dq=atrocities+Albanians+1913#v=onepage&q=atrocities%20Albanians%201913&f=false |accessdate=28 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAn American relief agent named B. Peele Willett wrote in his report ''The Christian Work Fall'' from 1914 that:<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jacques |first1=Edwin E. |title=The Albanians: An Ethnic History from Prehistoric Times to the Present |date=1995 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-89950-932-7 |page=341 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=IJ2s9sQ9bGkC&pg=PA273&dq=1912+Shkodra+atrocities&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwior6O0ucXoAhXCrIsKHRTZABAQ6AEIQDAD#v=onepage&q=Shkodra&f=false |language=en}}</ref>\n{{quotation|...\"Serbian and Montenegrin troops destroyed one hundred villages in northern Albania without warning, without provocation, without excuse. ... 12,000 homes were burned and dynamited, 8,000 farm folk killed or burned to death, 125,000 made homeless. All livestock has been driven off. Corn fresh from the harvest has been carried away. Like hunted animals the farm folk fled to Elbasan, Tirana, Scutari and outlying villages. I have returned from a 400-mile journey, partly on foot, through these stricken regions. I saw the destroyed villages, the burned and dynamited houses. I saw the starving refugees. I saw women and children dying of hunger.\"<ref>Quoted from \"The Christian Work Fall\" from 1914. p.477</ref>}}\n\nThe Habsburg envoy in Belgrade at the time stated that the Serbian authorities were sponsoring and tolerating harsh treatments of Albanians specifically through pillaging, arson, and executions in the \"liberated lands\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=B\u00f6hler |first1=Jochen |last2=Borodziej |first2=Wlodzimierz |last3=Puttkamer |first3=Joachim von |title=Legacies of Violence: Eastern Europe's First World War |date=2014 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn=978-3-486-85756-6 |page=45 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jXnpBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA42&dq=Serbian+army+atrocities+1912#v=onepage&q=Albanian&f=false |accessdate=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe German newspaper ''[[Frankfurter Zeitung]]'' wrote it had obtained reports whose plausibility was corroborated by observers from Europe with an impartial stance, that massacres were committed in Albania and the region of Macedonia by Bulgarians, Serbs and Greeks.<ref name=\"Kramer137\"/> The newspaper stated that the position of the Serbs was the Albanian population \"must be eradicated\".<ref name=\"Kramer137\">{{cite book|last=Kramer|first=Alan|title=Dynamic of destruction: Culture and Mass killing in the First World War|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780191580116|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6Gbgs1XFKTcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Dynamic+of+Destruction:+Culture+and+Mass+Killing+in+the+First+World+War#v=onepage&q=albanians&f=false|pages=137|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn 1921, ''The Near East'' published an article of the Albanian deputies who had spoken on 28 July on the Ambassadors Conference in Tirana stating that between 1913 and 1920, Serbian forces had killed approximately 85 676 Albanian civilians in Kosovo, with numerous villages being burned. They also stated that the [[Black Hand (Serbia)|The Black Hand]] had brought Russian colonists to settle in the areas where Albanians had been killed or expelled in Kosovo.<ref>{{cite book |author=Near East College Association (New York, N.Y.) |title=The Near East |date=1921 |publisher=s.n. |location=Tirana |page=199 |edition=Albanians at the Ambassador Conference in Tirana, 1 August. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=gD8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA763&dq=Serbian+tyranny#v=snippet&q=massacred&f=false |accessdate=31 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 1913, British official Mr. Dayrell Crackanthorpe sent a letter to Edward Grey from Belgrade mentioning an Albanian uprising against Serbian forces which the Austrians stated was due to the fact that Serbian army had not withdrawn their forces from Albania and that they had committed massacres on the civilian population.<ref>{{cite book |author=Great Britain Foreign Office |title=pt. 1. The Near and Middle East on the eve of war. pt. 2. The last years of Peace |date=1936 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Office |page=14 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=GxCamBG25ZsC&pg=PA15&dq=Servian+raids+on+Albanians+1913#v=onepage&q=Albanians&f=false |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A third reason was that the Serbian authorities had closed the borders thus cutting off important food markets necessary to the local population.\n\nA Romanian doctor named Leonte wrote in the Bucharest paper Adevarul on 6 January 1913, that the horrors inflicted by the Serbian Army in Kosovo were ''\"much more frightening than one could imagine\"''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schwartz |first1=Stephen |title=Kosovo: Background to a War |date=2000 |publisher=Anthem Press |isbn=978-1-898855-56-9 |page=59 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jL4tAQAAIAAJ&q=Adeverul+Serbian+Army+1913&dq=Adeverul+Serbian+Army+1913 |accessdate=2 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHenrik August Angel, a [[Norwegian people|Norwegian]] military officer and writer who personally followed the trail of the [[Ottoman army]] and army of [[Kingdom of Serbia]], in his work<ref>{{Citation |last1=Henrik August|first1=Angel |title=Kada se jedan mali narod bori za \u017eivot: Srpske vojni\u010dke pri\u010de |publisher=Haka |year=1995|isbn=978-86-81635-01-8 }}</ref> described \"[[demonization]] of [[Serbs]]\" in texts published in English language newspapers, and especially in German language newspapers from [[Germany]] and [[Austria-Hungary]], as \"shameful injustice\".<ref>{{cite news| title       = Istorija \u2013 mit i zablude| first       = Dragan| last        = Vlahovi\u0107 | newspaper   = [[Politika]] | publisher   = Politika Newspapers and Magazines | location    = Belgrade | date        = 25 December 2010 | language    = Serbian |trans-title=History \u2013 myth and misconceptions | quote       = Igrom slu\u010daja.... prejahao popri\u0161te i sopstvenim nogama i\u0161ao tragom turske i srpske vojske...  Srbima naneta sramotna nepravda... sanjao dopisnik iz Budimpe\u0161te}}</ref><sup>{{Unreliable source?|date=March 2020}}</sup>\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn scholarship, reliable numbers exist for military casualties of the Balkan Wars.<ref name=\"Pezo67\"/> A research gap exists on civilian victims, often from a targeted ethnic or religious group, due to the statistics being interpreted and used for nationalist purposes.<ref name=\"Pezo67\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|p=67}}</ref> The Balkan Wars resulted in numerous people becoming refugees and some fled to [[Istanbul]] or [[Anatolia]].<ref name=\"Pezo70\"/> Following the creation of Albania, Albanian refugees, in particular of the Muslim religion sought shelter in the country.<ref name=\"Pezo70\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|p=70}}</ref> In late 1913, Serbian control was challenged by an insurgency in the [[Ohrid\u2013Debar uprising]] and its defeat by Serbian forces resulted in tens of thousands of Albanian refugees arriving in Albania from Western Macedonia.<ref name=\"Pezo667071\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|pp=66, 70\u201371}}</ref> At the time, news reports by Freundlich stated that in the town of Shkod\u00ebr, the Albanian refugee population numbered 8,000-10,000, 7,000 in the [[Shala (region)|Shala]] region and 7,000 in the [[Iball\u00eb]] area.<ref name=\"Pezo7071\">{{harvnb|Pezo|2017|pp=70\u201371}}</ref> As a large number of refugees were located in northern Albania, scholar Edvin Pezo says that part of the population likely arrived from the Kosovo area.<ref name=\"Pezo71\"/> A lack of assistance from the new Albanian government and Albanian immigration restrictions by the Ottomans, drove many refugees to return to their place of origin, often finding their houses were destroyed.<ref name=\"Pezo71\">{{cite book|last=Pezo|first=Edvin|chapter=Violence, Forced Migration, and Population Policies During and After the Balkan Wars (1912-14) |editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Balkan Wars from Contemporary Perception to Historic Memory|year=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319446424|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aIXgDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Balkan+Wars+from+Contemporary+Perception+to+Historic+Memory#v=onepage&q=Montenegrin%20army%20balkan%20wars%20albanians&f=false|pages=71|ref=harv}}</ref> People that lived through violent events of the Balkan Wars, such as those in Skopje, often did not talk about their experiences.<ref name=\"Trix44\"/>\n\nAs a result of the [[Treaty of London, 1913|Treaty of London]] in 1913 which designated the former Ottoman lands to Serbia, Montenegro and Greece (namely, the large part of the Vilayet of Kosovo being awarded to Serbia), an independent Albania was recognised. As such, Greece, Serbia and Montenegro agreed to withdraw from the territory of the new [[Principality of Albania]]. The principality however included only about half of the territory populated by ethnic Albanians and a large number of Albanians remained in neighboring countries.<ref name=\"Elsie\">[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1913_2.html Robert Elsie, The Conference of London 1913] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.albanianhistory.net%2Ftexts20_1%2FAH1913_2.html&date=2011-02-11 |date=11 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe previous two Serbian Army invasions into Albania, one in 1913 and the second in May 1915, made many Albanian locals take revenge through sniper attacks upon the [[Great Retreat (Serbian)|retreating Serb army during World War One]], in part as retribution for Serbian brutality in the First Balkan War.<ref name=\"Mojzes42198\">{{cite book|last=Mojzes|first=Paul|title=Balkan Genocides: Holocaust and Ethnic Cleansing in the Twentieth Century|year=2011|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-4422-0663-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=m5bDUFZXQ5sC&pg=PA198&dq=Serbian+army+retreat+albania+revenge#v=onepage&q=Serbian%20retreat%20albania%20revenge&f=false|pages=42, 198|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Majstorovic178\">{{cite book|last=Majstorovic|first=Steven|chapter=Autonomy of the Sacred: The Endgame in Kosovo|editor1-last=M\u00e1iz|editor1-first=Ram\u00f3n|editor2-last=William|editor2-first=Safran|title=Identity and Territorial Autonomy in Plural Societies|year=2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135303945|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=MvqiAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT184&dq=Serbian+army+retreat+albania+revenge&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwie253Utf7lAhWA73MBHRtUAVEQ6AEIRTAE#v=onepage&q=Serbian%20army%20retreat%20albania%20revenge&f=false|pages=8178|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Ramet48\">{{cite book|last=Ramet|first=Sabrina P.|title=The Three Yugoslavias: State-building and Legitimation, 1918-2005|year=2006|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253346568|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FTw3lEqi2-oC&pg=PA48&dq=Serbian+army+retreat+albania+revenge#v=onepage&q=Serbian%20army%20retreat%20albania%20revenge&f=false|pages=48|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe Balkan wars resulted in Serbian forces viewing themselves as a \"liberator\", whereas non-Serbs became concerned about the future and their integration into the new reality.<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\"/> The current Serbian position of the Balkan Wars is that it was a \"final\" freedom struggle to liberate \"the cradle of Serbdom and occupied brothers.\"<ref name=\"Jovanovic42\">{{cite book|last=Jovanovi\u0107|first=Vladan|chapter=\"Reconquista of Old Serbia\": On the continuity of territorial and demographic policy in Kosovo|editor1-last=Pavlovi\u0107|editor1-first=Aleksandar|editor2-last=Dra\u0161ko|editor2-first=Gazela Pudar|editor3-last=Halili|editor3-first=Rigels|title=Rethinking Serbian-Albanian Relations: Figuring out the Enemy|year=2019|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351273145|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?hl=en&lr=&id=YCCeDwAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA39&dq=%22Reconquista+of+Old+Serbia%22:+On+the+continuity+of+territorial+and+demographic+policy+in+Kosovo&ots=8MENqkhlj4&sig=o0cIcr9ymyIzHKV8zcic8TKe-Gg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=balkan%20wars%2025%2C000%20Albanians&f=false|pages=42|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn Macedonian and Yugoslav books on history, accounts of violent events such as those that occurred in Skopje are not mentioned.<ref name=\"Trix44\">{{cite book|last=Trix|first=Frances|title=Urban Muslim migrants in Istanbul: Identity and trauma among Balkan immigrants|year=2016|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=9781786731081|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=KBOMDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=Albanians&f=false|pages=44|ref=harv}}</ref> The majority of history books in Albania and Kosovo present the notion of attacking the Ottoman state to liberate Greeks, Serbs and Albanians from government misrule as a positive move.<ref name=\"Dauti96\"/> They interpret the arrival and conduct by Serbian, Greek and Montenegrin military forces in Albania, as \"chauvinist\" and unwarranted.<ref name=\"Dauti96\"/> The \"liberation\" of the Albanian population by military forces, especially Serbian and Montenegrin armies belonging to the Balkan League is described as the \"invasion of enemies\", or that of longstanding \"foes\".<ref name=\"Dauti96\"/> In Albania and Kosovo, this particular understanding of the Balkan Wars prevails within school textbooks and the education curriculum.<ref name=\"Dauti96\">{{cite book|last=Dauti|first=Daut|chapter=Gjergj Fishta, the \"Albanian Homer,\" and Edith Durham, the \"Albanian Mountain Queen\": Observers of Albania's Road to Statehood|editor1-last=Boeckh|editor1-first=Katrin|editor2-last=Rutar|editor2-first=Sabine|title=The Balkan Wars from Contemporary Perception to Historic Memory|year=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319446424|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aIXgDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Balkan+Wars+from+Contemporary+Perception+to+Historic+Memory#v=onepage&q=Montenegrin%20army%20balkan%20wars%20albanians&f=false|pages=96|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n[[War crimes in Kosovo|In 1998-9]]9, similar war crimes to those comitted in 1912 against the Albanian population would occur.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Booth |first1=Ken |title=The Kosovo Tragedy: The Human Rights Dimensions |date=2012 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-136-33476-4 |page=106 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=e4MsBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA73&dq=#v=onepage&q=1912&f=false |accessdate=8 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThese events have greatly contributed to the growth of the Serbian-Albanian conflict.<ref>[http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1914_1.html Dimitrije Tucovi\u0107: Serbien und Albanien: ein kritischer Beitrag zur Unterdr\u00fcckungspolitik der serbischen Bourgeoisie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617232534/http://www.albanianhistory.net/texts20_1/AH1914_1.html |date=17 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Albania's Golgotha]]''\n* [[Albania during the Balkan Wars]]\n* [[Albanophobia]]\n* [[Attacks on Serbs during the Serbian\u2013Ottoman War (1876\u201378)]]\n* [[Expulsion of the Albanians 1877\u20131878]]\n* [[1901 massacres of Serbs]]\n* [[War crimes in the Kosovo War|War crimes in the Kosovo War (1999)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.org/details/reportofinternat00inteuoft Report of the International Commission to Inquire into the Causes and Conduct of the Balkan War]\n*{{cite book|last1=Tucovi\u0107|first1=Dimitrije|title=Srbija i Arbanija. Jedan prilog kritici zavojeva\u010dke politike srpske bur\u017eoazije|date=1946 |publisher=Kultura|location=Beograd \u2013 Zagreb|url=https://vdocuments.mx/dimitrije-tucovic-srbija-i-albanija.html}}\n\n[[Category:1912 in Albania]]\n[[Category:1913 in Albania]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Serbia|Albanians in the Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Albania|Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:20th century in Albania]]\n[[Category:20th century in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Serbian war crimes in the Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Anti-Albanian sentiment]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Kosovo|Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Massacres in the Ottoman Empire|Albanians in the Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1912]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1913]]\n[[Category:1912 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:1913 murders in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: comitted \u2192 committed, devestated \u2192 devastated, targetted \u2192 targeted, tounges \u2192 tongues, 1912-13 \u2192 1912\u201313", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massacres_of_Albanians_in_the_Balkan_Wars"}
{"title_page": "Desi Boyz", "text_new": "{{short description|2011 Indian Hindi-language romantic comedy film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Desi Boyz\n| image          = 11nov desiboyz-poster01.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Rohit Dhawan\n| producer       = [[Krishika Lulla]]<br />Vijay Ahuja<br />Jyoti Deshpande\n| writer         = '''Dialogue:-'''<br />Renuka Kunzru<br /><small>'''Additional Screenplay:-'''</small><br />[[Milap Zaveri]]\n| screenplay     = Rohit Dhawan\n| story          = Rohit Dhawan\n| based on       = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} -->\n| starring       = [[Akshay Kumar]]<br />[[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]]<br />[[Deepika Padukone]]<br />[[Chitrangada Singh]]<br />[[Anupam Kher]]<br />[[Sanjay Dutt]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br />[[Pritam]]<br />'''Background Score:'''<br />[[Sandeep Shirodkar]]\n| cinematography = [[Natarajan Subramaniam]]\n| editing        = Nitin Madhukar\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[Eros International]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2011|11|25|}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}}65 crore<ref>{{cite web|title=Desi Boyz collect Rs 9 crs at Box office on first day  |url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/box-office/2011/desi-boyz-first-day-collection-box-office-report-271111.html|accessdate=3 July 2013|date=27 November 2011}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{INR}}77 crore<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 Worldwide Figures: Twenty Films Cross 50 Crore |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3944&nCat= |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=3 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215132739/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3944&nCat= |archivedate=15 February 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Desi Boyz''''' is a 2011 Indian [[romantic comedy]] film<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/bollywood-delivers-the-desi-boyz-1.431008 |title=Bollywood delivers the Desi Boyz |last=Johnson |first=Alice |date=24 November 2011 |publisher=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)]]}}</ref> directed by debutant Rohit Dhawan, son of director [[David Dhawan]]. The film stars [[Akshay Kumar]], [[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]], [[Deepika Padukone]] and [[Chitrangada Singh]] in lead roles<ref>{{cite web|last=Sahgal|first=Geety|title=Desi Boyz takes off in Mumbai|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/Desi-Boyz-takes-off-in-Mumbai/712576/|accessdate=11 December 2010}}</ref> while [[Sanjay Dutt]] features in an extended cameo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Dutt to feature in a cameo as Mr. Desi Boyz in Desi Boyz and |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2011/10/04/16420/|accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> The film was released on 25 November 2011, and received a mixed response from critics though it had a decent run at the box office.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story follows two friends and roommates, the Gujarati rebel Jignesh 'Jerry' Patel ([[Akshay Kumar]]) and clean simpleton Nikhil 'Nick' Mathur ([[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]]), who live in London. Jerry does odd jobs for a living as he is an undergraduate but Nick has a white-collar job. However, both find themselves jobless due to the economic downturn. Jerry has a school-age nephew named Veer (Master Virej Desai) whom he looks after, as the child has lost his parents. Nick intends to marry his girlfriend, Radhika Awasthi ([[Deepika Padukone]]), who dreams of a lovely wedding, a great honeymoon and a wonderful house to live in after marriage.\n\nOut of a job, Jerry finds it difficult to even pay the school fees of his nephew because of which the government is on the verge of giving the custody of his nephew to a foster family. Nick fears he won't be able to fulfill the dreams of his to-be wife. It is to tide over the difficult times that Jerry and Nick turn to the oldest profession in the world. Jerry and Nick become male escorts for the company \"Desi Boyz\", fulfilling the fantasies of girls and ladies. Nonetheless, Jerry is unable to prevent his nephew from being sent to a foster home; and Nick loses Radhika when she learns of what he has been up to while she is away in India. Frustrated, Nick blames Jerry for forcing him into the profession and asks him to move out of his house and life.\n\nNick now tries to win Radhika back and help comes from the most unlikely source \u2013 Radhika's father Suresh ([[Anupam Kher]]) who has come to London with her. Meanwhile, Jerry registers in college again to complete his graduation so that he can earn enough money to get his nephew back home. In college, Jerry meets Tanya Sharma ([[Chitrangada Singh]]) who used to be his classmate and is now a professor at the same college. Sparks fly between Jerry and Tanya. To make Nick jealous, Radhika dates a man named Ajay ([[Omi Vaidya]]). Nick starts to pick on Ajay, often calling him Vijay intentionally. After some reconsideration, Radhika forgives Nick, but Nick rejects her after she disapproves of Jerry. Meanwhile, Jerry graduates college and also wins Tanya's heart. Nick comes and apologizes to Jerry. All is forgiven when Nick and Jerry reconcile. Jerry then helps Radhika win back Nick.\n\nNick then helps Jerry get a high paying job, and Jerry decides to go to court and get back the custody of his nephew. Ajay turns out to be the lawyer against Jerry's case. He decides to get revenge on Nick by not letting Jerry win his case. Ajay tells the court about Jerry being a male escort and what a bad role model he would be to his nephew, bringing in 3 witnesses to testify against Jerry. He asks each of them if they had paid Jerry for sex, but only one says yes. Ajay is on the verge of winning, but Mr. Desi Boyz comes into the courtroom and influences the judge. Then, Jerry makes an inspiring speech to the judge. He ends up winning the case and gaining full custody of Veer. The economy improves and everyone is happy in the end. In a short ending scene, a newspaper article is shown, that states the recession will strike back, then Mr. Desi Boyz gives a call and says that he has gotten the license for a branch in Mumbai.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Akshay Kumar]] as Jignesh 'Jerry' Patel (Rocco)\n* [[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]] as Nikhil 'Nick' Mathur (Hunter)\n* [[Sanjay Dutt]] as Mr. Khalnayak\n* [[Deepika Padukone]] as Radhika Awasthi\n* [[Chitrangada Singh]] as Tanya Sharma\n* [[Master Virej Desai]] as Veer Patel\n* [[Anupam Kher]] as Suresh Awasthi, Radhika's father\n* [[Omi Vaidya]] as Ajay Bapat\n* [[Mohnish Bahl]] as Social Worker\n* [[Shraman Jain]] as Rohan, Jerry's Friend\n* [[Bharati Achrekar]] as Jerry's mother\n* [[Satish Kaushik]] as Mr. Dhillon\n* [[Ashwin Mushran]] as Defence Lawyer\n* [[Bruna Abdullah]] in a Special Appearance in song \"Subha Hone Na De\"\n* [[Larissa Bonesi]] in a Special Appearance in song \"Subha Hone Na De\"\n\n==Inspiration==\n''Desi Boyz'' was reported to be inspired by the aftermath of thousands of Indian students being duped by various universities in the West such as Tri Valley University, Herguan University, London Metropolitan University and University of Navarra.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tuteja|first=Joginder|title=\"'Desi Boyz' is a 'Dramady' with a lot of 'Soul'\" - Akshay|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/74018.html|accessdate=17 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Yount|first=Stacey|title=More on Desi Boyz|url=http://bollyspice.com/31795/more-on-desi-boyz|accessdate=17 November 2011|date=6 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Varma|first=Lipika|title=I have got all that I wanted, says Akshay Kumar|url=http://www.emirates247.com/bollywood/take-one/i-have-got-all-that-i-wanted-says-akshay-kumar-2011-11-17-1.428712|accessdate=17 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Plagiarism==\nThe basic plot and even some of the scenes of the movie have been lifted from various [[Adam Sandler]] movies like ''[[Reign Over Me]]'', ''[[Billy Madison]]'' and ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/11031-movie-review-karan-a-on-why-desi-boyz-is-the-best-of-the-worst-but-still-only-gets-2-stars.html|title=Movie Review: Karan A on Why Desi Boyz Is the Best of the Worst But Still Only Gets 2 Stars|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n''Desi Boyz'' started filming on 7 November 2010,<ref>{{cite web|title=Desi Boyz Starring Deepika Padukone, Akshay Kumar Begins Production|url=http://www.sawfnews.com/Bollywood/65670.aspx|accessdate=15 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101110123500/http://www.sawfnews.com/Bollywood/65670.aspx|archive-date=10 November 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> and completed shooting in May 2011. The film was to feature [[Sonam Kapoor]] as the lead actress,<ref>{{cite news|last=Lalwani|first=Vickey|title=Sonam, Deepika patch up|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-24/news-interviews/28269215_1_ranbir-and-deepika-deepika-padukone-ranbir-kapoor|accessdate=15 September 2011|work=The Times Of India|date=24 October 2010}}</ref> but she declined the film. There were also rumours of the film being offered to [[Anushka Sharma]], but she denied this.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anushka Sharma tempted by DESI BOYZ?|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/10/jul/12-anushka-sharma-tempted-by-desi-boyz-071014.asp|accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=I'm not starring in 'Desi Boyz': Anushka|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-04/news-interviews/28253496_1_anushka-sharma-directorial-debut-deepika-padukone|accessdate=15 September 2011 | work=The Times Of India|date=4 December 2010}}</ref> Eventually, [[Deepika Padukone]] and [[Chitrangada Singh]] were finalised as the female leads. This marks the collaboration of Kumar and Abraham after ''[[Garam Masala (2005 film)|Garam Masala]]''. Padukone was seen opposite [[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]] for the first time and Singh starred opposite [[Akshay Kumar]] in her first commercial venture.<ref>{{cite web|title='Desi Boyz' to cast together Akshay Kumar and John Abraham|url=http://cool-mediaworld.blogspot.com/2011/03/desi-boyz-to-cast-together-akshay-kumar.html|accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Akshay, Deepika, John- Desi Boyz|url=https://www.imdb.com/news/ni5461710/|accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chitrangada Singh Debuts Dancing in Desi Boyz|url=http://bolly.sawfnews.com/Film.aspx?id=671|accessdate=15 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915010112/http://bolly.sawfnews.com/Film.aspx?id=671|archive-date=15 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter short on extras for a scene at [[Oxford University]], the film used website StarNow.com to recruit extras for filming.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bollywood film to be shot in London soon|url=http://www.starnow.co.uk/Casting-Calls/Actors-wanted/Feature-film/bollywood_film_to_be_shot_in_london_soon.htm|accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref> The first theatrical trailer was released on 23 September 2011, alongside ''[[Mausam (2011 film)|Mausam]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title='Desi Boyz' to arrive with 'Mausam'|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/71059.html|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> whilst the second trailer was released alongside ''[[Ra.One]]'' on 26 October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=DESI BOYZ's second full theatrical trailer to release with RA.ONE|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/11/oct/24-desi-boyzs-second-theatrical-trailer-to-release-with-raone-101108.asp|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Desi Boyz'' got an [[U/A certificate|'A' certificate]] from [[Central Board of Film Certification]], although the makers were expecting a [[U/A certificate]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-19/news-interviews/30419412_1_film-industry-adult-certificate-dirty-picture | title=Dirty Picture passed with no cuts, Desi Boyz for adults only | publisher=[[The Times of India]] | accessdate=22 November 2011 | date=19 November 2011}}</ref> The movie released in the United States on 23 November 2011 for the Thanksgiving Holiday weekend<ref>{{cite web |title=Desi Boyz - USA release |url=http://boxofficereport.net/desi-boyz-set-for-huge-opening// |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125111022/http://boxofficereport.net/desi-boyz-set-for-huge-opening/ |archivedate=25 November 2011  }}</ref> and released in India two days later on 25 November 2011.\n\n==Reception==\nTaran Adarsh gave the film 2 stars, owing to the \"tedious and least compelling second hour\". However, he praised the chemistry of the lead actors, commenting that \"the camaraderie between Akshay and John is piping hot\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Adarsh|first=Taran|title=Desi Boyz : Movie Review by Taran Adarsh|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/review/14319/index.html|accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> Raja Sen of Rediff.com gave 1.5 stars calling it a disaster. Aniruddha Guha gave the film 2 stars, and called it \"more than tolerable\", despite recalling that \"the film did make [him] laugh out loud about twice.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Guha|first=Aniruddha|title=Aniruddha Guha reviews Desi Boyz|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/review_aniruddha-guha-reviews-desi-boyz_1617105|accessdate=25 November 2011|date=25 November 2011}}</ref> Subhash K. Jha gave the film 3.5 out of 5 Stars calling \"highly entertaining sex comedy movie having Smart, sassy, sexy and sparkling with dark audacious humour\".<ref>{{cite web|title='Desi Boyz' Movie Reviews : highly entertaining sex comedy|url=http://news.worldsnap.com/entertainment/movie-review/desi-boyz-movie-reviews-user-reviews-viewer-views-113529.html|accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> The film mainly received positive reviews from the Times of India gave a verdict of \"Good\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-25/news-interviews/30440319_1_desi-boyz-rohit-dhawan-akshay-kumar | work=The Times Of India | title=Desi Boyz: Movie Review | date=25 November 2011}}</ref> Indiaglitz gave it 4 stars.<ref>Joginder Tuteja, [http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/review/13398.html \"Desi Boyz - Yes, these boys deserve to make some noise\"], IndiaGlitz, 25 November 2011.</ref> Glamsham gave it 3 stars.<ref>Martin D'Souza, [http://glamsham.com/movies/reviews/25-desi-boyz-movie-review-111105.asp \"Desi Boyz Review\"], Glamsham.com, 25 November 2011.</ref> Sify gave it 3 stars as well.<ref>Sonia Chopra, [http://www.sify.com/movies/desi-boyz-review-from-getting-laid-off-to-getting-laid-review-bollywood-14984162.html \"Desi Boyz review: From getting laid off to getting laid\"], Sify Movies.</ref> Komal Nahta also gave it {{frac|3|1|2}} stars.<ref>Komal Nahta, [http://www.koimoi.com/reviews/desi-boyz-review/ \"Desi Boyz Review\"], Koimoi.com, 25 November 2011.</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Desi Boyz'' had an above average opening of Rs 275&nbsp;million domestically in its opening weekend. It showed a 20% increase on Saturday, bringing the two-day total to Rs. 180&nbsp;million net. The film grossed approximately INR 280&nbsp;million by the end of the weekend and INR 380&nbsp;million net by the end of its first week. It raked in INR 342.5&nbsp;million in its second week taking the total to INR 460&nbsp;million, it collected a total of INR 540 million in India and INR 770&nbsp;million worldwide. Desi Boyz was overall declared \"Average\". Its box office collections were much lower than expected because it surprisingly got an [[U/A certificate|'A' certificate]] from [[Central Board of Film Certification]].<ref name=\"gross\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3944&nCat= |title=2011 Worldwide Figures: Twenty Films Cross 50 Crore |publisher=boxofficeindia |date=20 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419150736/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3944&nCat= |archivedate=19 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Desi Boyz\n| type         = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist       = [[Pritam Chakraborty]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 19 September 2011\n| recorded     = 2010-11\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Film soundtrack]]\n| length       = {{Duration|m=47|s=40}}\n| label        = [[Super Cassettes Industries T-Series|T-Series]]<br />[[Eros International|Eros Music]]\n| producer     = [[Pritam Chakraborty]]\n| prev_title   = [[Tell Me O Kkhuda]]\n| prev_year    = 2011\n| next_title   = [[Players (2012 film)|Players]]\n| next_year    = 2012\n}}\nThe film's songs are composed by [[Pritam Chakraborty]] and lyrics are penned by [[Irshad Kamil]], [[Kumaar]], [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]] & [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://itwofs.com/milliblog/2011/10/21/desi-boyz-music-review-hindi-pritam/ | title=desi-boyz-music-review | publisher=itwofs.com | accessdate=2 November 2011}}</ref> [[Bohemia (musician)|Bohemia]] raps to set the scene for [[Sanjay Dutt]]'s cameo as he walks in the courtroom.\n\nThe [[film score]] is composed by [[Sandeep Shirodkar]].\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = {{Duration|m=47|s=40}}\n| title1 = Make Some Noise For The Desi Boyz\n| extra1 = [[Krishnakumar Kunnath|KK]], Bob\n| lyrics1 = [[Kumaar]]\n| length1 = 4:06\n| title2 = Subha Hone Na De\n| extra2 = [[Mika Singh]], [[Bohemia (musician)|Bohemia]], [[Shefali Alvares]] [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]] added Lines\n| lyrics2 = [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]]\n| length2 = 4:48\n| title3 = Jhak Maar Ke\n| extra3 = [[Neeraj Shridhar]], [[Harshdeep Kaur]]\n| lyrics3 = [[Irshad Kamil]]\n| length3 = 3:53\n| title4 = Allah Maaf Kare\n| extra4 = [[Sonu Nigam]], [[Shilpa Rao]]\n| lyrics4 = Irshad Kamil\n| length4 = 3:51\n| title5 = Let It Be\n| extra5 = [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]]\n| lyrics5 = [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]]\n| length5 = 4:13\n| title6 = Tu Mera Hero (Subha Hone Na De)\n| extra6 = [[Mika Singh]], [[Shefali Alvares]], [[Bohemia (musician)|Bohemia]]\n| lyrics6 = Kumaar\n| length6 = 4:52\n| title7 = Allah Maaf Kare (Remix)\n| extra7 = [[Sonu Nigam]], [[Shilpa Rao]]\n| lyrics7 = Irshad Kamil\n| length7 = 4:41\n| title8 = Jhak Maar Ke (Remix)\n| extra8 = [[Neeraj Shridhar]], [[Harshdeep Kaur]]\n| lyrics8 = Irshad Kamil\n| length8 = 3:03\n| title9 = Subha Hone Na De (Remix)\n| extra9 = [[Mika Singh]], [[Shefali Alvares]], [[Bohemia (musician)|Bohemia]]\n| lyrics9 = Kumaar\n| length9 = 4:59\n| title10 = Make Some Noise For The Desi Boyz (Remix)\n| lyrics10 = Kumaar\n| extra10 = [[Krishnakumar Kunnath|KK]], Bob\n| length10 = 4:32\n| all_writing = \n}}\n\n===Reception===\nThe music album of ''Desi Boyz'' received positive reviews. Joginder Tuteja of [[Bollywood Hungama]] gave the album 4 stars, saying \"Music of Desi Boyz exceeds expectations\" and described the album as \"one of the better 'masala' albums of the year.\" Furthermore, he chose ''Subha Hone Na De'', ''Allah Maaf Kare'', ''Make Some Noise For The Desi Boyz'' and ''Jhak Maar Ke'' as favorite picks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tuteja|first=Joginder|title=Desi Boyz: Music Review by Joginder Tuteja|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/musicreview/14319/index.html|accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nGlamsham gave the music a rating of 4 out of 5 saying, \"Pritam builds up a good tempo in ''Make Some Noise For The Desi Boyz'' and carries the fun promisingly with ''Jhak Maar Ke'' and ''Tu Mera Hero'' with an all-together new breed and genre of music.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.glamsham.com/music/reviews/31-desiboyz-music-review-101101.asp | title=Music Review : Desi Boyz | publisher=Glamsham | accessdate=22 November 2011 | author=Satyajit}}</ref>\n\nThe official video of ''Subha Hone Na De'' has reached over 130 million views on [[YouTube]] as of May 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Bollywoodhungama|14319}}\n*{{IMDb title|1985981}}\n*{{Mojo title|desiboyz}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|desi_boyz}}\n*{{metacritic film|id=desi-boyz}}\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring songs by Pritam]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:2011 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2011 Indian Hindi-language romantic comedy film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Desi Boyz\n| image          = 11nov desiboyz-poster01.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Rohit Dhawan\n| producer       = [[Krishika Lulla]]<br />Vijay Ahuja<br />Jyoti Deshpande\n| writer         = '''Dialogue:-'''<br />Renuka Kunzru<br /><small>'''Additional Screenplay:-'''</small><br />[[Milap Zaveri]]\n| screenplay     = Rohit Dhawan\n| story          = Rohit Dhawan\n| based on       = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} -->\n| starring       = [[Akshay Kumar]]<br />[[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]]<br />[[Deepika Padukone]]<br />[[Chitrangada Singh]]<br />[[Anupam Kher]]<br />[[Sanjay Dutt]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br />[[Pritam]]<br />'''Background Score:'''<br />[[Sandeep Shirodkar]]\n| cinematography = [[Natarajan Subramaniam]]\n| editing        = Nitin Madhukar\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[Eros International]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2011|11|25|}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}}65 crore<ref>{{cite web|title=Desi Boyz collect Rs 9 crs at Box office on first day  |url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/box-office/2011/desi-boyz-first-day-collection-box-office-report-271111.html|accessdate=3 July 2013|date=27 November 2011}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{INR}}77 crore<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 Worldwide Figures: Twenty Films Cross 50 Crore |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3944&nCat= |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=3 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215132739/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3944&nCat= |archivedate=15 February 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Desi Boyz''''' is a 2011 Indian [[romantic comedy]] film<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/bollywood-delivers-the-desi-boyz-1.431008 |title=Bollywood delivers the Desi Boyz |last=Johnson |first=Alice |date=24 November 2011 |publisher=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)]]}}</ref> directed by debutant Rohit Dhawan, son of director [[David Dhawan]]. The film stars [[Akshay Kumar]], [[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]], [[Deepika Padukone]] and [[Chitrangada Singh]] in lead roles<ref>{{cite web|last=Sahgal|first=Geety|title=Desi Boyz takes off in Mumbai|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/Desi-Boyz-takes-off-in-Mumbai/712576/|accessdate=11 December 2010}}</ref> while [[Sanjay Dutt]] features in an extended cameo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanjay Dutt to feature in a cameo as Mr. Desi Boyz in Desi Boyz and |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2011/10/04/16420/|accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> The film was released on 25 November 2011, and received a mixed response from critics though it had a decent run at the box office.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story follows two friends and roommates, the Gujarati rebel Jignesh 'Jerry' Patel ([[Akshay Kumar]]) and clean simpleton Nikhil 'Nick' Mathur ([[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]]), who live in London. Jerry does odd jobs for a living as he is an undergraduate but Nick has a white-collar job. However, both find themselves jobless due to the economic downturn. Jerry has a school-age nephew named Veer (Master Virej Desai) whom he looks after, as the child has lost his parents. Nick intends to marry his girlfriend, Radhika Awasthi ([[Deepika Padukone]]), who dreams of a lovely wedding, a great honeymoon and a wonderful house to live in after marriage.\n\nOut of a job, Jerry finds it difficult to even pay the school fees of his nephew because of which the government is on the verge of giving the custody of his nephew to a foster family. Nick fears he won\u2019t be able to fulfill the dreams of his to-be wife. It is to tide over the difficult times that Jerry and Nick turn to the oldest profession in the world. Jerry and Nick become male escorts for the company \"Desi Boyz\", fulfilling the fantasies of girls and ladies. Nonetheless, Jerry is unable to prevent his nephew from being sent to a foster home; and Nick loses Radhika when she learns of what he has been up to while she is away in India. Frustrated, Nick blames Jerry for forcing him into the profession and asks him to move out of his house and life.\n\nNick now tries to win Radhika back and help comes from the most unlikely source \u2013 Radhika\u2019s father Suresh ([[Anupam Kher]]) who has come to London with her. Meanwhile, Jerry registers in college again to complete his graduation so that he can earn enough money to get his nephew back home. In college, Jerry meets Tanya Sharma ([[Chitrangada Singh]]) who used to be his classmate and is now a professor at the same college. Sparks fly between Jerry and Tanya. To make Nick jealous, Radhika dates a man named Ajay ([[Omi Vaidya]]). Nick starts to pick on Ajay, often calling him Vijay intentionally. After some reconsideration, Radhika forgives Nick, but Nick rejects her after she disapproves of Jerry. Meanwhile, Jerry graduates college and also wins Tanya's heart. Nick comes and apologizes to Jerry. All is forgiven when Nick and Jerry reconcile. Jerry then helps Radhika win back Nick.\n\nNick then helps Jerry get a high paying job, and Jerry decides to go to court and get back the custody of his nephew. Ajay turns out to be the lawyer against Jerry's case. He decides to get revenge on Nick by not letting Jerry win his case. Ajay tells the court about Jerry being a male escort and what a bad role model he would be to his nephew, bringing in 3 witnesses to testify against Jerry. He asks each of them if they had paid Jerry for sex, but only one says yes. Ajay is on the verge of winning, but Mr. Desi Boyz comes into the courtroom and influences the judge. Then, Jerry makes an inspiring speech to the judge. He ends up winning the case and gaining full custody of Veer. The economy improves and everyone is happy in the end. In a short ending scene, a newspaper article is shown, that states the recession will strike back, then Mr. Desi Boyz gives a call and says that he has gotten the license for a branch in Mumbai.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Akshay Kumar]] as Jignesh 'Jerry' Patel (Rocco)\n* [[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]] as Nikhil 'Nick' Mathur (Hunter)\n* [[Sanjay Dutt]] as Mr. Khalnayak\n* [[Deepika Padukone]] as Radhika Awasthi\n* [[Chitrangada Singh]] as Tanya Sharma\n* [[Master Virej Desai]] as Veer Patel\n* [[Anupam Kher]] as Suresh Awasthi, Radhika's father\n* [[Omi Vaidya]] as Ajay Bapat\n* [[Mohnish Bahl]] as Social Worker\n* [[Shraman Jain]] as Rohan, Jerry's Friend\n* [[Bharati Achrekar]] as Jerry's mother\n* [[Satish Kaushik]] as Mr. Dhillon\n* [[Ashwin Mushran]] as Defence Lawyer\n* [[Bruna Abdullah]] in a Special Appearance in song \"Subha Hone Na De\"\n* [[Larissa Bonesi]] in a Special Appearance in song \"Subha Hone Na De\"\n\n==Inspiration==\n''Desi Boyz'' was reported to be inspired by the aftermath of thousands of Indian students being duped by [http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/waiting-to-happen-a-hundred-trivalleys/article3817234.ece various universities in the West] such as Tri Valley University, Herguan University, London Metropolitan University and University of Navarra.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tuteja|first=Joginder|title=\"'Desi Boyz' is a 'Dramady' with a lot of 'Soul'\" - Akshay|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/74018.html|accessdate=17 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Yount|first=Stacey|title=More on Desi Boyz|url=http://bollyspice.com/31795/more-on-desi-boyz|accessdate=17 November 2011|date=6 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Varma|first=Lipika|title=I have got all that I wanted, says Akshay Kumar|url=http://www.emirates247.com/bollywood/take-one/i-have-got-all-that-i-wanted-says-akshay-kumar-2011-11-17-1.428712|accessdate=17 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Plagiarism==\nThe basic plot and even some of the scenes of the movie have been lifted from various [[Adam Sandler]] movies like ''[[Reign Over Me]]'', ''[[Billy Madison]]'' and ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/11031-movie-review-karan-a-on-why-desi-boyz-is-the-best-of-the-worst-but-still-only-gets-2-stars.html|title=Movie Review: Karan A on Why Desi Boyz Is the Best of the Worst But Still Only Gets 2 Stars|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n''Desi Boyz'' started filming on 7 November 2010,<ref>{{cite web|title=Desi Boyz Starring Deepika Padukone, Akshay Kumar Begins Production|url=http://www.sawfnews.com/Bollywood/65670.aspx|accessdate=15 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101110123500/http://www.sawfnews.com/Bollywood/65670.aspx|archive-date=10 November 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> and completed shooting in May 2011. The film was to feature [[Sonam Kapoor]] as the lead actress,<ref>{{cite news|last=Lalwani|first=Vickey|title=Sonam, Deepika patch up|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-24/news-interviews/28269215_1_ranbir-and-deepika-deepika-padukone-ranbir-kapoor|accessdate=15 September 2011|work=The Times Of India|date=24 October 2010}}</ref> but she declined the film. There were also rumours of the film being offered to [[Anushka Sharma]], but she denied this.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anushka Sharma tempted by DESI BOYZ?|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/10/jul/12-anushka-sharma-tempted-by-desi-boyz-071014.asp|accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=I'm not starring in 'Desi Boyz': Anushka|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-04/news-interviews/28253496_1_anushka-sharma-directorial-debut-deepika-padukone|accessdate=15 September 2011 | work=The Times Of India|date=4 December 2010}}</ref> Eventually, [[Deepika Padukone]] and [[Chitrangada Singh]] were finalised as the female leads. This marks the collaboration of Kumar and Abraham after ''[[Garam Masala (2005 film)|Garam Masala]]''. Padukone was seen opposite [[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]] for the first time and Singh starred opposite [[Akshay Kumar]] in her first commercial venture.<ref>{{cite web|title='Desi Boyz' to cast together Akshay Kumar and John Abraham|url=http://cool-mediaworld.blogspot.com/2011/03/desi-boyz-to-cast-together-akshay-kumar.html|accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Akshay, Deepika, John- Desi Boyz|url=https://www.imdb.com/news/ni5461710/|accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chitrangada Singh Debuts Dancing in Desi Boyz|url=http://bolly.sawfnews.com/Film.aspx?id=671|accessdate=15 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915010112/http://bolly.sawfnews.com/Film.aspx?id=671|archive-date=15 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter short on extras for a scene at [[Oxford University]], the film used website StarNow.com to recruit extras for filming.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bollywood film to be shot in London soon|url=http://www.starnow.co.uk/Casting-Calls/Actors-wanted/Feature-film/bollywood_film_to_be_shot_in_london_soon.htm|accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref> The first theatrical trailer was released on 23 September 2011, alongside ''[[Mausam (2011 film)|Mausam]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title='Desi Boyz' to arrive with 'Mausam'|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/71059.html|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> whilst the second trailer was released alongside ''[[Ra.One]]'' on 26 October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=DESI BOYZ's second full theatrical trailer to release with RA.ONE|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/11/oct/24-desi-boyzs-second-theatrical-trailer-to-release-with-raone-101108.asp|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Desi Boyz'' got an [[U/A certificate|'A' certificate]] from [[Central Board of Film Certification]], although the makers were expecting a [[U/A certificate]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-19/news-interviews/30419412_1_film-industry-adult-certificate-dirty-picture | title=Dirty Picture passed with no cuts, Desi Boyz for adults only | publisher=[[The Times of India]] | accessdate=22 November 2011 | date=19 November 2011}}</ref> The movie released in the United States on 23 November 2011 for the Thanksgiving Holiday weekend<ref>{{cite web |title=Desi Boyz - USA release |url=http://boxofficereport.net/desi-boyz-set-for-huge-opening// |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125111022/http://boxofficereport.net/desi-boyz-set-for-huge-opening/ |archivedate=25 November 2011  }}</ref> and released in India two days later on 25 November 2011.\n\n==Reception==\nTaran Adarsh gave the film 2 stars, owing to the \"tedious and least compelling second hour\". However, he praised the chemistry of the lead actors, commenting that \"the camaraderie between Akshay and John is piping hot\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Adarsh|first=Taran|title=Desi Boyz : Movie Review by Taran Adarsh|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/review/14319/index.html|accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> Raja Sen of Rediff.com gave 1.5 stars calling it a disaster. Aniruddha Guha gave the film 2 stars, and called it \"more than tolerable\", despite recalling that \"the film did make [him] laugh out loud about twice.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Guha|first=Aniruddha|title=Aniruddha Guha reviews Desi Boyz|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/review_aniruddha-guha-reviews-desi-boyz_1617105|accessdate=25 November 2011|date=25 November 2011}}</ref> Subhash K. Jha gave the film 3.5 out of 5 Stars calling \"highly entertaining sex comedy movie having Smart, sassy, sexy and sparkling with dark audacious humour\".<ref>{{cite web|title='Desi Boyz' Movie Reviews : highly entertaining sex comedy|url=http://news.worldsnap.com/entertainment/movie-review/desi-boyz-movie-reviews-user-reviews-viewer-views-113529.html|accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>  The film mainly received positive reviews from the Times of India gave a verdict of \"Good\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-25/news-interviews/30440319_1_desi-boyz-rohit-dhawan-akshay-kumar | work=The Times Of India | title=Desi Boyz: Movie Review | date=25 November 2011}}</ref> Indiaglitz gave it 4 stars.<ref>Joginder Tuteja, [http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/review/13398.html \"Desi Boyz - Yes, these boys deserve to make some noise\"], IndiaGlitz, 25 November 2011.</ref> Glamsham gave it 3 stars.<ref>Martin D'Souza, [http://glamsham.com/movies/reviews/25-desi-boyz-movie-review-111105.asp \"Desi Boyz Review\"], Glamsham.com, 25 November 2011.</ref> Sify gave it 3 stars as well.<ref>Sonia Chopra, [http://www.sify.com/movies/desi-boyz-review-from-getting-laid-off-to-getting-laid-review-bollywood-14984162.html \"Desi Boyz review: From getting laid off to getting laid\"], Sify Movies.</ref> Komal Nahta also gave it {{frac|3|1|2}} stars.<ref>Komal Nahta, [http://www.koimoi.com/reviews/desi-boyz-review/ \"Desi Boyz Review\"], Koimoi.com, 25 November 2011.</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Desi Boyz'' had an above average opening of Rs 275&nbsp;million domestically in its opening weekend. It showed a 20% increase on Saturday, bringing the two-day total to Rs. 180&nbsp;million net. The film grossed approximately INR 280&nbsp;million by the end of the weekend and INR 380&nbsp;million net by the end of its first week. It raked in INR 342.5&nbsp;million in its second week taking the total to INR 460&nbsp;million, it collected a total of INR 540 million in India and INR 770 million worldwide. Desi Boyz was overall declared \"Average\". Its box office collections were much lower than expected because it surprisingly got an [[U/A certificate|'A' certificate]] from [[Central Board of Film Certification]].<ref name=\"gross\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3944&nCat= |title=2011 Worldwide Figures: Twenty Films Cross 50 Crore |publisher=boxofficeindia |date=20 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419150736/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3944&nCat= |archivedate=19 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Desi Boyz\n| type         = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist       = [[Pritam Chakraborty]]\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 19 September 2011\n| recorded     = 2010-11\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Film soundtrack]]\n| length       = {{Duration|m=47|s=40}}\n| label        = [[Super Cassettes Industries T-Series|T-Series]]<br />[[Eros International|Eros Music]]\n| producer     = [[Pritam Chakraborty]]\n| prev_title   = [[Tell Me O Kkhuda]]\n| prev_year    = 2011\n| next_title   = [[Players (2012 film)|Players]]\n| next_year    = 2012\n}}\nThe film's songs are composed by [[Pritam Chakraborty]] and lyrics are penned by [[Irshad Kamil]], [[Kumaar]], [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]] & [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://itwofs.com/milliblog/2011/10/21/desi-boyz-music-review-hindi-pritam/ | title=desi-boyz-music-review | publisher=itwofs.com | accessdate=2 November 2011}}</ref> [[Bohemia (musician)|Bohemia]] raps to set the scene for [[Sanjay Dutt]]'s cameo as he walks in the courtroom.\n\nThe [[film score]] is composed by [[Sandeep Shirodkar]].\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = {{Duration|m=47|s=40}}\n| title1 = Make Some Noise For The Desi Boyz\n| extra1 = [[Krishnakumar Kunnath|KK]], Bob\n| lyrics1 = [[Kumaar]]\n| length1 = 4:06\n| title2 = Subha Hone Na De\n| extra2 = [[Mika Singh]], [[Bohemia (musician)|Bohemia]], [[Shefali Alvares]] [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]] added Lines\n| lyrics2 = [[Yo Yo Honey Singh]]\n| length2 = 4:48\n| title3 = Jhak Maar Ke\n| extra3 = [[Neeraj Shridhar]], [[Harshdeep Kaur]]\n| lyrics3 = [[Irshad Kamil]]\n| length3 = 3:53\n| title4 = Allah Maaf Kare\n| extra4 = [[Sonu Nigam]], [[Shilpa Rao]]\n| lyrics4 = Irshad Kamil\n| length4 = 3:51\n| title5 = Let It Be\n| extra5 = [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]]\n| lyrics5 = [[Amitabh Bhattacharya]]\n| length5 = 4:13\n| title6 = Tu Mera Hero (Subha Hone Na De)\n| extra6 = [[Mika Singh]], [[Shefali Alvares]], [[Bohemia (musician)|Bohemia]]\n| lyrics6 = Kumaar\n| length6 = 4:52\n| title7 = Allah Maaf Kare (Remix)\n| extra7 = [[Sonu Nigam]], [[Shilpa Rao]]\n| lyrics7 = Irshad Kamil\n| length7 = 4:41\n| title8 = Jhak Maar Ke (Remix)\n| extra8 = [[Neeraj Shridhar]], [[Harshdeep Kaur]]\n| lyrics8 = Irshad Kamil\n| length8 = 3:03\n| title9 = Subha Hone Na De (Remix)\n| extra9 = [[Mika Singh]], [[Shefali Alvares]], [[Bohemia (musician)|Bohemia]]\n| lyrics9 = Kumaar\n| length9 = 4:59\n| title10 = Make Some Noise For The Desi Boyz (Remix)\n| lyrics10 = Kumaar\n| extra10 = [[Krishnakumar Kunnath|KK]], Bob\n| length10 = 4:32\n| all_writing = \n}}\n\n===Reception===\nThe music album of ''Desi Boyz'' received positive reviews. Joginder Tuteja of [[Bollywood Hungama]] gave the album 4 stars, saying \"Music of Desi Boyz exceeds expectations\" and described the album as \"one of the better 'masala' albums of the year.\" Furthermore, he chose ''Subha Hone Na De'', ''Allah Maaf Kare'', ''Make Some Noise For The Desi Boyz'' and ''Jhak Maar Ke'' as favorite picks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tuteja|first=Joginder|title=Desi Boyz: Music Review by Joginder Tuteja|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/musicreview/14319/index.html|accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nGlamsham gave the music a rating of 4 out of 5 saying, \"Pritam builds up a good tempo in ''Make Some Noise For The Desi Boyz'' and carries the fun promisingly with ''Jhak Maar Ke'' and ''Tu Mera Hero'' with an all-together new breed and genre of music.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.glamsham.com/music/reviews/31-desiboyz-music-review-101101.asp | title=Music Review : Desi Boyz | publisher=Glamsham | accessdate=22 November 2011 | author=Satyajit}}</ref>\n\nThe official [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y7G-tYRzwYY|music video] of ''Subha Hone Na De'' has reached over 130 million views on [[YouTube]] as of May 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Bollywoodhungama|14319}}\n*{{IMDb title|1985981}}\n*{{Mojo title|desiboyz}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|desi_boyz}}\n*{{metacritic film|id=desi-boyz}}\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring songs by Pritam]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:2011 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Fylindfotberserk", "label": "safe", "comment": "Generalformattingbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desi_Boyz"}
